<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RainierDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0700 05-21 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rainier Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mount Rainier Claims Three More Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with identities of bodies confirmed
and CORRECT that Kellokoski is from Tahoe-Paradise, Calif. sted
Meyers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers used a helicopter Friday to lift
the bodies of three climbers from the snowy face of Mount Ranier,
bringing the death toll on the mountain described as ``Everest ...
on a minature scale'' to 54 in the last 90 years.
   The three bodies recovered at the 10,000-foot level of the
14,410-foot mountain were identified as those of Craig Loyal
Adkison, 37, of Kirkland; David Kellokoski, 30, of Tahoe-Paradise,
Calif.; and Greg Remmick, 32, of Citrus Heights, Calif., said
Pierce County Coroner's spokesman Stewart Rankin.
   The three, described as experienced climbers, began their trek
May 9 and were supposed to have completed it last Saturday. A
search was begun Tuesday, and the bodies, still roped together,
were spotted from the air Thursday.
   Since 1981, nine people _ including the three latest victims _
have died on the steep and strenuous Liberty Ridge on the north
face of Rainier, a dormant volcano.
   Cy Hentges, Mount Rainier National Park spokesman, said the
ridge's appeal has increased since its inclusion in a 1979 book on
classic North American climbs. Prior to 1981, there were no
reported deaths on the ridge.
   But the entire mountain is something to be reckoned with,
Hentges said.
   ``The American Everest team trained on it,'' Hentges said.
``That should tell you something. It's on a miniature scale, but it
provides anything and everything that Everest does, except it's not
that high.
   ``You can walk up sometimes, roped with proper equipment but in
shorts. But all it takes is one storm to come in _ and this has
happened many times _ to kill people.''
   ``It looks so lovely and so beautiful, and yet it can be a devil
that shows pity on no one,'' he said.
   Hentges said it was likely the Adkison, Kellokoski and Remmick
hit bad weather and unstable fresh snow and fell 2,000 feet to
their deaths in an avalanche.
   Because of continued avalanche danger, the helicopter did not
land near the bodies but snagged the rope still connecting them,
lifted them and flew to a safer spot where they could be loaded and
flown off the mountain.
   Edward Cabelera, owner of an exercise equipment company that
Remmick worked for, said that not long before his friend left on
the climb, ``I asked him why he wasn't going on a guided trip. He
told me he didn't want anybody to hold his hand.
   `` `If I don't make it, that's the way I want to go.' That's the
last thing he told me,'' Cabelera said.
   Ironically, rangers said, the latest deaths will probably
attract more climbers.
   ``News like this tends to bring more people to the mountain
...,'' Chief Park Ranger Bill Jensen said. ``It's a very dangerous,
hazardous route and that's what attracts people _ the thrill of
danger.''
   About 8,000 people attempt to climb Rainier each year, most of
them up the south side, and about half of them make it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
