<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--ForsythMarch     05-21 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Forsyth March,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Gets Eight Years In Prison For Forsyth County Assault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUMMING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white man convicted of assaulting a black
man after a huge civil rights march last year was sentenced to
eight years in prison.
   Superior Court Judge Richard S. Gault on Friday also ordered
Randall Allen Norton, 31, of Toccoa be placed on seven years of
probation for the assault on Dennis Alfredo Edwards of Smyrna.
   Norton was convicted Wednesday of aggravated assault.
   Norton and his brother, Roger Dale Norton, 29, also of Toccoa,
were arrested in July 1987 and charged with hitting Edwards with a
piece of concrete after the January 1987 march. Roger Norton is to
be tried in July.
   District Attorney Rafe Banks III said Edwards has a piece of his
skull missing as a result of the attack.
   The civil rights march, which attracted more than 20,000 people,
was a response to attacks by Ku Klux Klan members and other
bystanders on a smaller march held the week before in virtually
all-white Forsyth County north of Atlanta.
</TEXT>
