<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuffaloRoam     05-21 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buffalo Roam,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escaped Buffalo Roam Free In South Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Angelo Abbate addressed a golf
ball with a nine-iron at Hollywood Lakes Country Club, a herd of 13
buffalo addressed him with wide-eyed stares.
   ``I got kind of scared there for a second,'' said Abbate, 73,
who blames his bogey on the bison.
   Buffalo have roamed Broward and Dade counties for two months
after a horse thief inadvertently freed 250 of them from a ranch.
Since then, they have surprised motorists on Interstate 75, hung
around farmers' fields and even grazed on the greens at golf
courses. Last week, a buffalo died after it was hit by a
tractor-trailer in Dade.
   State troopers and wildlife officers say the buffalo problem is
getting out of hand.
   ``It is just a question of time before someone is going to get
hurt,'' said cattle farmer George Williams. ``What they need to do
is catch them in a steel pen that can hold them once and for all.''
   Officers from the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission
rounded up the bison at the golf course Wednesday and put them
inside a barbed wire fence on Williams' nearby pasture.
   But the free-spirited buffalo broke through the fence Thursday
morning and headed to civilization, clogging rush hour traffic on
Interstate 75 until wildlife officers chased them off the road.
They were moved to another fenced-in field in Broward County, where
they remain.
   The buffalo saga began March 20, when horse thieves cut a hole
in the fence surrounding Chi-O Ranchero in Miami Lakes.
   While the thieves made off with 26 horses, about 250 buffalo
escaped from the 2,000-acre pasture, said Arnold Oper, a Chi-O
stockholder.
   Oper has hired free-lance cowboys to track down the buffalo,
valued at $2,000 each. About 200 of the bison have been rounded up
so far.
   Oper and his partners invested in the buffalo with the hope the
meat would become popular in Florida.
   Wildlife officers charged Oper with a second-degree misdemeanor
of housing wildlife in an unsafe manner and allowing them to
escape, said Jim Huffstodt, the wildlife commission's information
officer.
   Bob Harper, the golf course superintendent at Hollywood Lakes,
said buffalo have twice left tracks on the links during the past
two weeks.
   ``At first nobody believed me when I told them there were
buffalo out there,'' he said. ``The police thought I was crazy. The
farmer out back thought I was crazy. (But) I'm from Kansas. I grew
up around farms and cattle. I know buffalo.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
