<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid Bjt   05-21 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, Bjt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungry Contras Leaving Nicaragua In Search Of Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contra guerrillas are leaving Nicaragua
``at a high rate'' because they are hungry and searching for food
in neighboring Honduras, the head of the U.S. foreign aid program
says.
   The American-supported Contras are moving because they have been
blocked from receiving supplies at their jungle bases in Nicaragua,
said Alan Woods, administrator of the Agency for International
Development.
   Woods told a Senate subcommittee Friday that ``there are people
inside Nicaragua who are desperate ... we've had reports of people
eating tree roots.''
   Woods declined to estimate how many people were involved, but
other administration officials have said that up to 3,000 rebels
have fled into neighboring Honduras in recent weeks to look for
food.
   The administration plans to give cash to the Contras to buy
food, at the rate of $1 per day per rebel, Woods said. The money,
which will be sent in by couriers, will be in the form of cordobas,
the Nicaraguan currency.
   ``We have taken this particular step as a last resort,'' he
said, adding that the United States wants to keep as many Contras
inside Nicaragua as possible.
   The Contras and Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government are in
the middle of peace talks, and keeping the Contras inside the
Central American nation will keep the pressure on Nicaragua, U.S.
officials say.
   A March 23 agreement between the Contras and the Sandinistas
allows humanitarian aid to go to the guerrillas during the peace
talks. But Woods said there has been a dispute over how to
distribute the aid and the impasse has blocked any help from being
sent.
   Direct shipments of food have not begun because the two sides
cannot agree on a neutral distribution organization, a requirement
spelled out by Congress in March when it voted $48 million in
humanitarian aid.
   Woods said the International Red Cross has been rejected by the
Contras as a delivery agency, but he didn't know why.
   ``The simple bottom line ... is that if they'd reach agreement,
we'd start delivering food,'' he said.
   The cash plan is a substitute, he told the Foreign Relations
western hemisphere subcommittee.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the subcommittee,
raised a number of questions about the cash plan.
   Dodd called it ``a pretty weak accounting system'' and suggested
the proposal raises ``serious questions about compliance with
existing legislative restrictions.''
   Woods responded that ``we're doing the best we can under the
circumstances'' to account for the money.
   When Congress approved the humanitarian aid, it barred using any
of the money for weapons. It would be difficult to use the cordobas
to buy guns because the currency is not generally accepted outside
Nicaragua, Woods said.
   Two Republicans on the subcommittee, Sens. Rudy Boschwitz of
Minnesota and Paul Trible of Virginia, praised Woods' efforts.
   Boschwitz said, ``It really is a difficult situation.''
   Trible added, ``It's very easy to criticize, but you're
operating under very difficult circumstances.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
