<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Drugs Bjt   05-21 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Drugs, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide Says Vice President Didn't Follow Up On Early Drug
Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush was told as early
as 1983 of allegations that Panamanian officials were involved in
the drug trade, but did not follow up on them, says Bush's top
foreign policy aide.
   The aide, Donald Gregg, testified in a deposition Friday that
then-Panamanian President Ricardo de la Espriella mentioned the
allegations to the vice president at the close of a December 1983
meeting in Panama, but the Panamanian official also told Bush the
stories were untrue.
   Bush, then chairman of a task force to combat the flow of drugs
into south Florida, ``said he had not been aware (of the charges)
or he would have raised them'' with de la Espriella, Gregg
testified in a deposition for a private civil lawsuit.
   After returning to Washington, ``We did nothing to follow that
up'' Gregg said. ``It was not yet as clear to us as it has
subsequently become, who was involved.''
   The meeting also was attended by Manuel Antonio Noriega, the
general who now is Panama's de facto leader and who was indicted in
Florida in February on drug charges. Bush has said he received no
reliable information connecting Noriega to drugs until the
indictment.
   Gregg also testified that he was aware in 1983 that the
government of Panama had been helpful to the United States in
getting military supplies to Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   The testimony came during a daylong deposition taken for a $24
million suit by the Christic Institute, a liberal policy group,
charging that a list of defendants, some of whom were involved in
the Iran-Contra affair, supplied the Contras with weapons in trade
for cocaine, and conspired in a failed attempt to assassinate a
maverick Contra field commander, Eden Pastora.
   Richard Stearns, Gregg's Justice Department attorney, objected
repeatedly to the questioning, charging that it ranged far from the
subject of the suit and was being done for political purposes.
   ``I think it's quite clear you have some other agenda in mind,''
he told Michael Withey, an attorney for the plaintiffs.
   On Thursday, another Bush aide, Col. Samuel J. Watson, had
invoked executive privilege and declined to answer when asked
during a similar deposition what Bush and the U.S. ambassador to
Panama, Everett Briggs, discussed about narcotics at a meeting on
Dec. 16, 1985.
   When Withey questioned Gregg on Friday about the same meeting,
Gregg agreed to discuss it but said his recollection was not
specific.
   ``I think we came away from the meeting with Ambassador Briggs
with the sense that Noriega was a growing problem _ politically,
militarily and possibly in the drug area,'' Gregg testified. But he
said any drug problems involving Noriega ``were not highlighted''
by Briggs.
   Later in the day, Withey asked Gregg: ``The fact that General
Noriega may have had some involvement in the narcotics problem,
that was coming out of the December '85 meeting at that time, isn't
that correct?''
   Gregg responded: ``It would have been part of the general
picture of Noriega as a political problem, as corruption, and as a
general policy problem, yes.''
   But talking with reporters later, Gregg said he did not recall
any discussion of Noriega's involvement in drug trafficking. ``I am
saying that narcotics as a problem in Panama was part of the agenda
of the meeting. ... There was no discussion of any direct
connection between that and Noriega.''
   Gregg also testified that a State Department briefing paper
would have been prepared for Bush's meeting with Briggs outlining
the background of the ambassador's concerns, and that the paper
would have been placed in Bush's briefing book.
   That document is among papers sought by the plaintiffs in the
suit, but which have not been turned over by the government.
</TEXT>
