<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-21 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Land Bank In Louisville To Get $90 Million In Assistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new government board created to help the
financially troubled Farm Credit System has taken its biggest step
so far by approving $90 million for the Federal Land Bank of
Louisville, Ky.
   Eric P. Thor, chief executive officer of the Farm Credit System
Assistance Board, said Friday the Louisville bank will receive
assistance through the sale of up to $90 million in preferred stock
to the Financial Assistance Corp., which will raise funds for that
investment by selling 15-year bonds.
   The board and corporation were created by last year's
Agricultural Credit Act to help bail out the financially distressed
Farm Credit System, a network of cooperatively owned farm banks and
associations.
   Thor said the Louisville bank, which serves borrowers in Ohio,
Indiana, Kentucky and Tennessee, applied to th board for financial
help in February. He said the board and the bank have ``reached
agreement on a number of steps which will continue to strengthen''
the institution's financial management.
   Although the Louisville bank had presented ``a well-thought-out,
workable plan for financial recovery,'' its stock had dropped to 65
percent of par value and the bank was unable to implement the plan
without federal help, he said.
   ``The bank has made substantial progress in resolving its own
financial problems over the past two years,'' Thor said.
   Programs included an asset-liability management program in 1986
to control interest rate risks and reduce costs, and a market-based
loan pricing system in 1987 to provide competitive rates to
borrowers. Also, he said, the bank ``reduced its non-performing
loans and inventory of acquired property by 30 percent, and
projects a similar reduction this year.''
   Jeanne Kling, a spokeswoman for the board, said the $90 million
for the Louisville bank was ``the first full-blown'' assistance
designated under the new law.
   Earlier this year, the board approved $25 million in ``limited
purpose'' assistance in short-term funding to help the Federal Land
Bank of Jackson, Miss., stay in business. And $20.5 million was
provided to retire stock in six financially troubled production
credit associations in the Omaha, Neb., and Spokane, Wash.,
districts.
   ``But this is the first one that we've done under the general
context of helping the bank'' in general, Ms. Kling said.
   The 1987 law gave the board broad authority to work with
institutions of the Farm Credit System. The board consists of the
secretaries of Agriculture and Treasury, with a third member still
to be confirmed by the Senate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One reason for an upturn in U.S. wheat exports
has been bad weather in Europe and the Soviet Union, says an
Agriculture Department report.
   The adverse weather ``kept competitor production down and import
demand up,'' the department's Economic Research Service said
Friday. As a result, U.S. wheat exports are expected be at their
highest level since 1981.
   ``Rail car shortages have plagued grain shippers since June
1987, but the total distribution system may yet meet domestic and
export commitments,'' the report said.
   The brief report included much information released May 10 when
USDA's new 1988 winter wheat forecast was issued, including
supply-and-demand figures showing that the total wheat carryover on
June 1 for 1988-89 may be around 1.23 billion bushels.
   ``While still equivalent to more than 5{ months of anticipated
use, almost 60 percent (of the June 1 carryover) is expected to be
in Commodity Credit Corp. inventory or the farmer-owned reserve,''
the report said.
   Wheat held by the CCC or under price support loan in the
farmer-owned reserve is effectively locked out of the free market
and doesn't have an impact on price movements.
   The 1988-89 season average market price of wheat is forecast at
$2.89 to $3.20 per bushel, up from $2.55 in 1987-88 and $2.42 in
1986-87, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm-raised catfish production in April
totaled 20.8 million pounds, down 22 percent from a year ago, says
the Agriculture Department.
   The decline helped boost the average price paid to catfish
farmers to 75 cents per pound, liveweight, up 10 cents from April
1987.
   Despite the April decline, catfish production for the first five
months was up from a year earlier, totaling 102.8 million pounds
against 97.5 million in the same period of 1987.
</TEXT>
