<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0938</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country music group Alabama took a trip
south _ downtown, that is _ where the musicians fed the hungry at a
soup kitchen in the city's Lower East Side.
   Group members Randy Owen, Mark Herndon, Jeff Cook and Teddy
Gentry donned white hats Friday to serve fried chicken, salad and a
strawberry dessert at the Bowery Mission. Then they stopped to chat
with the lunch crowd.
   Alabama is a featured act on the Marlboro Country Music Tour,
which ends today at New York's Madison Square Garden. One dollar
from each ticket sold along the 30-city tour goes to Second
Harvest, a national food bank for the hungry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEVON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Ruth Pointer of The Pointer Sisters was
admitted to Bryn Mawr Hospital in satisfactory condition after she
and her sisters canceled a concert series, a hospital spokesman
said.
   Ms. Pointer left the theater Friday night complaining of a
``lower tract infection'' less than 20 minutes before The Pointer
Sisters were to open a three-night stand, said Jim McCormick,
manager of the Valley Forge Music Fair in Devon.
   She arrived in the hospital's emergency room at 7:55 p.m., the
hospital spokesman said.
   The performances were rescheduled for Sept. 22 and 23, McCormick
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who invented Nautilus exercise
equipment says he will donate nearly $8.5 million to the Health
Science Center and Center for Exercise Science at the University of
Florida.
   ``I have a longstanding interest in physical training and
wellness, and my support of the University of Florida will boost
the research of lower back pain, one of man's most nagging
problems,'' said inventor Arthur A. Jones.
   Jones, who is credited with revolutionizing the exercise
industry, sold his Nautilus empire in 1986 to devote his time to
his MedX Corp., which began marketing the Lumbar Extension Machine
later that year.
   The college's exercise center is testing Jones' latest
invention, a computerized machine designed to evaluate and
rehabilitate the lower back.
   ``As the beneficiary of the largest gift in the history of the
University of Florida and our state university system, we welcome
the opportunity to join in his crusade against lower back
problems,'' University President Marshall Criser said Friday in
accepting the donation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people gathered at a high school
in Jimmy Stewart's hometown to celebrate the actor's 80th birthday
by watching ``The Philadelphia Story'' and eating cake.
   Stewart was in Beverly Hills, Calif., where he said his wife,
Gloria, had ``fixed up a party.'' But he sent greetings in a letter
to some of his friends.
   Stewart received the Academy Award for best actor in 1940 for
his role in ``The Philadelphia Story,'' and the Oscar for years was
displayed in the window of his father's hardware store on
Philadelphia Street in this small southwestern Pennsylvania town.
   The film was shown Friday night in the auditorium of the Indiana
Area Senior High School, and a birthday cake was served to
Stewart's fans in the lobby. The cake depicted a statue of Stewart
that was unveiled in front of the county courthouse during a
three-day bash held for Stewart's 75th birthday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hall of Fame outfielder Willie Mays made a
pitch for his book, ``Say Hey,'' at a local bookstore, but balked
at interviews with two broadcasters who hadn't read the
autobiography.
   Fans stood in line an hour or more Thursday as Mays signed
copies of ``Say Hey.''
   Mays, 57, wouldn't sign baseballs or baseball cards, just books.
Many people bought three or four copies; a few bought six or seven.
   But when sportscasters Howard Eskin of WTAF-TV and Scott Palmer
of WPVI-TV asked for on-camera interviews, Mays asked if they had
read the book.
   Neither had.
   ``Scan through the book and then ask some questions,'' Mays told
Eskin. ``You should be prepared.''
   Palmer met a similar fate.
   Mays played for the Giants, first in New York and then in San
Francisco, before finishing his 22-year career with the New York
Mets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duke of Gloucester, cousin of Queen Elizabeth
II, will visit the British fortress colony of Gibraltar next week,
his office announced.
   Press Association, the domestic news agency, reported that the
duke will stay four days and, as a patron of the Friends of
Gibraltar Heritage Trust, tour the naval dockyard and other
historic sites. It did not say when he would begin his visit.
   The agency said it will be the first Gibraltar visit by a member
of the royal family since the Prince and Princess of Wales began
their honeymoon cruise from the colony in 1981.
   Spain claims sovereignty over the colony, and Spanish King Juan
Carlos stayed away from the royal wedding because the couple made
Gibraltar the first stop of their honeymoon.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children's Hospital of Philadelphia says it
will honor U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, formerly the
hospital's chief surgeon, by establishing a chair in his name.
   Hospital board members, colleagues, friends and former patients
contributed $1.5 million to endow the C. Everett Koop Chair in
Pediatric Surgery, the first of many chairs the institution plans
to create as funds are raised, hospital spokeswoman Shirley Bonnem
said Friday.
   The chair's first occupant will be Dr. James O'Neill Jr., the
hospital's current surgeon-in-chief, Bonnem said.
</TEXT>
