<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietBase     05-21 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Base,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Soviets Might Expand Syrian Facility Into Permanent Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is poised to turn its naval
repair facility in Syria into a permanent base in a move cementing
the military alliance between the two nations, Jane's Defense
Weekly says.
   The expanded base at Tartus would serve as home for the Soviets'
Mediterranean navy, according to today's issue of the respected
magazine.
   Jane's based its report on diplomatic sources, which it did not
identify.
   The report said the development of Tartus ``indicates a
consolidation of the Soviet Union's military relationship with its
key Middle East ally.''
   Jane's said a number of high-ranking Soviet military officials
had visited Tartus recently, port calls had increased and
deployment of aircraft had been expanded.
   It said Western analysts were particularly concerned because the
Soviet admiral in charge of Tartus supervised the development of
the Soviet's Cam Ranh Bay base in Vietnam.
   Cam Ranh Bay has been described by U.S. intelligence sources as
the ``largest Soviet naval forward deployment base'' outside the
Soviet Union, the report said.
   It said the Soviets have used Tartus, about 35 miles north of
the Lebanese border, since 1969 as a limited repair and maintenance
facility. But their presence increased markedly in 1976 after they
were expelled from Egyptian bases.
   The magazine said Tartus is now the Soviets' primary maintenance
facility for submarines and the deployment of anti-surface warfare
and reconnaissance aircraft has increased.
   Jane's said the Soviets pay no rent for the base.
</TEXT>
