<DOCNO> AP880521-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0884 05-21 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0884,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Steps Back From Noriega Policy; Dukakis Says He'll Talk With
Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS top 2 grafs to clarify that Dukakis comments referred to
Reagan administration dealings with Noriega, not plan to drop drug
charges.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush took another step away from President
Reagan's controversial negotiations with Panama's indicted leader
Manuel Noriega on Friday. Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
said the ``American people want an explanation'' of why the Reagan
administration was dealing with Noriega.
   Dukakis, campaigning in California, said ``somebody in the
administration'' should tell the American people ``who it was who
thought it was in the interests of the American people and this
country that we do business with somebody who was a known drug
peddler and who was suspected of murder.''
   He added, ``Unless and until we have that explanation, I'm not
going to be satisfied.''
   Bush said nothing publicly on Noriega, but his maneuverings came
two days after he declared that he would not negotiate with accused
drug runners in this country or on foreign soil. At the time, he
did not mention either Panama or its indicted leader, Noriega, by
name.
   But following the publication of a story Friday in The
Washington Post, the vice president's chief of staff, Craig Fuller,
issued a statement saying that ``the administration sources who
have suggested that the vice president favors ending the
negotiations and bringing the envoy back to Washington are
essentially correct.''
   The statement was issued just hours before sources disclosed a
tentative agreement for Noriega to relinquish power and leave
Panama temporarily in exchange for the Reagan administration
dropping the drug indictment.
   The Fuller statement was as close as Bush has come to publicly
uttering words of disagreement with Reagan over his Panamanian
policy, and came after several days of slippage in the public
opinion polls and with many Republican allies urging him to air his
differences with the president.
   The issue of Panama and drugs also arose in a court deposition
given by Donald Gregg, Bush's national security adviser.
   Gregg said in the sworn statement that the president of Panama
told the vice president in December 1983 that allegations of drug
running among government officials were untrue.
   ``The vice president said he had not been aware of the charges
or he would have raised them'' during the session, Gregg testified
in a deposition for a private civil lawsuit.
   He added, ``We did nothing to follow up.'' The vice president
was chairman of the South Florida Drug Interdiction Task Force at
the time.
   Spokesman Stephen Hart had no comment on Gregg's deposition.
   Jesse Jackson, meanwhile, repeated his criticism of U.S.
negotiations with Noriega but made no reference to the reported
tentative agreement.
   ``Noriega is not plea bargaining with Reagan and Bush. Reagan
and Bush are plea bargaining with Noriega,'' Jackson told more than
500 supporters at a San Francisco church.
   Jackson, the sole remaining rival to Dukakis for the Democratic
nomination, said, ``We need to know what's going on. Send a special
prosecutor to Panama. Send a congressional delegation to Panama.
Hear both sides of an ugly story.''
   Dukakis also campaigned in California in advance of the state's
June 7 primary.
   He said he and Jackson met on Sunday and will ``be meeting
regularly.'' The Massachusetts governor did not say what he and
Jackson would discuss in their talks, but his challenger has been
pressing for a greater share of votes from ``super delegates'' to
the Democratic National Convention. These party and elected
officials, who are automatically entitled to attend the nominating
convention, have largely been lining up behind Dukakis.
   At home, the Dukakis administration announced new proposed
spending cuts, efficiency steps and revenue plans designed to
improve the bottom line of Dukakis' $11.9 billion state budget
proposal for next year by $217 million.
   Faced with a shortfall in tax collections, Dukakis is proposing
to cut $92 million from expansions he had previously proposed in
dozens of individual programs. He also signed off on a hoped-for
$47 million in savings through improved government operations. He
also hopes to raise millions more through bottle deposits and a
higher tax on cigarettes. Friday's sobering budget news could hurt
Dukakis' attempts to campaign on earlier balanced budgets.
   Democratic platform writers met in suburban Washington, where
Sen. John Glenn of Ohio said the public is under ``the great
misconception'' that nuclear arms treaties may allow the United
States to spend less on conventional weapons.
   Glenn, mentioned as a possible running mate on a Dukakis ticket,
said the truth was ``exactly the opposite. ... We may have to spend
more instead of less.''
   Rep. Ron Dellums of California, representing both the Jackson
campaign and his own views, said the Democrats should find ways to
reduce the burden of the Pentagon's $299 billion budget, which has
doubled since 1980.
   Dellums said the United States should call home some of its
325,000 troops in Europe and scrap a wide range of weapon systems,
from the MX missile, the Midgetman and Trident II to research on
Star Wars.
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk, meanwhile, unleashed a
stinging attack on Bush as a ``quintessential elitist establishment
Republican country clubber.''
   In a speech before the Association of Democratic State Chairs
meeting in Atlanta, Kirk said the vice president has been
``applauding in the dark shadows of this Republican administration
as it turns thumbs down on the Civil Rights Restoration Act, thumbs
down on a simple 60-day notice to working men and women who are
about to lose their jobs.''
   He said Bush ``has neither the toughness to govern nor the
compassion to care.''
</TEXT>
