<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialMoney     05-21 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Money,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Fights In Money Big League</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats Jesse Jackson and front-runner
Michael Dukakis are going head-to-head on spending in the home
stretch of the presidential primary season as Vice President George
Bush coasts along with a comfortable bank account.
   Jackson, who once had to scrimp along while Dukakis surpassed
all the other Democrats in fund-raising, actually matched the
Massachusetts governor in money from contributors during the month
of April. Both men collected $1.9 million, reports filed Friday
showed.
   With federal matching funds and a $624,000 loan added to his
receipts, Jackson raised more than Dukakis overall in April. The
reports showed he had a total of $4.2 million in receipts,
including $1.7 in matching funds, while Dukakis took in $3.4
million, including $1.1 million in matching funds.
   Dukakis has borrowed no money, and has been the Democratic money
leader since he entered the presidential race. The figures show
continued growth in Jackson's fund-raising capability, which
started out very weak but has steadily improved.
   Looking toward the costly battles in California and New Jersey,
Dukakis and Jackson each entered May with $1 million-plus bank
accounts.
   While Dukakis is collecting delegates at a pace that will land
him the Democratic nomination, Jackson still is waging a
high-stakes fight.
   Jackson actually spent more than Dukakis during April, but a
good chunk of it _ $804,570 _ went to pay off loans, according to
the financial disclosure report he filed with the Federal Election
Commission. Jackson spokesman Tom Schade said the borrowing and
repayment figures reflected a rotating line of credit for Jackson's
operating expenses.
   Jackson reported spending $4 million during the month that saw
costly races in New York and Pennsylvania, while Dukakis spent $3.7
million.
   Jackson ended the month with $1.1 million in cash on hand and
$548,741 in debts. Dukakis had $1.4 million on hand, and $699,906
in obligations.
   On the Republican side, Bush had $4 million in the bank at the
end of April, after raising $2 million for the month _ including
$1.2 million in matching funds _ and spending $1.7 million. Bush
also reported taking out a $20,000 loan for general election
campaign start-up costs.
   Bush's only remaining rival, religious broadcaster Pat
Robertson, suspended his campaign last week. Robertson reported a
debt of $1.4 million at the start of this month. He raised $1.1
million, with $341,523 of that in federal matching funds, and spent
$1.1 million during April. Robertson had $29,473 in the bank.
   Dukakis' campaign said he has raised $23.6 million from the
start of his campaign through the end of April, including $6.8
million in matching funds, which are based on the amount a
candidate raises on his own.
   Jackson's campaign total through April was $11.7 million.
   Dukakis' campaign has been wearing a tight belt lately in order
to save enough for the expensive June 7 California primary and
still be able to spend on its summer convention operations without
surpassing the $27 million cap on the amount primary candidates are
allowed to spend.
   Among the also-rans, Democrats Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee
and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri each have campaign debts of
$1.6 million, their reports show. Republican Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas was left with a $1.2 million debt after he dropped out of
the race.
</TEXT>
