<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BraidwoodNuclear     05-21 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Braidwood Nuclear,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Grants Full-Power License for Braidwood Nuclear Reactor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second of two reactors at the Braidwood
nuclear plant near Chicago should be in full operation by summer
under a full-power license granted by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, Commonwealth Edison Co. says.
   The NRC voted 5-0 on Friday to grant the license, five months
after it had approved a permit for low-power testing at the
reactor, commission spokesman Frank Ingram said.
   ``We're very gratified by the fact that the commissioners voted
unanimously,'' utility spokeswoman Deborah Vestal said. ``We feel
very confident we'll maintain that kind of the support from the
NRC.''
   She said tests of the reactor will continue and it will be
brought up to full power gradually, producing 1.1 million kilowatts
of electricity a day when fully operational in the summer.
   The first of Braidwood's two reactors, located about 20 miles
southwest of Joliet, Ill., was licensed for full-power operation on
July 2, 1987.
   Ingram said the time between issuance of low-power and
full-power licenses for the second Braidwood unit was somewhat
longer than usual because of equipment problems that have since
been resolved.
</TEXT>
