<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   05-21 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defiant Noriega Says No Accord While U.S. `Aggression' Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY38</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MIGUELITO, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega says he
wants recognition of his president and a reduction of U.S. forces
in Panama before he agrees to end his standoff with Washington.
   Though a White House official said Friday that a tentative deal
had been worked out under which the general would step down as
Panama's military leader, Noriega stridently repeated conditions he
has insisted on for weeks.
   He spoke Friday during a dedication of a grandstand and
sportcasters' and dignitaries' box at an athletic complex in this
working-class suburb nine miles northeast of Panama City.
   ``There cannot be conversation if the (U.S.) aggression
continues, aggression at whatever level, whatever magnitude,
whether it is psychological or economic aggression,'' Noriega said.
   ``Second, (there must be) respect for the government of the
president of the republic, Manuel Solis Palma. And there cannot be
conversation, there cannot be a solution if an exaggerated number
of troops remain on our territory as psychological aggression,'' he
said.
   Neither can there be a solution, he said, unless the government
that remains is recognized by Panama's military.
   About 10,000 U.S. troops are normally stationed at 10 U.S.
military installations along the Panama Canal. About 2,000
reinforcements have been added in recent months as tensions rose
between the United States and Panama.
   Noriega did not refer to a report in Washington that U.S. and
Panamanian negotiators have tentatively agreed on a deal that calls
for the general to leave Panama for nine months beginning in August.
   In return, the United States would drop federal drug smuggling
charges against Noriega, according to a Reagan administration
official in Washington who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Noriega, as head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces, controls
the civilian government. The Reagan administration has imposed
sweeping economic sanctions against the country in an effort to
force his ouster.
   The United States still recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle, who has
been in hiding, as Panama's legitimate president. Noriega
engineered Delvalle's dismissal on Feb. 26, the day after Delvalle
tried to fire Noriega.
   Noriega spoke to supporters in San Miguelito from the new
dignitaries' box. On the field were several hundred members of the
so-called Dignity Batallions, volunteers formed to confront what
the Noriega regime says is the danger of a U.S. invasion.
   About three dozen volunteers armed with World War II-era rifles
ran through an obstacle course, then battered a dummy dressed in
olive green during a demonstration of their training skills.
   Noriega said the militias would fight any invaders.
   ``Those powerful ones who think they can come to this territory
without getting a whipping are mistaken,'' he said.
   The master of ceremonies who introduced Noriega told foreign
reporters: ``If there is an invasion, you won't be filming
Panamanian cadavers, but the cadavers of North American soldiers
that we will send home to North American mothers.''
   Noriega concluded the list of conditions for a U.S.-Panamanian
solution by saying: ``If I have said nothing, it is because I know
them (the Americans), and because I know them, I remain silent.''
   He also denounced corruption in public administration.
   ``What we need,'' he said, ``is punishment similar to Islamic
punishment. He who puts his hand in the till should have it cut
off. We must reach that kind of radicalization.''
   About 400 militia members were at the combination soccer and
baseball field. Scores of Panamanian flags fluttered in the slight
breeze.
   A similar number of residents were in the grandstands and around
the playing field.
   Several folk groups danced and sang traditional songs. One dance
company featured women in long flowing skirts performing folk tunes
played on guitars and tamborines.
</TEXT>
