<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Workers     05-21 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Workers,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Gives More Freedom to Foreign-Funded Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has approved new regulations to give
foreign-funded businesses greater freedom in hiring and firing
workers, the official China Daily newspaper reported today.
   The move comes as China energetically seeks to boost foreign
investment to advance its economic development.
   The new rules buck the country's state-controlled industrial and
business enterprises, known as ``work units,'' which have often
blocked people from changing jobs and resisted dismissals for
anything short of serious crimes or work violations.
   The newspaper said the new rules approved by the State Council
let foreign-funded businesses recruit their own workers and
managerial staff. They will no longer need permission from local
labor offices to hire workers from outside the area where the
businesses are located, the newspaper said.
   Workers recruited by such businesses will be able to resign from
their present jobs even if their work units raise objections, it
said.
   The regulations also say foreign-funded ventures can fire
employees according to their contracts and without being subject to
outside intervention.
</TEXT>
