<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorkerDisplacement     05-21 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worker Displacement,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Inadequate Job Assistance May Lead To Underclass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate Republican study group says the
United States is developing an underclass of unskilled workers
because displaced laborers are not receiving adequate job search
assistance, training, counseling or benefits.
   The Senate Republican Conference task force on education and job
training, in a report released Friday, said Congress should enact a
$980 million education and job training program that consolidates
two current programs _ the Job Training Partnership Act and the
Trade Adjustment Assistance Act.
   The group said the new program would serve an estimated 700,000
workers and ``seek to eliminate some of the costly duplication of
effort as well as the delays by the current ... certification
process.''
   ``The new program would also provide substantially greater
emphasis on actual retraining,'' the report said. ``Workers who are
unable to find new jobs which utilize their existing skills require
programs that offer opportunities to update their skills or to
retrain for new occupations.''
   The task force report said of the more than one million American
workers displaced annually, more than one-third of them have
extended periods of unemployment while some never return to the
work force.
   Of those who do return, almost one-half take pay cuts, according
to the study group which was chaired by Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I.
   The United States ``is faced with the creation of a growing
underclass, increasingly made up of former manufacturing and
industrial workers without the skills to enter (the work place),''
the report said.
   The report said projections for the next 15 years indicate that
millions of Americans are not only ill-prepared for existing jobs
but will have even more difficulty in the future ``unless the work
force is retrained and continuously prepared for marketplace
change.''
   The GOP conference is an organization made of all 46 Republican
senators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
