<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   05-21 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Dealings With Noriega Serve As Fodder On Campaign
Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's dealings with Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega continue to attract attention on the presidential
campaign trail, as Michael Dukakis demands an explanation and
George Bush tries to distance himself from the policies of his boss.
   Democratic front-runner Dukakis, campaigning in California, said
Friday that ``somebody in the administration'' is going to have to
tell the American people ``who it was who thought it was in the
interests of the American people and this country that we do
business with somebody who was a known drug peddler and who was
suspected of murder.''
   ``Unless and until we have that explanation, I'm not going to be
satisfied,'' said Dukakis, who has focused on the Reagan
administration drug policy and dealings with Noriega as he
campaigns in advance of California's crucial June 7 primary.
   U.S. and Panamanian officials on Friday reportedly reached a
tentative agreement for Noriega's departure from the Central
American nation in August in exchange for dropping drug charges
against him in the United States.
   According to an administration source who disclosed the
tentative agreement, Bush already has registered his objections to
the plan.
   Dukakis' Democratic rival, Jesse Jackson, repeated his criticism
of U.S. negotiations with Noriega but made no reference to the
reported tentative agreement.
   The American people have received ``too much talk and too little
information,'' about what's going on concerning dealings with
Noriega, Jackson said at a church rally in San Francisco.
   ``Noriega is not plea bargaining with Reagan and Bush. Reagan
and Bush are plea bargaining with Noriega,'' Jackson told more than
500 supporters at the rally.
   Jackson was scheduled to appear at a shipyard rally with labor
groups in the San Pedro port of Los Angeles today.
   Bush was saying nothing publicly on Noriega, but the vice
president's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, issued a statement Friday
confirming published reports ``that the vice president favors
ending the negotiations and bringing the envoy back to Washington.''
   Fuller's statement, issued before the latest tentative deal was
disclosed, was the closest Bush has come to publicly disagreeing
with President Reagany over the administration's Panamanian policy.
Two days earlier Bush said, without mentioning Noriega by name,
that he would not negotiate with accused drug runners in this
country or on foreign soil.
   The subject of Panama and drugs arose again Friday when another
Bush aide, Donald Gregg, said in a sworn court deposition that
during a December 1983 meeting, the president of Panama told Bush
about allegations of drug running among Panamanian officials and
also told the vice president the stories were untrue.
   ``The vice president said he had not been aware of the charges
or he would have raised them'' during the session, Gregg testified
in a deposition taken in Washington for a private civil lawsuit.
   In Atlanta, the Democrats' top hired gun opened fire on Bush on
another front, calling him ``a quintessential elitist establishment
Republican country-clubber'' and a do-nothing public official.
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk said during a
meeting of the Association of Democratic State Chairs that Bush is
a mere functionary ``applauding in the dark shadows of this
Republican administration as it turns thumbs down on public ethics,
thumbs down on the Civil Rights Restoration Act, thumbs down on a
simple 60-days' notice to working men and women who are about to
lose their jobs.''
   The challenge for Democrats is to ``make sure that when people
go to the polls in November, George Bush will have a rendezvous
with his own record,'' Kirk told the party leaders.
   Democrats also took up the issue of military spending as the
party's platform committee met Friday in suburban Washington.
   California Rep. Ronald Dellums told the panel ``a significant
wing'' of the party shares the Jackson campaign's view that
Pentagon budgets should be trimmed by $200 billion over the next
four years.
   ``I represent a point of view that is a significant wing of the
Democratic Party,'' said Dellums. ``I don't believe that we can
tiptoe into the White House. ... I don't believe that we can
continue to play the game of `Me too,''' on defense spending.
   ``Either we're a party advocating peace or we're a party
advocating war,'' Dellums added.
   But two Democratic senators who are mentioned as possible
running mates r front-runner Michael Dukakis _ John Glenn of Ohio
and Sam Nunn of Georgia _ told the committee the party must stand
for a strong national defense.
</TEXT>
