<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Thailand-Crash     05-21 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Thailand-Crash,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amphetamines Found On Driver In Crash That Killed 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amphetamines were found on the body of
a driver whose truck crashed through a railway crossing and struck
a moving passenger train, killing at least 23 people, authorities
said today.
   Two cars of the train were thrown into an irrigation canal
during Friday's crash in the Takhli district of central Nakhon
Sawan province, about 200 miles north of Bangkok.
   Police said 23 people died, but Takhli hospital officials said
the bodies of 24 people were recovered. Reports said there were two
other bodies at another hospital.
   Doctors said 15 people remain hospitalized today.
   Takhli police Sub-Lt. Wallop Kangtaratip said police found
amphetamines, a stimulant, on the body of Somkid Fakkao, 20, whose
truck was loaded with rocks bound for a cement factory when it
crashed.
</TEXT>
