<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Prison 1stLd-Writethru a0437 05-21 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Prison, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0437,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says Demeaning Conditions Drive Women Inmates to Drugs,
Lesbianism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT date of Tass report to a year ago, SUB third to
last graf, `The official ... an education.' Picks up penultimate
graf, `Soviet officials ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented Soviet newspaper article
describes life as being so demeaning and dreary in one women's
penal colony on the Volga River that inmates are driven to drugs
and lesbianism.
   A prisoner identified only as Kutsyenkova, a former college
lecturer, told the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya of the desperation
among prisoners in Corrective Labor Women's Colony No. 65-15 in
Kuybyshev, 620 miles southeast of Moscow.
   ``The regime of the colony gives rise to a destructive process
in a woman,'' says Kutsyenkova, whose crime leading to her
imprisonment was not disclosed in the article.
   ``Marching in formation, ugly clothes, banging of iron,
commands, meatless diet _ this makes one insipid, dull, leads one
to search for emotional relief at any price.''
   Inmates could fight off ``a breakdown'' for five years at the
most, Kutsyenkova says in the Friday article _ but ``then the
organism catastrophically weakens'' and convicts seek solace in
smoking, lesbianism and narcotics.
   The prisoner ``experiences an atrophy of will and initiative, a
growing of uncontrollable rage,'' says the woman, whose doctoral
dissertation had been about the family.
   According to the article, punishment of prisoners often
backfires, causing them to get into more trouble instead of leading
them to rehabilitation.
   Some inmates don't want to be freed after serving long prison
terms because they no longer have families on the outside,
Kutsyenkova said. The article told of two freed prisoners who slept
for several nights right outside the colony, ``praying to be taken
back'' because they could no longer live on their own.
   It was one of the first articles about conditions in women's
prison camps. Conditions at the Soviet Union's notorious penal
colonies and labor camps for men, described in the books of exile
Alexander Solzhenitsyn, were once taboo subjects for Soviet news
media.
   However, the policy of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev of
open discussion of the nation's problems has produced reports
exposing deficiencies in the criminal justice system.
   Alexander V. Vlasov, who as minister of internal affairs
oversees the prisons, acknowledged in a commentary accompanying the
article that improvements are needed.
   ``Quite a few problems have piled up in the system of corrective
labor institutions. Perestroika is needed also in this sphere in
which the human factor should be made predominant too,'' he writes.
   Perestroika is Gorbachev's term for his overhauling of Soviet
society.
   The article said inmates of Corrective Labor Women's Colony No.
65-15 had murdered husbands and children, taken bribes or engaged
in other forms of corruption. Sovietskaya Rossiya said one woman
had been an engineer-economist, another a chief bookkeeper, a third
the director of a large store. Several had been senior lecturers at
colleges.
   As prisoners, they had to work up to 10-12 hours a day in sewing
shops with poor ventilation, the article said.
   If a prisoner went out without a shawl, smoked in a prohibited
area or said goodnight too loudly to cellmates the punishment might
be 10-15 days in an isolation cell.
   Vlasov said his ministry was trying to improve the quality of
its staff at the colonies and labor camps. He said new codes were
being drafted to make the punishment more appropriately fit a
convict's crime and to provide in some cases for a reduction of
sentences.
   Time off for good work and good behavior is being planned as one
experiment.
   Vlasov did not specifically address the problems of lesbianism
and drug addiction among women inmates.
   The official Tass news agency carried a report a year ago saying
life in one camp outside Moscow was hard, but that prisoners were
treated fairly and given free time and an opportunity to get an
education.
   Soviet officials say the camps are designed to make inmates take
a conscientious attitude toward work and teach them to live by the
law.
   Western organizations estimate the camps hold 1 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
