<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     05-21 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas and Contras Agree on New Date for Talks But Not on
Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and rebel leaders have
agreed to resume peace talks next week before their tenative truce
expires, but remain at odds over where to meet.
   Jorge Rosales, spokesman for the U.S.-supported rebels known as
Contras, said from Miami on Friday that rebel leaders had agreed to
the government's proposal that the third round of talks begin
Wednesday.
   He said Contra leaders plan to meet with representatives of the
leftist Sandinista government at the southern frontier post of
Sapoa, where the sides signed a 60-day cease-fire on March 23.
   But Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said in a note to rebel
official Roberto Ferrey that the meeting must be held in Managua.
   To meet outside the capital would be ``to go back on the
advances that, with great difficulties, have been achieved,'' he
said in the letter released by the presidential press office.
   The Contras have objected to keeping the talks in Managua, where
the first two rounds were held, because they said their movements
were restricted by the Sandinista government. The rebels said they
were unable freely meet with domestic opposition leaders.
   The sides are trying to forge a lasting peace under the Sapoa
accords, which provided for the temporary truce that expires May 30
and promised the Contras a role in the political future of a more
democratic Nicaragua.
   But little progress appears to have been made and rebel fighters
have been reluctant to move into designated cease-fire zones agreed
to by negotiators.
   Tinoco told reporters Friday that the government had proposed
halting the fighting for another month, but the rebels have not
responded. The Sandinistas have threatened to mount a major
offensive if the truce is not extended.
   The Contra leadership has in the past month suffered from
infighting over the military leadership of Col. Enrique Bermudez.
But rebel officials now say the rifts have been healed.
   On Friday, a Costa Rican official said Bermudez would attend
next week's peace talks. He has not previously taken part in the
discussions.
   Sources say thousands of rebel fighters have moved toward the
border with Honduras, through which the U.S. Agency for
International Development is providing them humanitarian aid.
   As part of the Sapoa accords, rebel fighters have been permitted
to receive humanitarian aid through a neutral organization.
   The Sandinistas have said the insurgents can receive food,
medicine and clothes distributed by the International Red Cross.
But the Contras rejected that, saying the organization sympathizes
with the government.
   Meanwhile, the government on Friday temporarily barred
church-run Radio Catolica from airing a news program that had
broadcast an interview with a rebel chief.
   The Interior Ministry said in a statement that the station
should have cleared the interview with the government and that the
news program could not resume broadcasting until Tuesday.
   Radio Catolica and two other privately owned radio stations were
temporarily prohibited from broadcasting news programs earlier this
month because of their reports on a workers' strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
