<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     05-21 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Courts Reduce Sentences for Three Solidarity Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has reduced the prison
sentences of three Solidarity activists jailed during this past
month's widespread labor unrest. The two still being held are to be
freed on Wednesday.
   Gdansk activists Bogdan Lis and Czeslaw Nowak, arrested May 4 on
charges of urging strikes in the Baltic port city, on Friday had
jail terms reduced from three months to three weeks.
   Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz, originally
sentenced May 7 to six weeks in prison but freed Monday pending
appeal, was instead ordered to perform 20 hours of public service.
   The three were arrested during more than two weeks of strikes
and street protests that ended May 10.
   The protests, triggered in part by steep price increases, posed
the most serious challenge to Poland's Communist leaders since
their 1981 martial law crackdown on Solidarity.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said one day after the final
strike ended peacefully May 10 at the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk that
the government would follow a ``non-repressive policy'' toward the
strikers.
   The last of 38 strikers arrested May 5 when police stormed the
strikebound Nowa Huta steelworks in southern Poland were freed
Monday.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said even the shortened sentences
meted out by the appeals court Friday were unjustified.
   ``I don't know what to think about these sentences,'' he said
from his home in Gdansk. ``It is ridiculous.''
   Onyszkiewicz had been charged with spreading false information
intended to cause public unrest. The mathematics instructor at
Warsaw University said he was put on trial as a warning to people
not to speak to the Western press.
   ``This is glasnost Polish-style,'' he said.
   Solidarity, the only independent labor federation ever allowed
in the Soviet bloc, was banned in 1982.
</TEXT>
