<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShooting-Scene     05-21 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting-Scene,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tranquil Suburb Shaken By Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-School Shooting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children here need to be convinced that
school is a safe place, officials said, following a woman's
shooting rampage that left one child dead and six other people
critically wounded.
   ``It's an incident the violates all of us,'' Winnetka
Superintendent Don Monroe said late Friday night after meeting with
parents, children, clergy and social workers.
   More meetings are planned throughout the weekend, as the shocked
community of 12,500 tries to work through what one parent called
the ultimate nightmare.
   ``The intent of all of our activities is to work together so
that children will once again feel that there are familiar adults
in school that care about them,'' Monroe said.
   A woman identified as Lori Wasserman Dann, 30, was found dead in
a house where she had barricaded herself for nearly nine hours
after she went on the shooting spree Friday morning at Hubbard
Woods Elementary School, killing one child and wounding five
others. She later wounded an adult. Police said she killed herself.
   Ms. Dann, a baby sitter, had entered the school about 10:45
a.m., shot a youngster in the bathroom and then entered a
second-grade classroom, where she opened fire, police said.
   Eight-year-old Nicholas Corwin died of his wounds at Highland
Park Hospital. The other five children were taken to two hospitals,
along with a 20-year-old man who tried to wrestle a gun away from
Ms. Dann.
   Ann Arnold, who lives across the street from one of the wounded
children, said her 7-year-old son made sure the doors were locked
after he came home from school.
   ``He's still scared something else is going to happen,'' Mrs.
Arnold said.
   Adults, too, were in shock.
   ``I don't feel comfortable being outside,'' said Anne Belmont.
   Monroe, his shirt stained with blood, tried to reassure anxious
parents immediately after the shooting at the sprawling, one-story
brick school.
   ``We never have a drill for something like this. But we do have
fire and tornado drills, so the kids were on the floor in the other
classrooms'' after the shooting, he said.
   Parents who arrived on the scene after the shooting helped
entertain children until social workers arrived.
   Standing outside school at the end of the day, Jim Romey said
his 7-year-old daughter was in another classroom when the shooting
occurred.
   ``The kids are calm,'' said his wife, Blanche. School officials
``told us to take them home and let them talk because they've been
talked to a lot today,'' she said.
   Parents also were told not to push their children to talk, but
to give them time to react to the tragedy.
   Winnetka, a northern Chicago suburb, is marked by large homes
and comfortable incomes. A survey released last year by a Roosevelt
University urbanologist ranked it as the nation's 22nd-wealthiest
suburb with an estimated per-capita income of $35,406.
   ``The community has responded beautifully,'' Monroe said.
``There's a high level of cooperation and people are coming
together to try to put this in perspective.''
   Families of four of the injured children gathered at Evanston
Hospital, which assigned a special team of doctors and social
workers to meet with them.
   ``All four families were together in one room,'' said John
Bozeday, a social worker.
   ``One of the things that has happened,'' he said, ``is that
they've kind of pulled together and formed a larger family of their
own.''
</TEXT>
