<DOCNO> AP880521-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0535EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchSuit     05-21 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church Suit,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $1.5 Million To Man Who Claimed Lesbian Nun Broke Up
Marriage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $1.5 million to a man
who claimed his marriage was destroyed by a lesbian nun who seduced
his wife, and that church officials did nothing to prevent it.
   Steve Woolverton sued former Sister Mary Kregar and the Catholic
Diocese of Brownsville, alleging that an affair between Ms. Kregar
and his wife, Mary Woolverton, broke up his 12-year marriage in
1984.
   Woolverton's personal-injury lawsuit, filed in 1986, also
claimed church officials were negligent by allowing Ms. Kregar to
serve as a nun in Port Isabel and continue serving there after
Woolverton told them of the affair.
   ``The jury has returned a verdict finding not only the conduct
on the part of the nun (was negligent), as we had stated in our
lawsuit, but also the conduct on the part of the parish priest in
not attending and responding to this in a timely fashion,'' Edwin
Randolph Fleuriet, Woolverton's lawyer, said after Friday's verdict.
   Ms. Kregar came to Our Lady Star of the Sea Church in Port
Isabel in September 1983 and became director of the choir, for
which Mrs. Woolverton played the guitar. Ms. Kregar left the
Franciscan order of nuns in August 1984.
   The Woolvertons, who have three children, separated in May 1984,
and Woolverton claimed in his suit filed two years later that Ms.
Kregar ``used her fiduciary position of trust to commence a
seduction of plaintiff's wife.''
   Jurors deliberated for five hours before awarding Woolverton
$500,000 in actual damages, $500,000 in exemplary damages from Ms.
Kregar and $500,000 in exemplary damages from the diocese.
   The Rev. Ben Verbrugge, then parish priest; Bishop John J.
Fitzpatrick; Ms. Kregar; and Sister Cecilia Rolling, a nun at the
Port Isabel church, were found guilty of ``gross negligence'' by
failing to intervene in the matter after Woolverton told the priest
of the lesbian relationship.
   Although Woolverton had sought $5 million in damages, Fleuriet
said he was pleased with the judgment.
   Defense lawyers never denied that there had been an affair
between Mrs. Woolverton and Ms. Kregar. Most of the trial testimony
took the form of videotaped depositions from Ms. Kregar, Mrs.
Woolverton, church officials and a family friend.
   Darrell Barger, lead attorney for the diocese, contended during
the trial that the suit was for ``money, money, money'' and that
when Bishop Fitzpatrick became convinced of the lesbian
relationship in March 1984, he acted quickly to remove the nun.
   Ms. Kregar left the Rochester, Minn.-based order in August 1984
by a ``mutual decision,'' primarily because of her inability to
lead a celibate life, said Sister Mary Franchon Pirkl, executive
councillor of the Franciscan Order.
   Woolverton said he convinced the bishop of the relationship with
a secretly recorded conversation between his wife and the nun,
described as sexual in nature. He also employed a private
investigator to watch his wife.
   Woolverton now lives in Durango, Colo. His ex-wife lives
elsewhere in that city with their children, and Ms. Kregar is a
social worker in Pueblo, Colo.
   ``I'm glad it's over for everybody,'' Woolverton said. ``I'm
going back with my kids and help raise them.''
   He declined further comment.
   Church officials quickly left the Cameron County Courthouse
after the jury's decision, and could not be reached for comment
later. Ms. Kregar and her attorney, Virginia Raymond, declined to
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
