<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mofford-Gifts Bjt   05-21 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mofford-Gifts, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford `Stands Behind' Gifts; Prosecutors Investigate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford has defended her
expenditure of thousands of dollars in state funds on gifts and
other items, including diet food, a $530 watch and a joke-writing
service.
   The Maricopa County Attorney's office said Friday it will
broaden an ongoing investigation into Mrs. Mofford's finances while
she served as secretary of state to include the new disclosures.
   Mrs. Mofford declined to answer questions about the disclosures
Friday. However, in a brief interview with radio station KFYI, Mrs.
Mofford defended the expenditures.
   ``I never misspent a penny,'' Mrs. Mofford told the station.
``It was appropriated for VIP gifts, and I used it for that type of
purpose. I never used anything for personal gain.''
   ``As has been the practice to date, the items to be purchased
were also available to the executive, legislative and judicial
branches of government,'' the governor's office said in a
seven-page statement released late Friday.
   Mrs. Mofford, 65, became governor April 4 when elected Gov. Evan
Mecham was convicted in a Senate impeachment trial of misusing
state funds and obstructing justice. Mecham was automatically
removed from office.
   Her chief of staff, George Cunningham, said he had not found any
record of who received the gifts but would request a legislative
staff audit to ensure public confidence.
   Records examined by The Associated Press showed Mrs. Mofford's
gift expenditures totaled at least $50,000 during her last five
years as secretary of state.
   The governor and her aides said the spending had legislative
authorization, but lawmakers and staff budget analysts said they
were unfamiliar with the authorization.
   The state constitution bars the state from giving anything of
value to an individual without public benefit, and state law makes
unauthorized expenditures of public funds a felony.
   House Speaker Joe Lane, who launched the impeachment probe of
Mecham, said he would wait to hear from Attorney General Bob Corbin
and Maricopa County Attorney Tom Collins before deciding whether to
launch a similar investigation of Mrs. Mofford.
   Since Corbin is next in line to succeed Mrs. Mofford, he has
turned over to Collins an investigation of her financial disclosure
practices. That investigation stemmed from an AP report that while
secretary of state she had failed to include a number of her
business dealings in the state-required reports.
   Mrs. Mofford used state funds to pay for such things as
paintings, watches, Indian kachina dolls, clocks, flags and
knickknacks, typically charging them to ``other operating
expenses'' or ``supplies.''
   The Legislature's official records show $2,400 in unspecified
``other'' expenses for the secretary of state was approved in 1980
and $2,500 in 1981. More recently, the Legislature provided
lump-sum allocations for the operation of the secretary of state's
office with little direction as to how the funds were to be divided.
   Cunningham said Mrs. Mofford believed the Legislature had
granted her gift-giving authority and had actually expanded its
scope from her original request for ``visiting dignitaries'' to
encompass Arizonans as well.
   A 1978 protocol-fund statute allows the governor, House speaker
and Senate president to make gifts that promote state interests and
encourage public service. It does not include the secretary of
state, but Cunningham and other aides say the Legislature's
approval of the $2,400 was the equivalent of including her.
   Earlier this month, Mrs. Mofford said that when faced with the
need to present gifts to important visitors as secretary of state,
she ``took care of it myself.''
   The gifts resulted in a public benefit because they promoted
good will for the state, Cunningham said.
   He said the joke-service helped spice up Mrs. Mofford's speeches
and likened it to a reference book. He said the diet food appeared
to be bee pollen capsules manufactured in Arizona that Mrs. Mofford
was using to promote state agriculture.
</TEXT>
