<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-21 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREELEY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A business student may be living proof of
the adage that some people will do anything for a buck.
   The former John W. ``Jack'' Kriss, 23, was awarded $10,000 this
week by KOAQ-FM in Denver after he legally changed his name to
``The New Q103 FM'' and collected as many documents as possible
identifying him with the new name.
   ``I worked on it for three straight days,'' Kriss said. ``It was
a lot of fun and a lot of stress, but the best thing about it is
that I'm going to get out of school debt-free.''
   Kriss, a senior at the University of Northern Colorado, at first
was skeptical of the contest because he did not think he could win.
His roommate, Denton Cochell, persuaded him to try.
   The first stop for the Colorado Springs native was the Weld
County Courthouse, where Kriss had his name legally changed for
$30. It was the first of 53 documents he would secure.
   Along the way, he purchased a fishing license, won a lottery
check for $2, signed an apartment lease and obtained receipts for a
keg of beer and a will.
   Kriss estimates he spent about $50 and 60 hours on his entry. He
also sold his television set to raise $35 for the trip to Denver,
where about 50 other contestants were on hand with documents.
   Kriss _ who said he intends to change his name back in a few
days _ deposited the winnings in a bank account Friday, but not
before giving half to his roommate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LEWISBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dress code at Tri-County North High
School allows miniskirts, but requires shorts to extend below the
kneecaps for both boys and girls.
   Unfair, say some of the school's males. So they've taken the
only reasonable step as hot weather approaches.
   They're wearing miniskirts, too.
   More than two dozen young men wore borrowed miniskirts to school
Friday to show their disdain for the code.
   ``We feel that it is unfair that girls can wear miniskirts, but
we are not allowed to wear shorts that come past our knees. If
they're going to have a school dress code, they should make it
equal,'' said the leader of the protest, senior Jason Gourlas,
whose hot pink miniskirt went past mid-thigh.
   Betty Hawkins, a junior, agreed.
   ``If the girls can wear short skirts and show off everything
they have, why can't the guys wear shorts?'' she asked.
   Principal Carl Walter said his hands are tied.
   ``The school cannot be run as a democracy. ... They're here to
get an education, and those guidelines were set by the board of
education, elected by the people. Since I'm hired by the board, I
follow the rule,'' he said.
   But Walter added he had no problem with male skirt-wearers as
long as they did not create disruptions. He acknowledged that the
skirts were shorter than the required length for shorts, but said
rules are rules.
</TEXT>
