<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainCollision     05-21 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Collision,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed In Collision Of Two Freight Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIR LAWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Conrail freight trains collided
head-on early today, killing a brakeman, authorities said. There
were no other injuries reported.
   The brakeman, who was not identified, apparently had gotten off
a local freight train, which moves freight for industries in
northern New Jersey, ``to perform work on the ground'' such as
throwing a switch or coupling hoses, when the accident happened,
said Steve Lubetkin, a Conrail spokesman in Philadephia.
   The local train was hit by another Conrail freight train from
Elkhart, Ind. bound for northern New Jersey, Lubetkin said. He was
unsure how fast the trains were traveling at the time of the 1 a.m.
accident.
   ``The accident itself does not appear to have been serious in
terms of damage to the equipment,'' he said.
   The train crews were being interviewed early today to determine
the cause of the accident and how the brakeman was killed. Lubetkin
said he did not know how many cars the trains were pulling.
</TEXT>
