<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteinbeckSale     05-21 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinbeck Sale,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steinbeck Mementos Go on Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drinking glasses were the first items
snapped up as author John Steinbeck's personal effects went on sale
at auction here.
   Most of the glasses sold separately to Steinbeck admirers happy
to have any item owned by the late author, who won the Pulitzer
Prize in 1940 for ``Grapes of Wrath'' and the Nobel Prize for
Literature in 1962.
   The highest-priced item, at $6,000, was a painting of Gwyn
Steinbeck, second of the author's three wives and mother of his
sons. The lowest-priced, at $1, was a plastic measuring cup owned
by his son, John Steinbeck IV.
   Many of the buyers Friday were writers.
   ``He was a great American author, and so am I,'' said Jim
Hermanson of Denver, who bought a plain water glass for $16. He
described himself as ``an unemployed writer of short stories and
autobiographical pieces.''
   KCNC-TV editor Jim Syring of Denver found the sale a good
opportunity, ``especially in this area of the country, to get
something that was Steinbeck's without having to go to either coast
_ and just to have something that was his.'' He bought a wineglass
for $24.
   ``This will sit on my desk,'' he said, ``and I'll sit back
occasionally and have a glass of sherry in it ... and remind myself
that that was partly his downfall.''
   Evergreen building contractor Dean Snyder bought a hand-blown
blue martini glass with a twisty stem for $40.
   ``I've read Steinbeck all my life,'' he said. ``And my
father-in-law has read Steinbeck all his life. My father-in-law
also drinks martinis, so he's going to have a Steinbeck martini
glass.''
   Snyder also bought a slightly tattered photograph of Steinbeck,
signed by the author. ``I think it's a real bargain'' at $40,
Snyder said.
   The sale was to continue today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
