<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EastStLouis     05-21 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-East St Louis,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Police Endangerment Charges Against East St. Louis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has dismissed charges that East
St. Louis is endangering its police officers, saying the court does
not have the authority to tell the poverty-stricken city how to run
its police department.
   The ruling Friday by St. Clair County Associate Judge Robert
LeChien was a setback for county State's Attorney John Baricevic,
who had charged the city with eight counts of reckless conduct for
not providing police with properly working cars.
   Baricevic had said it was the first time an Illinois city was
charged with criminal violations.
   LeChien rejected the charges.
   ``The authority over budgetary priority clearly lies with the
Aldermanic Council of the city of East St. Louis,'' LeChien wrote
in his order. ``For this court to engage in realignment of the
city's priorities would constitute judicial encroachment of
legislative power.''
   Baricevic was out of town Friday and could not be reached for
comment.
   East St. Louis Alderman Clarence Ellis said he wasn't surprised
by the ruling.
   ``Being a lawyer, I think he should have known he didn't have
any jurisdiction in this case,'' Ellis said. ``But he may have
helped us. He made us more conscious of the importance of having an
effective police force. He was concerned, and I want him to
continue to be concerned.''
   If convicted on all eight counts, the city could have faced
fines of up to $8,000.
   During a two-day trial last week, East St. Louis corporate
counsel Sam Ross contended no state law requires the city to supply
its police officers with working radios and cars.
   Twenty-six officers testified they were not assigned police
radios or cars, or received broken equipment.
   Witnesses also testified that city officials knew about the
deterioration of police radios and patrol cars, and that about
$10,000 in city funds was spent on such things as newspaper
advertisements, including a re-election ad for Mayor Carl E.
Officer.
   Neither Officer nor Ross could be reached for comment, the
Belleville News-Democrat reported today.
</TEXT>
