<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0554EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     05-21 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Killed In Shiite Clashes, Arafat's Men Dislodge Rivals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias today
pounded each other with howitzers and mortars in Beirut's southern
slums in a 16th day of fighting, ignoring Iranian efforts to halt
the bloodshed.
   Police said five people were killed and 41 wounded in the
fighting between the Iranian-backed fundamentalist Hezbollah, or
Party of God, and Syria's main Lebanese ally, the Amal militia.
   By police count, that raised the casualty toll to 258 killed and
855 wounded since the battle for control of the labyrinthine slums
erupted May 6.
   Most of the 18 foreign hostages captured in Lebanon by Moslem
extremists _ half of them Americans _ are believed held in the
slums.
   In nearby Palestinian refugee camps, Yasser Arafat's Fatah PLO
faction dislodged Syrian-backed rivals of Fatah-Uprising after
night-long fighting, police said. The rival factions have clashed
several times in recent days for control of the camps.
   The Fatah-Uprising fighters, led by dissident Col. Saeed Mousa,
sought refuge today in Syrian-controlled territory on the edges of
the camps, said a police spokesman who by regulation cannot be
named.
   The Syrians have made no move to aid faction, which opposes
reconciliation moves between the Palestine Liberation Organization
led by Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad to end a 5-year-old
feud.
   The thud of exploding shells resounded across Beirut today as
Hezbollah and Amal, Arabic for hope, battled in the 16-square-mile
southern slums.
   Efforts to contain the fighting have shifted to Damascus, where
acting Foreign Minister Ali Mohammed Besharati of Iran met with
Assad and delivered a message on the crisis from President Ali
Khamenei of Iran.
   The official Syrian Arab News Agency reported on the meeting
Friday night but did not disclose the contents of Khamenei's
message.
   Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, chief of Syria's military intelligence
in Lebanon, was also in the Syrian capital to consult with his
superiors, a source at the Syrian command in Beirut said.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Kenaan was
expected to return to Beirut today or Sunday ``to pursue his
efforts with the warring factions.'' He did not elaborate.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, Hezbollah's spiritual guide,
was quoted by Beirut's independent An-Nahar daily today as saying
discussions in Damascus ``may be decisive in determining the next
step'' in south Beirut.
   Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, was
also in Damascus today, waiting to meet with Assad.
   Walters said Friday that the visit was ``not specifically for
the hostages.'' Still, he was expected to discuss Syrian efforts to
free the hostages, the longest-held being Terry Anderson,
Associated Press chief Middle East correspondent. He was seized
March 16, 1985.
   Amal claimed Friday that it had foiled a plan by Hezbollah to
trade an unidentified hostage for arms and ammunition from the
Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main militia.
   Hezbollah and the Lebanese Forces denied there had been any such
deal.
   Syria has had 7,500 troops and 500 tanks massed on the southern,
western and northern edges of the embattled southern slums since
Sunday.
   But its officers say a decision to move in to quell the fighting
has been delayed to give political efforts a chance to arrange a
settlement.
   Besharati's efforts to arrange a cease-fire have apparently
failed, but it was not known when the Syrians might send in their
troops.
   France's Le Monde newspaper on Friday quoted Kenaan as saying:
``the entry of the Syrian army into south Beirut is inevitable.
   ``For the moment, we are simply allowing time for the
negotiators to reach a political agreement, which would be the best
solution for our entry.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, is Iran's principal
ally in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf war against Iraq, a long-time
Syrian rival.
   The Syrians have been alarmed by Iran's efforts through
Hezbollah to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites, the largest
single sect in this country ravaged by nearly 13 years of civil war.
   But diplomatic sources believe neither Damascus nor Tehran want
a major confrontation in Lebanon right now.
   The Iranians have suffered a string of military and economic
setbacks in the gulf and the Syrians, in trouble economically
themselves, need the free oil that Iran gives them.
</TEXT>
