<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Teen-AgePlot     05-21 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen-Age Plot,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Teens Who Stole Blasting Caps Planned To Blow Up
Bridges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrests of three teen-gers foiled an
alleged plot to blow up Illinois River bridges using 2,400 stolen
blasting caps, police say.
   Lt. Jerry Sample, of the Peoria County Sheriff's Department,
said Friday he took the threat ``very seriously'' and kept the
information quiet until after the arrests were made to avoid panic.
   ``The kids who stole the dynamite caps were telling other kids
about it and they made comments about their plans to blow up
bridges,'' Sample said. ``I didn't take it as a joke at the time.
And they certainly didn't tell us it was a joke during
interrogation.''
   Late last week, police arrested the three 17-year-olds _ Kenneth
Johnson, Tyrone Gayton and Christopher Caho, all of Peoria _ in
connection with the May 9 theft of 2,400 blasting caps from a rural
Pottstown site.
   The caps are owned by a mining equipment and supply company.
Some are fused caps, which are extremely sensitive to shock, and
others are electric caps that can be detonated by radio
transmissions, police said.
   The teens were in Peoria County jail, charged with burglary and
theft, police said. Bond ranged from $5,000 to $10,000.
   In an interview from jail, Johnson said he was joking when he
told friends he might blow up a bridge. He said he planned to sell
the caps.
   Sample said it's unclear whether the caps would have been
powerful enough to blow up a bridge.
   ``The experts ... said that if you take 1,000 caps and put them
together, you can make a 10-foot crater in the ground,'' Sample
said. ``Whether they would hurt a steel bridge, we don't know.''
   All but about 60 of the stolen caps were recovered, Sample said.
</TEXT>
