<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-21 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Drench Texas, Eastern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains drenched portions of Texas today after closing roads
and raising river waters 8 feet, while a flood watch remained in
effect over several Eastern states.
   Meanwhile, northern California residents basked in a heat wave
after the mercury soared Friday, breaking records in a hot spell
that sent people flocking to beaches and parks.
   In Texas, thunderstorms brought more than 3 inches of rain to
Kerrville and over 2 inches to portions of Austin. Some roads were
closed in northern Val Verde and other southwestern counties. At
Stonewall, west of Austin, the Pedernales River reportedly rose 8
feet late Friday night.
   Flood watches were in effect for portions of southeastern New
York, eastern Pennsylvania, New Jersey, northern Delaware,
Maryland, northern Virginia and northeastern West Virginia.
   Strong winds from a possible tornado late Friday did
considerable damage to roofs and cars at New Braunfels, Texas,
between Austin and San Antonio.
   The weather was quiet over the Southeast, with clear skies from
Florida to the Tennessee Valley. Clear skies also covered the
nation west of the Rockies.
   Northern California sizzled Friday. The mercury reached 97
degrees in San Jose, highest in the area and surpassing the record
of 94 degrees set in 1942. Downtown San Francisco registered 92,
four degrees higher than the mark reached the same year.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from New England across the mid-Atlantic states to eastern Ohio and
eastern North Carolina; widely scattered showers and thunderstorms
in central and southern Florida and the lower Mississippi Valley;
and showers and thunderstorms from the upper Mississippi Valley
across the central and southern Plains to eastern Colorado and New
Mexico.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s and 60s in New
England, from western Minnesota across South Dakota, and western
portions of the central and southern Plains to the central Rockies;
90 degrees in the south Atlantic and Gulf Coast states; in the 90s
over western Oregon and California; 90s to near 105 degrees in the
desert Southwest; and in the 70s or 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Laramie, Wyo., to 83 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 fair; Boston 51 foggy; Buffalo 59 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 70 fair; Cincinnati 63 partly cloudy; Cleveland 51
foggy; Detroit 56 foggy; Miami 76 fair; New York 57 cloudy;
Philadelphia 59 cloudy; Pittsburgh 52 foggy; Portland, Maine 49
foggy; Washington 63 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 cloudy; Chicago 61 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
67 rain; Denver 46 cloudy; Des Moines 65 fair; Indianapolis 67
partly cloudy; Kansas City 66 foggy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 69 partly
cloudy; Nashville 61 fair; New Orleans 72 foggy; St. Louis 75
partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 50 showers; Anchorage 48 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 71 fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 83 fair; Salt Lake City
51 fair; San Diego 64 foggy; San Francisco 71 fair; Seattle 55 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 cloudy; Toronto 55 foggy.
</TEXT>
