<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Venezuela     05-21 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Venezuela,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-President Says U.S. Would Look Silly If It Drops Charges
Against Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carlos Andres Perez
says the United States would look silly if it were to drop drug
charges against Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in exchange for his
stepping down as Panama's leader.
   ``It would be a scandal,'' Perez said in an interview. ``It
would make the U.S. look ridiculous.''
   Earlier this year, Perez claimed he had negotiated a deal by
which Noriega would leave power, but that deposed President Eric
Delvalle of Panama upset the agreement by trying to fire Noriega on
Feb. 26.
   Perez said the apparent U.S. effort to negotiate Noriega's exit
after economic pressures to remove him failed, ``leaves us amazed.''
   But he agreed that Noriega, leader of Panama's 15,000-strong
Defense Forces, would have to give up power if democracy is to
prevail in Panama.
   ``To create continuity in Panama's democracy, it is convenient
to lower the influence of the military,'' Perez said. ``That
includes Noriega.''
   The former president, currently the frontrunner for Venezuela's
presidential election in December, says he feels he ``could still
help'' in mediating a solution to Panama's political crisis.
</TEXT>
