<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Riot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Crush Bloody Anti-Government Riots In Taipei</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To specify farmers' demands, SUB 4th graf, `The fighting ...
for farmers.' Picks up 5th graf pvs, `About 3,000 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of protesters disrupted rail
traffic, smashed vehicles and hurled rocks at club-swinging police
during 18 hours of bloody riots on the streets of Taipei, police
and witnesses said today.
   An estimated 200 people were injured during the anti-government
demonstrations that were quelled early today. Police said 130
protesters were arrested.
   Local media described the roving riots as among the worst public
disturbances in Taiwan since the Nationalist Chinese government
fled the Communist mainland for this island in 1949.
   The fighting began Friday during a demonstration demanding that
the government provide farmers with insurance and quadruple its
rice purchases.
   About 3,000 rock-throwing protesters clashed with police at the
Legislative Yuan, Taiwan's highest legislative body, before moving
to the headquarters of the governing Nationalist Party.
   At a police station, rioters smashed five police vans and set
fire a car and a motorcycle, police said.
   Riot police used batons and water cannons to disperse most of
the protesters from the front of the police station. Demonstration
leader Lin Kuo-hwa and 11 other activists were arrested, witnesses
said.
   Police chased about 200 remaining protesters throughout the
city, fighting pitched battles in front of government buildings and
businesses.
   The rioters tore out rails at a railroad crossing, disrupting
train traffic for three hours and smashed phone booths before they
were dispersed, police said.
   Police beat demonstrators with clubs and stomped on some who
fell to the ground, the liberal Independence Evening Post reported
today.
   Two policemen, two photographers and four protesters were
hospitalized with head injuries, police reported.
   Another 60 officers were treated at hospitals and released, said
police, who put the total casualties at approximately 200 people.
   Taipei Police Deputy Chief Wang Hwa-cheng said among those
arrested were people who ``posed as farmers and incited the crowd
in an attempt to disrupt the 40 years of development on this
island.''
   Wang did not elaborate, but authorities said opposition
Democratic Progressive Party members and students were among the
demonstrators.
   Presiding Judge Liu Ching-yi of the Taipei District Court said
most of the detained protesters were ``non-farmers,'' claiming some
may have been incited by ``communist elements'' who infiltrated
from the rival Chinese government in Beijing. He also did not
elaborate.
   Demonstrating farmers had accused the government of ignoring
their concerns while focusing on industrial development.
   They demanded that President Lee Teng-hui, an agricultural
economics expert who succeeded the late Chiang Ching-kuo in
January, help improve the livelihood of farmers who have been hurt
by low prices for farm goods.
   Lee urged agricultural officials Friday to help solve farmers'
problems.
</TEXT>
