<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Poll     05-21 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Poll,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Soviets Believe Relations With U.S. Satisfactory, Pravda Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Soviet citizens surveyed in a public opinion
poll believe relations with the United States are satisfactory but
unstable, Pravda reported today.
   The Communist Party daily said 67 percent of those surveyed
described relations as satisfactory, 8 percent said they were good
and 6 percent characterized relations as bad.
   Pravda said in an article headlined ``The Barometer of Hopes''
that it wanted to report Soviets' views of U.S.-Soviet relations
because it had published a similar poll of Americans on May 12.
   President Reagan arrives in Moscow on May 29 for his fourth
summit with Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Pravda said two-thirds of those questioned characterized changes
in Soviet-American relations after the three previous summits as
``significant but unstable.''
   Pravda said the poll was conducted by a group in the Institute
for Sociological Research of the Soviet Academy of Sciences along
with the Center for Study of Public Opinion of the Communist Party
in the Georgian republic.
   Pravda said 1,200 people were interviewed in 12 regions of the
Russian republic and several regions of Georgia. It did not say
when or how the poll was conducted or give a margin of error.
   The poll of Americans published by Pravda on May 12 said 61
percent of those surveyed believed relations between the two
countries are improving.
</TEXT>
