<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zambia-Rebels     05-21 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zambia-Rebels,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zambian Forces Kill 73 Mozambicans, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces crossed into Mozambique
and killed 73 guerrillas who killed peasants and stole cattle in a
raid on a Zambian border village, a government official was quoted
as saying today.
   Lusaka newspapers quoted a government spokesman as saying the
guerrillas were members of the Mozambique National Resistance,
which is fighting to topple Mozambique's leftist government.
   The rebels were blamed for crossing into Zambia on Wednesday and
raiding the village of Tafelela Nsoni in Chadiza District, killing
eight peasants.
   The guerrillas fled back to Mozambique with 28 stolen steers,
the spokesman was quoted as saying.
   Zambian security forces followed the guerrillas more than 12
miles into Mozambique, attacked two rebel camps, killed 73
guerrillas and recovered 22 steers, the spokesman was quoted as
saying.
   Mozambican rebels often cross borders to rob villages in Malawi,
Zambia and Zimbabwe. As a result, Malawi and Zimbabwe have about
12,000 troops stationed in Mozambique, mainly to protect supply
lines vital to their landlocked economies.
   Last month, President Kenneth Kaunda said Zambian forces killed
several rebels inside his country after they attacked border
villages and stole 150 steers.
