<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0474,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Slaughter Nine Sleeping Farm Laborers In Latest Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with temple elders agreeing to
cooperate with government. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `On Thursday ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sikh separatists massacred nine
sleeping Hindu laborers in Punjab state today as the guerrillas
kept up their bloody campaign to avenge a police siege on their
sacred Golden Temple.
   The attack raised to 200 the number of deaths blamed on Sikh
extremists since May 9, when government forces besieged the temple,
Sikhism's holiest shrine.
   On Friday, police fanned out across the northern state and
raided Sikh hideouts in an effort to blunt the wave of violence
prompted by the 10-day siege on the Amritsar temple that ended
Wednesday.
   Today, the committee of Sikh elders that oversees the temple
agreed to cooperate with government efforts to prevent militants
from again turning the temple into an armed stronghold. On Friday,
it had refused to cooperate.
   Committee member Shiv Singh Khushipuri said the group decided
today to restrict visitors from bringing weapons into the temple
complex and prevent people from living in the offices that surround
the temple.
   Sikh extremists in the past have used the offices to hide from
police.
   But Khushipuri repeated the committee's demand that police free
four militant Sikh priests arrested May 12 when they defied a
curfew and tried to march on the shrine.
   He said that only the priests could resume religious rites at
the temple, which have been suspended for nearly two weeks.
   At least 42 people, mostly Sikh guerrillas, were killed during
the siege on the 400-year-old temple. Four Sikhs committed suicide
rather than surrender.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
more political autonomy or an independent homeland in Punjab for
their minority sect. They claim Sikhs are discriminated against by
India's majority Hindus.
   Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of India's 800 million people
but are a majority in Punjab. Their religion was founded about 500
years ago as an alternative to Hinduism and Islam.
   Killings of civilians by Sikh separatists escalated sharply in
1987 and 1988 despite efforts by police and paramilitary troops to
blunt the crusade.
   Early today, about six Sikhs armed with automatic rifles opened
fire on sleeping workers in the village of Gujarpura, about 18
miles northwest of Amritsar, said Chaman Lal, inspector general of
the Border Security Force.
   Nine workers were killed and three wounded, he said.
   It was the third such raid on a Hindu migrant workers' camp
since Tuesday, when 30 workers were slain as they slept at a camp
near the state capital of Chandigarh.
   On Thursday night, Sikh extremists ordered Hindu migrants at a
camp in Amritsar District to line up against a wall and shot five
of them to death.
   The attacks have prompted an exodus of hundreds of the Hindu
laborers who traditionally migrate from the northern states of
Bihar and Orissa to work on farms in Punjab, India's richest
agricultural state.
   Indian newspapers have speculated that the Sikh extremists are
trying to destroy the state's economy by driving away farm labor.
   The latest killings raised to at least 1,136 the number of
people slain by Sikh extremists in Punjab this year. Last year,
1,030 people were killed.
   Punjab has been placed under a police alert. On Friday, 9,000
police and paramilitary troops were sent out across the state to
protect citizens and raid the hideouts of Sikh extremists in three
border districts.
   The order came after at least 38 people were killed during raids
late Thursday and early Friday.
   Attacks Friday included numerous bombings in the town of
Pathankot in the northernmost part of Punjab. Several bombs went
off in buses, and five people were killed. The town was put under
curfew after the bombings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
