<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kenya-Censorship     05-21 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kenya-Censorship,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Video Renters May Get Visit From Censors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has empowered its film
censors to make surprise inspections of private homes to search for
undesirable videocassetes, a Nairobi newspaper reported today.
   The Daily Nation quoted Japhet Kiti, permanent secretary in the
Ministry of National Guidance and Political Affairs, as saying the
Film Censorship Board's authority has been extended to Kenya's
booming videocassette industry.
   ``The public is warned that they will be equally guilty if they
rent videos that have not been cleared and would be liable to face
the rigors of the legal process if found in possession of the
uncleared cassettes,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The ministry said it intended to halt the importation of
``morally decadent, violent and possibly subversive videos.''
   Kiti set a May 31 deadline for all video rental libraries in
Kenya to submit a list of their cassettes. ``Any cassettes found to
be unsuitable will be removed from circulation,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   Videocassettes added after the deadline will have to be viewed
by the censor before they can be rented.
   President Daniel arap Moi established the Ministry of National
Guidance and Political Affairs in March and one of its jobs is
censorship.
   While moviehouse films have been screened by the government's
Film Censorship Board before public showings, videos have not been
scrutinized until now.
</TEXT>
