<HEAD>Thai Temple Opens With Chicago Artifact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand reopened an ancient temple
today even though it was missing a stone sculpture that officials
have tried in vain to have returned from the Art Institute of
Chicago.
   Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn, a daughter of the
constitutional monarch, opened the Khao Phanomrung Temple in the
northeast province of Buriram after restoration work was completed.
   The lintel, or crosspiece over a door or window, disappeared
from the temple in the 1960s and some Thais have charged it was
stolen with the help of the U.S. officials.
   Thai officials pressed to have it returned in time for today's
ceremony.
   The art institute said in February that the sculpture, called
``The Birth Of Brahma With Reclining Vishnu On A Makara,'' has been
on display for 21 years and originally was obtained by a New York
antique dealer.
   It said in a statement that the institute may return the piece,
but that Thailand never proved that it had been stolen.
   Negotiations with the Chicago institute are continuing.
</TEXT>
