<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfRdp     05-21 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wreckage Recovered In Three Pieces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvage workers recovered the wreckage of
a downed U.S. helicopter gunship from the Persian Gulf today and
put it aboard a salvage tugboat, where investigators will examine
it for crash clues.
   The Marine Corps AH-1 Cobra, which vanished April 18 after
day-long clashes between U.S. and Iranian naval forces, was in
three large pieces when lifted out of 130 feet of water off the
coast of the United Arab Emirates.
   Investigators are interested in finding out whether the
helicopter was shot down, as Iran has claimed. Its two pilots have
been officially declared killed in action, and their bodies,
recovered earlier, were flown back to the United States.
   U.S. officials said the Cobra's crew reported in their last
radio message that they were being tracked by a hostile radar.
   One official said it was possible that the aircraft was either
hit or crashed trying to evade fire.
   The U.S. Navy, after origionally planning to blow up the sunken
wreck, decided to raise it ``to better enable investigators to
determine the cause of the crash,'' a military official said.
   A seagoing crane put the wreckage aboard a Navy-chartered
salvage tug and divers covered it with a tarpaulin. The tug headed
for shore, but its destination was not immediately known.
   Associated Press photographer Greg English, who observed the
wreckage from a news helicopter, said there was no evident missile
or gunfire damage.
   He said the helicopter was in three main pieces _ the nose and
cockpit section, the main fuselage with engine and rotor assembly,
and the tail boom.
</TEXT>
