<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Hunt For Masterminds Behind U.S. Embassy Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police hunted today for radical
leaders suspected of key roles in a bomb attack on the U.S. Embassy
in Seoul. Anti-government protests continued.
   Police officials said a search was under way for radicals
believed to be behind the attack Friday on the embassy, where
students scaled the walls and hurled homemade bombs.
   Radical students resumed demonstrations today against the
government of President Roh Tae-woo and the United States after
four days of fierce clashes between protesters and riot police.
Most of the demonstrations were peaceful.
   Police remained on nationwide alert and riot police squads
guarded key locations in Seoul and other cities.
   Students and dissidents demanding the overthrow of Roh have
battled riot police with firebombs and rocks in the streets of
Seoul and other cities. The violence is the worst political unrest
since major riots last summer.
   Investigators said the embassy attack apparently was organized
by radicals responsible for other attacks on U.S. diplomatic
offices and offices of the governing Democratic Justice Party.
   Seven students arrested in the embassy attack were being
questioned by police, they said.
   The police officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
at least 20 other students were suspected of plotting the attack
and they believed a student leader named Kim Chul was involved.
   Kim is wanted for a Feb. 24 attack on the U.S. Information
Service building in Seoul by radicals who exploded bombs and
briefly seized the building.
   Protesters broke windows and hurled several firebombs at the
same building during clashes on Thursday.
   In the embassy attack, students wielding iron bars and hurling
homemade bombs scaled the walls and clashed with police in the
compound. One police officer and two students were hurt.
   The bombs did not cause any damage to the embassy building, but
the policeman sustained blast wounds.
   Anti-U.S. sentiment has been running high in the recent wave of
anti-government protests. Radicals claim the Roh government is kept
in power by the United States.
   Protesters have burned American flags, attacked U.S. diplomatic
buildings and demanded the removal of about 42,000 U.S. troops
based in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, police remained on full alert
today following four days of violent anti-government and anti-U.S.
protests marking the anniversary of a 1980 civilian uprising. At
least 191 people died in the uprising.
   Tens of thousands of citizens and students have been staging
rallies in Kwangju, shouting anti-government and anti-U.S. slogans.
</TEXT>
