<HEAD>Paper Says Two Hijackers Killed in Beirut Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the Shiite Moslem militants who hijacked a
Kuwaiti jumbo jet last month were killed in fighting between Shiite
militias in the slums of south Beirut, a newspaper reported today.
   The Al-Qabas daily, quoting a report by an unidentified European
foreign ministry, identified the men as Qassem Zaineddin and Nihad
Khashman, or his brother Fuad.
   It said they were killed with 10 other Shiites in fighting near
the Bourj el-Barajneh Palestinian refugee camp in south Beirut
Monday night.
   Khashman's mother was also killed in the Beirut fighting, the
paper said.
   Al-Qabas said the Khashman brothers and Zaineddin were among the
nine hijackers who seized a Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 on April 5.
   They killed two Kuwaiti passengers before surrendering to
authorities in Algiers, the jumbo jet's third stop in the 17-day
drama, in return for what diplomats said was safe conduct to an
undisclosed country.
   There have been reports that the hijackers, believed to be
linked to Lebanon's Iranian-backed Shiite Hezbollah, or Party of
God, had gone to Lebanon. But their whereabouts have not been
officially confirmed.
   The paper did not say on which side the alleged hijackers had
been fighting in Beirut.
   But the Kuwaiti jumbo hijackers' demand that Kuwait free 17
comrades jailed for a string of 1983 bombings was identical to that
of Hezbollah-linked Shiites in Lebanon for the release of American
hostages.
   Hezbollah and the pro-Syrian Amal militia have been fighting in
south Beirut for control of the area since May 6. Lebanese police
have reported more than 250 people killed in the fierce street
battles.
   Shiite factions have been responsible for kidnapping most of the
79 foreigners grabbed in Lebanon since 1984. Eighteen, including
nine Americans, are still captives, most of them believed to be
held in south Beirut.
   Al-Qabas said some of the hostages were being held in the Shiyah
district of south Beirut, while others have been moved to the
Iranian embassy in Beirut or to the southern port of Sidon.
   Iranian embassy officials have denied earlier reports that
hostages were imprisoned in the building's basement.
   The daily said that Amal shelling has forced the kidnappers to
keep moving some captives between the home of Sheik Mohammed
Hussein Fadlallah, Hezbollah's spiritual guide, and a Hezbollah
meeting house, both in south Beirut.
   There was no independent confirmation of the al-Qabas report.
</TEXT>
