<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Sikorski 1stLd-Writethru a0485 05-21 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sikorski, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 10th graf, Shapiro could, to include
additional report; trims from bottom.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former aides and staff members have said Rep.
Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., expected them to run personal errands and
to campaign for the congressman, sometimes at taxpayer expense,
said published reports today.
   The Washington Post and The St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch said
in today's editions that former staff members complained about
personal services they performed for Sikorski and his family like
washing dishes, shoveling snow and transporting his daughter to and
from school.
   Staffers told the Post some of these tasks were done during
times they were being paid their government salaries.
   Sikorski, contacted early today by The Associated Press, said,
``No personal requests were made, authorized or approved'' for any
of his former or current staff members.
   He said some aides were personal friends who had ``volunteered''
on occasion to take care of personal tasks.
   Sikorski characterized the reported allegations as
``inaccurate'' and ``a first-class hatchet job.''
   The three-term congressman said the charges had been initiated
by a disgruntled employee who had been terminated from his
congressional staff.
   Dennis M. McGrann, Sikorkski's administrative assistant, said,
``I do know that the Post was informed that the allegations,
innuendos and many outright lies contained in the story came from
an individual who was terminated from the staff who vowed revenge.''
   McGrann identified the former staffer as Rick Shapiro, who he
said worked in Sikorski's Washington office for 7 months before he
was terminated for non-performance.
   Shapiro could not be reached for comment.
   An unidentified former staffer told the Star Tribune that
Sikorski's office has had high turnover since the congressman first
took office in 1983. ``I only know of one or two people who left on
good terms,'' the former staffer told the Minneapolis paper.
   He said Sikorski has a reputation as being a perfectionist and
difficult to work for, adding he sometimes criticizes staff members
in front of others.
   Sikorski admitted, ``I have lost my temper,'' and said he
expects much from his employees.
   ``We work hard,'' he said. ``We accomplish a lot. We work long
hours. That's the way I was raised. ... (But) the relationship is
much more positive and friendly than many people are led to
believe.''
   The Post reported that several staff members and others familiar
with Sikorski's office, most of whom it did not identify, said he
had a member of his staff shovel snow off the sidewalk near his
Capitol Hill home last year.
   Ione Yates, who worked as an executive assistant in the
Minnesota Democrat's office in 1983 and 1984, told the Post, ``Once
I remember staff was sent over to the house to do the dishes.''
   ``I just got tired of feeling like a piece of property,'' Yates
added.
   Sikorski also sent some employees from his legislative office in
Washington to Minnesota to help his 1986 re-election campaign while
they were paid their regular government salaries, the Post said,
citing House records and former staffers.
   ``Legislative staff people do not give up their right to
participate in politics ... as long as they put in their hours in
their official duties,'' said Sikorski. He said if his staff
members did any politicking they ``did it on their own time.''
   The St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch also reported that several
former staff members complained about being asked to complete
personal tasks for Sikorski, such as escorting his daughter home
from school, taking her lunch and tending his wife's dogs.
   ``On one rare occasion, my daughter was injured at school and a
staff person, without asking and without being asked, brought her
back to the office,'' Sikorski told The Associated Press.
   He said one staff member, who was a family friend before joining
the office, asked to help care for the dogs and has been
compensated by Susan Sikorski.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
