<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0417 05-21 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0417,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Reformer Says Hungarians Must Have Greater Voice In
Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Pozsgay calling for reform.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Communist Party reformer
today urged a greater voice for Hungarians in national affairs in a
party conference that has become a showdown between reformers and
longtime party leader Janos Kadar.
   ``Where we have democracy, we can really have renewal,'' Central
Committee member Imre Pozsgay told delegates during the second day
of debate at the first national party conference in 31 years.
   Pozsgay's remarks came a day after Kadar delivered a spirited
defense of single-party rule and blistering criticism for political
change that he said would undermine party control.
   Kadar's assault on reformers within the party clearly was aimed
at Pozsgay and other advocates of political change, who have
expressed support for independent political and trade union groups
that are demanding more of a voice in Hungary's affairs.
   Diplomats have speculated that Kadar would be asked to step down
when the conference concludes Sunday.
   ``The consensus is hardening that Kadar will go,'' said a
Western diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   But he said that Kadar, who turns 76 next week, is a ``wily and
experienced politician'' who still could have firm support among
party conservatives.
   Earlier today, Premier Karoly Grosz, a leading contender to
succeed Kadar, urged party unity but said it must ``rid itself of
ideological prejudices.''
   While Pozsgay did not refer to the proliferation of independent
political groups directly, much of the speech focused on the need
to allow more grass-roots participation in party decisions.
   ``People don't just want to implement party resolutions, they
want to participate in the preparations and policy making,'' said
Pozsgay.
   ``We need greater freedoms to build a democratic socialism ...
we must do away with barriers or barriers will destroy us.''
   Pozsgay has said in earlier speeches that he supports
constitutional changes to guarantee the independence of interest
groups outside the party.
   Kadar's address indicated he has no intention of yielding to
such demands, and was considered an attack on the recent formation
of Hungary's first independent trade union and efforts by students
to set up an unofficial democratic youth group.
   Grosz, 57, seemed to defend the one-party rule, saying those who
demand more parties in Hungary ``do not reckon with the fact that
this is not a matter of decision, but conditional on the real
social possibilities.''
   ``If the party is paralyzed, then the country will be paralyzed
and everyone will be the losers,'' Grosz said.
   But Grosz said the party should break with ``the practice of
secretiveness, self-isolation and inflexible working style.''
   Kadar and Grosz both acknowledged the country's economic
problems, which include 18.5 percent inflation in the first quarter
of this year and an $18 billion foreign debt.
   Kadar, who took power in 1956 after the Kremlin crushed a
popular uprising, increasingly has been blamed for the nations's
economic problems and for resisting political changes.
   Austerity measures imposed earlier this year have angered many
Hungarians, and reformers say economic innovations cannot be
achieved without sweeping political changes.
   The conference meanwhile elected a 34-member nominating
committee to select candidates for the new Central Committee, which
now has 106 members.
   The Central Committee in turn nominates candidates for the
Politburo, where changes are also expected.
   Politburo member Janos Berecz said personnel changes will be
announced in a live radio and television broadcast Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
