<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--ShipRescue     05-21 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ship Rescue,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crewmen Rescued After Tanker Runs Aground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian-registered tanker pummeled
by heavy winds ran aground Saturday and suffered extensive damage,
but all 19 crew members were rescued, officials said.
   A spokesman for the federal Sea Safety and Surveillance Center
in Canberra said rescue workers set up a cable between the cliffs
and the ship to bring the crew to safety. Winds up to 54 mph
prevented a helicopter from airlifting the crew from the stranded
vessel.
   The 30,000-ton Korean Star ran aground early Saturday at Cape
Cuvier, about 35 miles north of the remote town of Carnarvon in
western Australia.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
ship had been buffeted by heavy winds and was heavily damaged on
both sides.
   The Korean Star was en route from Hong Kong to Australia to
collect a consignment of salt.
</TEXT>
