<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Bombs     05-21 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Bombs,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Bombs Explode Around Athens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded in the Athens suburb of
Nikaia early Saturday, and a third was tossed from a car in the
port of Piraeus. There were no injuries, police said.
   All three attacks were claimed by a local left-wing terrorist
group, Revolutionary Popular Struggle.
   The first blast occurred at 12:45 a.m. on the ground floor of a
building housing the Nikaia police precinct, said a police
spokesman who declined to be identified in accordance with Greek
practice.
   At 4 a.m., another bomb exploded in an unoccupied building a few
streets away, the spokesman said.
   Just before 5 a.m., an explosive device was hurled from a
speeding car and hit the Evelyn Bar in Piraeus, which had closed
for the night, the spokesman said.
   An anonymous caller to the left-wing Athens daily Eleftherotypia
claimed the attacks on behalf of Revolutionary Popular Struggle.
   The group has taken responsibility for several hundred bomb
blasts around Greece over the past decade. Last month, the group
claimed two attacks against tax offices in the northern city of
Salonica.
</TEXT>
