<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ritual Killings,0114</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew Ordered To Halt Wave Of Ritual Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have imposed a dusk-to-dawn
curfew in Kwara state to halt ritual killings of women whose organs
were used to make charms, Nigerian media reported.
   Government radio reported Friday that 16 women have been killed
in the last three years. It said people who acquired charms made
from the women's organs believed they would make them rich.
   Two weeks ago police in Ilorin, the state capital, announced the
arrest of 11 people believed to be organizing the killings. The
killings occurred in the towns of Okene and Okehi, near Ilorin,
which is 160 miles northwest of Lagos.
</TEXT>
