<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NIreland-Hope Bjt   05-21 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Hope, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cautious Hopes Aroused of Fresh Peace Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of political smoke signals from
Dublin and Belfast has aroused hopes for a fresh and radically
different initiative on Northern Ireland.
   If successful, it could lead to contacts between Irish Prime
Minister Charles Haughey and James Molyneaux, the leader of
Northern Ireland's largest Protestant party.
   A year ago, the notion of talks between Haughey, the proud Irish
nationalist, and Molyneaux, the equally fervent British loyalist,
would have seemed inconceivable.
   The mere fact that they sound willing to talk demonstrates how
much the political atmosphere in both the Irish Republic and
Northern Ireland has changed.
   The new departure is rooted in the November 1985 Anglo-Irish
Agreement, which gave Dublin a say in the running of Northern
Ireland and a guardianship role over the province's 40-percent
Roman Catholic minority.
   Protestants, viewing Ireland as a hostile, Catholic-dominated
state, bitterly objected to the agreement, fearing the strategy was
to bring them under Dublin's rule.
   But 2{ years later, they are conceding failure to topple the
agreement and are beginning to accept that Dublin, having gained a
foothold through the Anglo-Irish Agreement, cannot be excluded from
any future deal.
   ``I don't think unionists (Protestants) should get themselves
hung up on this shibboleth that they have created for themselves in
the past about the relationship with Dublin,'' Raymond Ferguson,
the Protestant mayor of the Northern Ireland town of Enniskillen,
said in a television interview.
   People like Ferguson talk of an Irish Republic-Northern Ireland
confederation, in which Catholics and Protestants would share power
in Ulster. They prefer not to go into detailed proposals at this
stage, dwelling instead on the need for Protestants to rethink
their attitudes toward the Irish Republic.
   Ireland's and Britain's membership in the 12-nation European
Economic Community will take on major significance in 1992, when
the abolition of most frontier controls will inevitably knit this
island closer together, socially and economically.
   The quest for a united Ireland is being supplanted by a
consensus that unity is impossible without Protestant consent and
that this consent does not yet exist.
   ``There is an atmosphere of dialogue,'' John Hume, leader of
Northern Ireland's largest Catholic faction, the Social Democratic
and Labor Party, told American correspondents recently.
   Archbishop Robin Eames, head of the (Protestant) Church of
Ireland, told a synod Tuesday: ``One can sense a new recognition of
political reality in the air. Is it just possible that we are
seeing the first signs of a new and more hopeful chapter in our
troubled history?''
   Molyneaux, 67, gave the cue this spring when he spoke of the
need for London, Dublin and Northern Ireland to start discussing
Ireland's future.
   Haughey responded by saying: ``Direct dialogue of this kind
would be of great significance and would open the way for political
progress, even if only on a limited scale initially.''
   On May 8, on London Weekend Television, Molyneaux suggested an
``exchange of ideas on paper,'' followed by talks between civil
servants. Would he meet Haughey? ``I don't rule out that at some
stage ... it may be desirable,'' Molyneaux replied.
   The old animosities that used to permeate the language of
cross-border debate were nowhere in sight.
   Haughey, 62, was at pains to sound conciliatory toward the
Protestants, while Molyneaux praised Haughey as an effective
politician and castigated those who still harbored ``a blind,
unreasoning hatred'' of him.
   The overtures have tended to be overshadowed by this year's
upsurge in violence in Northern Ireland, and at this stage, few
will speculate where talks might lead. Haughey and Molyneaux have
been cautious not to raise any premature hopes.
   The Irish Republican Army, fighting to drive Britain out of
Northern Ireland, continues to see violent resistance as the only
answer, and hard-line Protestants may seek to torpedo any
compromise with Dublin.
   Molyneaux and Haughey ``face a perilous course in undertaking
any dialogue,'' commented the Irish Times of Dublin. ``But the
process has to start, and soon. The alternative is an indefinite
future of violence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
