<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Tatars     05-21 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Tatars,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Sympathetic to Crimean Tatar Ethnic Minority</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Ethic, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper painted an unusually
sympathetic picture Saturday of Crimean Tatars and their attempts
to return to their ancestral homeland on the Black Sea.
   ``For tens of thousands of Crimean Tatars, settled today all
around the country, everything connected with their native homes,
the history of the people, takes on a special acuteness,'' said
Komsomolskaya Pravda, the daily of the youth organization Komsomol.
   While not advocating mass resettlement of the Tatars, the
article took a more balanced look than other Soviet media at the
peoples' history and problems.
   It said authorities in the capital of the Crimea, Simferopol,
were addressing the problems of the Crimean Tatars and that ``the
question of the organized resettlement of part of the Tatars in the
Crimea is being settled.''
   The rights of the Soviet Union's more than 100 national groups
is one of the most sensitive issues facing the administration of
Mikhail S. Gorbachev. He has called on the Communist Party's
Central Committee to devote a plenary meeting to the issue, which
includes the recent unrest between the neighboring republics of
Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   Under Soviet dictator Josef V. Stalin, the Crimean Tatars were
deported from their homes on the Crimea, a peninsula in the
Ukrainian republic that juts into the Black Sea. They were charged
with betraying their country while the Crimea was occupied by Nazi
Germany.
   According to the article, nearly 200,000 Crimean Tatars were
loaded onto railroad cars and taken to Central Asia and Siberia.
Thousands died during the deportation, but Komsomolskaya Pravda did
not mention this.
   The government dropped the collective war crimes charges in
1967, but the Tatars were not allowed to return permanently to the
Crimea.
   Soviet newspapers usually ignore demonstrations by Crimean
Tatars, but Komsomolskaya Pravda recently reported on a meeting in
mid-May of about 100 people outside government offices in
Simferopol.
   The group heatedly debated whether the Crimean Tatars, who now
number about 350,000, should be allowed to resettle in their
homeland.
   Some of the Tatars who met outside the government offices told
the newspaper they had bought houses in the Crimea but that
authorities refused to recognize their right to reside there.
Authorities claim no work is available for the Tatars, although
``on the wall of the administrative offices are job announcements
for milkmaids and mechanics,'' the daily said.
   According to Komsomolskaya Pravda, nearly 4,200 Crimean Tatars
have been given permission to resettle in their homeland since
January, shortly before a government commission headed by President
Andrei A. Gromyko announced new procedures on resettlement.
   A government official said March 5 that Crimean Tatars who are
``the most virtuous and well-proven in work and social life'' would
be allowed to return to the Crimea. Crimean Tatar activists
predicted then that only a small number of their countrymen and
only those who toe the party line would be allowed back.
   Saturday's article was not the first time Komsomolskaya Pravda
reported sympathetically on ethnic issues.
   In March, the newspaper accused the Communist Party leadership
of trying to suppress the sensitive ethnic dispute that continues
in Aremenia and Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
