<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Biden     05-21 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biden,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biden Released From Washington Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., was released from a
hospital today following successful surgery earlier this month to
correct an aneurysm near his brain.
   ``I am happier than you can possibly believe to be out of the
hospital,'' Biden told reporters at an impromptu news conference
outside Walter Reed Medical Center.
   Biden was admitted to the hospital May 1 and underwent surgery
May 3. It was his second brain aneurysm since February. An aneurysm
consists of a ballooning of the weakened wall of an artery and is
caused by disease or injury.
   Pete Esker, a Walter Reed spokesman, said the neurological team
was pleased with Biden's recovery and had determined there was no
reason that he could not resume his Senate duties.
   In the operation, doctors inserted a clip on the artery wall to
eliminate the ballooning, Esker said. Doctors earlier said Biden's
second aneurysm was smaller than the first and there was no sign of
any others.
   Biden, chairman of the Senate judiciary committee, appeared thin
but relaxed, with his wife, Jill, and his 6-year-old daughter,
Ashley, by his side. He wore a baseball cap.
   After a recuperation at his home in Delaware, Biden said, he
plans to resume his full schedule in the Senate. That could come as
early as September, he said.
   Biden, 45, who is chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
dropped out of the Democratic race before his first aneurysm was
discovered in February.
</TEXT>
