<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ethiopia-Release 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Release, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0538,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Releases Relatives of Late Emperor</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to CORRECT that one woman is daughter-in-law
of daughter, sted of emperor; adds details and background. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today freed the
daughter and six other relatives of the late Emperor Haile Selassie
imprisoned since he was overthrown in a 1974 Marxist revolution,
the Ethiopian News Agency reported.
   The government-owned agency gave few details of the release.
There was no mention of three grandsons of Haile Selassie who also
were detained after the revolution.
   An East bloc journalist based in Addis Ababa who witnessed the
release of the elderly princesses said the women looked good and
were greeted by relatives in a tearful reunion in the courtyard of
the police headquarters.
   ``They walked out without anyone's help,'' said the journalist,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Those released were Haile Selassie's 79-year-old daughter,
Tenagne-Work Haile Selassie, her four daughters, her
daughter-in-law and another relative. They spent their nearly 14
years of detention in the women's section of the Central Prison in
Addis Ababa.
   Haile Selassie ruled Ethiopia for 44 years as head of one of the
world's last feudal states before he was deposed on Sept. 12, 1974
by a military clique that established a Marxist government.
   The emperor, who had made Ethiopia the United States' strongest
ally in Africa, was last seen alive climbing into the back seat of
a Volkswagen Beetle parked outside his main palace in the center of
Addis Ababa.
   He died under obscure circumstances 11 months later while in
detention and the government buried his body in a secret location.
   The 10 relatives were never brought to trial. Amnesy
International, the London-based human rights group, listed them
among its prisoners of conscience in Ethiopia.
   There had been frequent humanitarian appeals for their release,
all of which the government ignored.
   Haile Selassie also had three sons, two of whom died more than
20 years ago. The crown prince, Merid Azmatch Asfa-Wossen Haile
Selassie, is in his 70s and lives in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
