<DOCNO> AP880521-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GhostWorkers     05-21 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ghost Workers,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Census Shows Sierra Leone Paying 9,000 Non-existent Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Sierra Leone has
more than 9,000 non-existent employees on its payroll, according to
a census ordered by President Joseph Momoh.
   Momoh, who received the report Friday, described the findings as
``sad news.'' But he said they would help his government end the
abuse of government funds through phony schemes to hire
non-existent civil servants known as ``die men.''
   The report said that of the 74,699 government workers on the
payroll, only 65,514 could be located, a difference of 9,185.
   Momoh ordered the census last November after declaring a state
of economic emergency to prevent the collapse of the national
currency, the leone.
   He said then that Sierra Leone, with a population of 3.7
million, was spending $3 million a month on the salaries of
government employees.
   In West African countries, the term ``die men'' refers to
``ghost'' workers, whose paychecks are pocketed by corrupt
employers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
