<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ThruwayBridge     05-21 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Thruway Bridge,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Span of New Thruway Bridge Opens to Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final span of a new highway bridge over
Schoharie Creek opened Saturday, allowing traffic to flow normally
on Interstate 90 for the first time since the old bridge collapsed
nearly 14 months ago, killing 10 people.
   The northern span of the bridge was opened to westbound traffic
for the first time, but alternate lanes of the two-lane span will
have to be closed later on in order to finish painting it, said New
York State Thruway Authority spokesman Arthur D'Isabel.
   Traffic in both directions had been carried by the southern span
of the $13 million bridge since December.
   The April 5, 1987, bridge collapse has been blamed on erosion
around the footing of the bridge piers, which shifted and caused
the steel and concrete structure to tumble into the flood-swollen
creek.
   The new bridge has pier foundations supported on steel piles
driven into bedrock, solid concrete piers and continuous steel
girders. The creek was widened under the bridge to reduce the water
pressure on the bridge supports.
</TEXT>
