<DOCNO> AP880521-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SaragosaAnniversary Bjt   05-21 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saragosa Anniversary, Bjt,0890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saragosa, One Year Later: Memories of a Deadly Tornado</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARAGOSA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two miles north of Saragosa, the flat
cotton fields flanking Highway 17 begin to resemble a vast, dusty
junkyard. Crumpled tin roofs and sides of mobile homes, along with
the occasional battered stove, litter the countryside.
   They are leftovers from the tornado that ripped through Saragosa
a year ago Sunday, killing 30 people, injuring 170 and leveling
most of this unincorporated cotton-farming town of about 250
residents.
   Amid those fields lies Saragosa's cemetery, where 13 victims are
buried. Like the memories of the tornado's survivors, the silk and
plastic flowers that were put on the graves a year ago have barely
faded.
   ``It's a completely different place all the way. The tornado not
only moved things, it scratched things,'' said Maria Paz Candelas,
pronouncing ``scratched'' with a growl. ``It scratched the dirt. It
come out like this,'' she said, making a vigorous scooping motion
with her hand.
   ``You know how a strong wind will pick up papers and trash?
Well, this one picked up rocks. It pulled out mesquites. We used to
have a lot of trees,'' Mrs. Candelas said, pointing out the kitchen
window of her new house at the barren back yard, once covered by
stubborn-rooted mesquite trees.
   At about 8:30 p.m. on May 22, 1987, the twister dipped from the
clouds near the Davis Mountains six miles to the south and skipped
across the fields before slamming into the community center during
a preschool graduation ceremony. The community center was destroyed
along with 61 houses, the Catholic church, the Candelas family's
convenience store and pieces of farm machinery.
   ``For a lot of months, when you came out here it looked like
someone else's place, another world,'' said Tomas Martinez, living
in a trailer while he rebuilds his house. ``When I came out here
(after the tornado), there were no houses, but there were all sorts
of TV satellite trucks parked up and down the highway.''
   Now new, small, boxlike houses, built by Red Cross volunteers,
line Saragosa's streets. The new community center boasts a basement
shelter that can hold up to 300 people. A warning siren on a
30-foot pole stands in the center's back yard. A new church is
halfway finished. The diocese helped rebuild the Candelas Grocery.
   The tornado drove away a few Saragosa families. But most elected
to stay in the tightly knit, Mexican-American farming town despite
the painful memories.
   ``For starters, the people that died _ we miss them,'' said
Rosario Lopez, 26, a resident of nearby Balmorhea who works as a
clerk in the trailer that now serves as the town's post office.
``Every day, when we'd drive by, we'd seen them. Now they're dead.
It's unbelievable.''
   The Rev. Daniel Rojas, Saragosa's parish priest, was so taxed by
the job of counseling survivors that he took a leave of absence and
only a few people know where to reach him, said Corina Brijalba,
48, who lost seven family members and depended heavily on Rojas in
her grief.
   Mrs. Brijalba's son Lucas, a 28-year-old father of three, died.
So did her mother, Amelia Carrillo. Five other relatives _ two
aunts and three cousins _ were killed when the concrete walls of
the community center caved in. Mrs. Brijalba, who suffered a
punctured lung and a fractured skull, lost sight in her right eye.
The vision of her husband, Pat, was so impaired that he is legally
blind.
   After being in critical condition for three days, Mrs. Brijalba
was notified of the deaths.
   ``I asked, `How long did it last?''' she recalled. ``And they
said, `Five minutes.' I said, `Five minutes? My family was wiped
out in five minutes?'''
   Mrs. Brijalba, who recently was appointed the area's justice of
the peace, said she is impatient with the minority in town who have
complained of alleged irregularities in the distribution of
donations. There also have been complaints that the replacement
houses are too small and poorly built.
   ``That irks me,'' she said. ``The people who didn't lose anyone
seem to be the ones complaining about material things. I would have
taken a small bedroom if my son had been able to sleep in it.''
   There have been sleepless nights for many of Saragosa's
children, especially this spring, with its brown dust devils
snaking 200 feet skyward and its rainclouds marching over the Davis
Mountains toward the town.
   One recent windy, rainy night, Sylvia Mendoza's 8-year-old son
and 9-year-old daughter ran out of their room and jumped into bed
between their parents.
   ``Whenever they see a lot of clouds and whenever they see a lot
of wind, they get scared,'' Mrs. Mendoza said, adding that her
seven children don't range about town as far as they used to and
are more quick to go inside when it becomes windy and rainy.
   Mrs. Candelas said she misses the nightly soccer games children
used to play near her house.
   ``I used to get mad because they made so much noise,'' she said.
``They used to come out at night. Now they're afraid. They're
afraid if they come, the tornado will get them here.''
</TEXT>
