<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AbsentGovernor Bjt   05-21 0950</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Absent Governor, Bjt,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Critics Decry Dukakis' Absence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few weeks ago, nine college students occupied
the lobby of Michael Dukakis' Statehouse office and demanded an
audience with the governor.
   But Dukakis was off in Pennsylvania, campaigning for president,
and the only reception the students got was from the Capitol
police, who arrested them. ``Why isn't he here in the state when
there are all these issues to address?'' one of the protesters said.
   It's a question many on Beacon Hill have asked. Some have even
suggested Dukakis take an unpaid leave of absence and turn over the
reins of Massachusetts government to Lt. Gov. Evelyn Murphy while
he concentrates on his Democratic presidential race.
   The three-term governor, who has said he will not resign unless
and until he is sworn in as president, has been on the campaign
trail for more than a year, balancing his Statehouse duties with
those of a White House aspirant.
   ``Fortunately, I have been able to combine the two fairly well,
all things considered,'' he said recently. ``I think I can probably
continue to do that. Certainly I am going to work hard at doing
that.''
   But critics question how effectively he's handled the dual role.
They point to delays in enacting a $3 billion transportation bond
in January and in dealing with recently discovered multi-million
dollar revenue shortfalls in the fiscal 1988 and 1989 budgets.
   There also have been charges of presidential politics entering
into two other major initiatives his administration pushed in the
legislature _ a first-in-the-nation universal health care bill,
which he signed in April, and a pending bill to address
skyrocketing auto insurance rates, a hot topic in California and
New Jersey, the two large states whose primaries close the season
on June 7.
   House Republican Leader Steven Pierce has criticized Dukakis for
``management by neglect,'' and other members of the minority GOP
have used similar language to characterize Dukakis' lack of
on-the-spot leadership.
   ``He's spread too thin,'' the minority leader said. ``I've said
consistently that I have great respect for his energy and his
stamina.
   ``But even a person with a tremendous amount of those things
cannot be a chief executive of a state with 70,000 employees and a
$12 billion budget and a whole host of problems, and also be a
candidate for president of the United States. They are both
full-time occupations.''
   Robert Behn, director of Duke University's Governors Center,
said the question is more difficult than whether it is harder to do
two jobs at once. ``The hard question is _ can you do two things at
the same time and do them both well?'' he said.
   A sitting governor hasn't won the presidency since Franklin
Roosevelt, as New York's chief executive, did it in 1932. But Behn
said that was a different era when less was popularly expected of a
governor and less was required of a candidate to win the
presidential nomination.
   The Middlesex News in Framingham, Mass., has been keeping a
daily attendance record on the governor. Friday's tally showed that
since Jan. 1, Dukakis had been out of state for 121 partial or
entire days, including 31 weekend days.
   When the governor is away, his acting authority passes down a
constitutional chain of command. Lt. Gov. Murphy has officially
filled the bill most of the time, although Dukakis' chief
secretary, Hale Champion, carries out day-to-day government duties.
   However, Dukakis aides and Democratic legislative leaders say
that even if the governor isn't actually in the state, he is still
in charge.
   ``The governor is running the government,'' said Senate Ways and
Means Chairman Patricia McGovern.
   Similarly, House Ways and Means Chairman Richard Voke said:
``Oh, Michael Dukakis very definitely is the governor and in
charge, and I think certainly knows what's going on here on a
day-to-day basis.''
   Dukakis sets the policy and makes the ultimate decisions for the
administration, Champion said. He can do that without being in
Boston eight hours a day, through daily written briefings and phone
conversations and group sessions with his Cabinet and key
legislators, Champion said.
   ``I think this would be difficult to do if you had a governor
who was relatively new at his job, who didn't know the state,
hadn't been around a long time, didn't know all the players,''
Champion said. ``The governor can do it.''
   But Pierce said, ``The governor is obviously here some of the
time and tries to create the appearance of being in charge no
matter where he is. But the sense is that different people
(Dukakis' aides and Cabinet secretaries) are in charge at different
times and on different issues.''
   Stephen Hess, senior fellow at Brookings Institution in
Washington, said Dukakis has shattered some long-held theories by
coming as far as he has in the presidential race.
   ``It was said, until he showed otherwise, that you really had to
be an unemployed politician'' to run for president, Hess said.
``That was the history of Richard Nixon in 1968, it was the history
of Jimmy Carter in 1976, it was the history of Ronald Reagan in
1980 and it was the history of Fritz Mondale in 1984.
   ``So he has shown us that it is do-able. That's the important
thing. The conventional wisdom was otherwise,'' Hess said.
   How well Dukakis is able to fulfill his governor's duties during
this time will be more of a state issue than a national one, Hess
said, adding that Massachusetts residents may be less harsh on the
governor under the circumstances.
   The ``upside'' of this for the commonwealth, Hess added, is the
``prospect of possibly having your favorite son in the White
House.''
</TEXT>
