<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CyanideTrial     05-21 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Trial,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Seeks New Trial in Cyanide Tampering Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a woman convicted in the
nation's first death-by-product-tampering trial has asked a judge
to throw out the verdict, contending a juror's actions tainted the
deliberations.
   The juror, who had been holding out for acquittal, told the
judge she got a telephone call telling her the defendant had
flunked an FBI lie detector test, information which had not been
allowed in evidence. She then changed her vote to guilty.
   The same juror later revealed that she had won a settlement in a
product-tampering case a few months before.
   Stella Nickell, 44, of Auburn, was convicted May 9 of five
product-tampering counts, including two stemming from the June 1986
deaths of her husband, Bruce Nickell, and a woman she didn't know,
Susan Snow. Both died after swallowing cyanide-laced Extra-Strength
Excedrin capsules.
   Nickell could receive life imprisonment when she is sentenced
June 17.
   In a motion filed Friday, public defender Thomas Hillier II
asked U.S. District Judge William Dwyer to declare a mistrial
because of juror Laurel Holliday's actions.
   Hillier noted Ms. Holliday was the only juror who reported
receiving an anonymous phone that said Mrs. Nickell had flunked the
lie detector test.
   Ms. Holliday also failed to reveal the fact that she won a $500
settlement in a product contamination suit about three months
before the Nickell trial began and had discussed the possibility of
writing an article about her jury experiences, Hillier said.
   Ms. Holliday has said neither the telephone call nor her own
lawsuit affected her fairness as a juror. She has said she did not
consider her case relevant to the cyanide trial and so did not
mention it during jury selection.
   She sued Pepperidge Farms Inc. in June 1987, alleging she bit
into a cracker in July 1986 that contained an aspirin substitute
pill. Pepperidge Farms disputed the allegations but agreed to
settle out of court.
</TEXT>
