<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Walsh, the self-proclaimed court
jester of rock 'n' roll, says he takes a light approach to music to
offset what he sees as a bleak future for mankind.
   ``I like to make people think,'' said Walsh, who is here for a
concert Saturday. ``The best way to make 'em think is to get their
attention. The way to do that now is to make 'em laugh, 'cause
everything's so ridiculous you have to laugh, you know? It's the
only way.''
   Walsh, formerly of the James Gang and the Eagles, cited Agent
Orange, environmental disasters at Love Canal in New York and in
Times Beach, Mo., and the nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island
and Chernobyl.
   ``I think we're living in the peak of civilization, right now,''
Walsh said on a Kansas City radio station. ``It ain't gonna get any
better. I'd say in a hundred years there won't be anything left
alive on this planet except insects.''
   However, Walsh, 40, said young people can change the world by
caring and voting.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS victim Ryan White of Cicero will be
presented with his own car this week, but the 16-year-old needs a
license before he can drive it alone.
   The Indiana Independent Auto Dealers Association, which
represents the used car industry, will present Ryan with a 1987
Chevrolet Cavalier on Wednesday, said association President Fritz
Kreutzinger.
   He said he came up with the idea because Ryan deserved something
special.
   Ryan, a Hamilton Heights High School student, turned 16 on Dec.
16 and will get his license June 9.
   He has a permit so he can drive it with his mother as a
passenger until he passes the licensing test, said association
spokeswoman Lisa Kuntz.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the 1988 elections approach, career
women must push for day care, pregnancy leave and equal pay for
equal work, Diane Sawyer of CBS News says.
   ``It is backbreaking to do what women are still trying to do,''
Ms. Sawyer said of those who try to maintain a career and a family.
``It is a marathon, not a sprint. But we have to have help for the
next 23 miles.''
   The co-editor of ``60 Minutes'' spoke to about 1,000 people
Friday night at an awards banquet held by the Career Club of
Metropolitan Kansas City.
   Ms. Sawyer said career women need confidence, stamina and
resilience, qualities that she said can be hard for women to come
by.
   ``Women have so little cultural preparation for the game and how
it is played,'' she said.
   Ms. Sawyer recalled the words of Virginia Woolf, who said that
while men are given the opportunity to develop freedom and courage,
women have to learn it for themselves.
   Ms.Sawyer said women who have found such qualities today form
``a kind of throbbing heartbeat that is going to change the pulse
of this country in the next 10 years.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Philip Hannan celebrated his 75th
birthday and said he will offer his mandatory resignation to Pope
John Paul II after serving 23 years as head of the Archdiocese of
New Orleans.
   Under Roman Catholic Church law, bishops and archbishops must
submit their resignations when they turn 75, although the pope can
act at his leisure and Hannan will remain on the job until a
successor is named.
   Hannan said on his birthday, Friday, he was mailing his
resignation that day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A songwriter has filed a libel suit seeking more
than $11 million from Daryl Hall of the pop music duo Hall and
Oates.
   Attorney Mark Guralnick said the suit, filed Friday in U.S.
District Court, stems from a Dec. 14, 1986, Music Connection
magazine interview in which Hall allegedly defamed songwriter John
Madara, best known for the 1950s hit ``At The Hop.''
   Guralnick said Hall, using an obscene phrase, claimed Madara had
taken advantage of him early in his career, causing him to become
disillusioned with the music business.
   Guralnick said the suit is directed only at Hall, not the
magazine. It was filed in Florida because the federal court here
adheres to the two-year statute of limitations of Florida libel
law, he said. Suits against nationally circulated magazines may be
filed in any state.
   A call to Hall's attorney, Stephen Hayes of New York, was not
answered Friday evening and Hayes had no answering service.
   Among the many hits by Hall and Oates are ``Rich Girl,''
``Maneater'' and ``Kiss On My List.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court overturned
insurance benefits totaling $2.27 million for nine Malibu
homeowners, including actor Pernell Roberts, whose houses were
damaged in a landslide in the winter of 1982-83.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said Friday in a 3-0
ruling that losses caused by landslides were excluded from coverage
in the federal government's flood insurance program to which the
homeowners belonged.
   The homes, in the Big Rock Mesa area of Malibu, lie on an old
landslide that was activated when heavy rains and discharges from
septic systems raised the ground water level.
   The ruling reversed a district judge's order for payment to the
homeowners.
</TEXT>
