<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia     05-21 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Launches Major Offensive Against Eritrean Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has launched a
full-scale offensive against Eritrean rebels to capture their major
strongholds in northern Ethiopia, the state-owned Ethiopian News
Agency reported Saturday.
   The agency said the offensive started near Keren, the second
largest town in the province of Eritrea and about 59 miles west of
Asmara, Ethiopia's major port. It did not give the exact date the
push started.
   The agency said government soldiers launched an attack on all
fronts after repulsing what it described as ``two suicidal
attempts'' by guerrillas of the Eritrean Peoples' Liberation Front
to capture Keren. It gave no details.
   The central government in Addis Ababa has been planning an
offensive against rebel movements in Eritrea and neighboring Tigre
since March, when both insurgencies scored a string of victories
and forced the army to retreat.
   The rebels, who are fighting for a separate homeland, claimed in
a radio broadcast that Ethiopian warplanes had bombed the town of
Afabet, a rebel stronghold, for two hours Thursday. They said six
civilians were killed and 30 houses destroyed in the attack.
   Keren is strategically important as a staging area from which
the Ethiopian military can strike at Afabet and Nakfa, another
Eritrean stronghold.
</TEXT>
