<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Summit     05-21 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Summit,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Prods Senate on INF Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan urged the Senate on Saturday
to ratify the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty before his
May 29-June 2 summit with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow.
   ``This treaty has had a thorough and useful examination in
committee,'' Reagan said in his weekly radio address. ``Now the
Senate can join with me and show both our allies and adversaries
that it, too, wants to help build a brighter peace and better
world.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said Friday that
prospects for action before the Moscow session were fading ``daily
and hourly.'' Minority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., said he was
``optimistic ... but less so than yesterday.''
   Reagan is leaving Wednesday for Helsinki, Finland, where he will
spend four nights before going on to the Moscow meeting, where a
treaty governing intercontinental-range nuclear missiles will be
among the items discussed.
   In his broadcast from the Oval Office, he said he was pleased
that the Senate has now begun floor debate on the earlier treaty,
signed in Washington in December, which covers shorter-range
missiles.
   ``I hope the Senate will provide its consent to ratification ...
in time to bring it into force during my meetings with the general
secretary in Moscow,'' he said.
</TEXT>
