<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Lehder-Merkle Bjt   05-21 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder-Merkle, Bjt,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Prosecutor Gains Colombian's Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor who nailed cocaine
baron Carlos Lehder Rivas livens up his speeches with country
songs, once had the governor and 48 sheriffs calling for his
ouster, and is nicknamed ``Mad Dog'' for his aggressive,
bowl-over-the-opposition courtroom methods.
   ``In the immortal words of James Brown, `I feel good!''' U.S.
Attorney Robert W. Merkle exulted to reporters after Lehder's
conviction Thursday climaxed a 7{-month trial.
   Merkle, who jeopardized his job and drew national attention even
before the landmark trial, stayed on the offensive throughout his
prosecution of the Colombian on drug trafficking charges. It was
the first U.S. prosecution of a such a major foreign drug figure.
   Merkle, 43, became U.S. attorney for Florida's Middle District,
covering 32 counties from Fernandina Beach to Fort Myers, in 1982.
   Since then, the former Notre Dame running back has obtained the
indictments of three sitting Florida representatives, two judges,
three prosecutors and dozens of bankers, attorneys and postal
workers. He once called Gov. Bob Martinez a liar during a trial.
   When some of the state's top powers called for his replacement
in 1987, citizens in conservative central Florida rallied to
Merkle, a father of nine known for strong, pro-family positions and
anti-drug activism. They spurred what Justice Department spokesman
John Russell called the first letter-writing campaign in memory in
favor of a U.S. attorney.
   At the time, the outspoken prosecutor had his own view of the
effort to oust him: ``I'm not sweating it. I'm doing a great job.
If anyone looks at the performance of this office the last 4{
years, it's not just great, it's remarkable.''
   Critics acknowledge his legal skills but question his methods.
   ``He obviously has a great deal of talent. However, there is
another side. ... He can be rude, abrasive and abusive,'' said Jose
Quinon, one of Lehder's attorneys. ``If he had been around during
the Constitutional Convention a couple of hundred years ago, he
would have said the Constitution is not needed.''
   Merkle showed little fear of Lehder, identified with the violent
Medellin cocaine cartel. During one hearing in February 1987,
shortly after Lehder was arrested and brought to the United States
from Colombia, Lehder asked for a court-appointed attorney.
   ``Mr. Lehder,'' responded Merkle, ``Is that a Rolex watch you
are wearing on your wrist?''
   ``Do you know that watch is worth approximately $6,000?''
   At the time, Merkle was in political hot water for his dealings
with Martinez.
   Two days after Martinez, the former mayor of Tampa, was
inaugurated as governor, he was called as a defense witness in the
mail fraud trial of a Tampa insurance agent, Nelson Italiano. The
trial ended in a conviction, but the verdict was overturned on a
technicality.
   In closing arguments, Merkle told the jury that Martinez lied on
the stand when he denied receiving a bribe years earlier in
connection with the awarding of a Tampa cable television franchise.
   The governor quickly contacted an aide to President Reagan and
asked that Merkle be removed. Also tired of Merkle was three-term
Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles, who denied Merkle's claim the
senator told him to ignore reports of Hillsborough County
corruption.
   The two major newspapers in Merkle's Tampa base, the Tampa
Tribune and The St. Petersburg Times, called for his dismissal. So
did 48 Florida sheriffs.
   But the clamor died down as Merkle went after Lehder. Jon Peck,
spokesman for Martinez, said recently that the governor had not
taken any further action seeking Merkle's removal.
   Now, Merkle said he is ready, if it becomes possible, to
prosecute the drug indictment he secured against Panamanian Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   It is also reported, though Merkle won't comment, that he is
seeking indictment of Bahamian Prime Minister Lynden O. Pindling,
whose nation was a stopping point for many of Lehder's cocaine
shipments.
   It wasn't so strange for Merkle to quote one of soul singer
James Brown's hits in reacting to the Lehder verdict. A popular
speaker at civic functions, he often brings his guitar and sings
country songs with lyrics he has written.
   ``Mothers, don't let your babies grow up to be lawyers,'' is one
of his adaptations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880521-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-DemocratsText     05-21 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,710</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democrats' response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address, given by Senate Majority
Leader Robert C. Byrd:
   This is Senator Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia. I want to talk
to you about our national security.
   America's great power is being sapped. We are in danger of
becoming a second-rate power. Why? The reason is simple. Little by
little we are handing over our economic future to foreign
competition. We are giving away the store. We are surrendering our
economic leadership.
   This is wrong. If we cannot afford a strong military how can we
protect America's interests around the world. If we do not have a
strong economy, how can we afford a strong military? A strong U.S.
trade posture is fundamental to a strong military and economic
future.
   For years, the administration has talked tough about trade but
done little. As a result, we have an eroding economic base. Our
foreign competition keeps chipping away.
   Congress has sent the president a good trade bill. It has
bipartisan support. The president should sign the bill.
   But the president does not like a small section of the trade
bill _ the plant-closing provision _ that gives workers advance
notice if they are about to lose their jobs. The issue really is
one of common decency and justice.
   Today, Congress and the American people are still waiting on the
president's answer. As we began this weekend, the trade bill still
sat on the president's desk unsigned. American workers do not know
whether they will get a fair shake. Mr. President, keep America
strong _ sign the bill. Keep America number one.
   All across America people are worried. They see dark clouds on
the economic horizon. They are worried about their children's
future. They know our current prosperity is fragile.
   The president says the economy is booming, the economic future
is bright, there is no need to worry. If that is true, why is the
stock market so jumpy? Why are economists worried about a future
recession or a sudden inflationary spiral? The reason is simple.
The big boys are not willing to bet the farm on the rosy
predictions of the administration.
   It is time to rethink how we look at our economy, and our
national security. If we surrender our economic leadership, we
surrender our economic future and our national security to foreign
hands.
   Our real strength is measured in competence and stability _ not
just in warheads and bombers. Smart students are just as important
as smart weapons. A well-trained work force is just as important as
well-trained army in this era of competition.
   Not long ago the United States was the world's largest creditor.
Today, we are the world's largest debtor. Our treasury is forced to
do the tin cup two step in one financial capital after another. We
have put the power of our own purse in foreign hands.
   Foreign investors are buying everything from our bonds to our
businesses to our real estate. How much longer will we be in
control of our own house? The question of debt has become a
question of national standing, national security and national pride.
   In one industry after another, we are losing our position of
leadership. Good jobs are at stake. So is our security. Ten years
ago we led the world in the memory chips that are the building
blocks of computers and the weapons of war. Today, we are
struggling just to keep up with the Japanese.
   The machine tool industry is a critical defense industry but
foreign machine tools are flooding the American market. This is
alarming, because without machine tools, we cannot build the ships,
submarines, tanks, guns and missiles needed to protect the United
States and our interest abroad. This is dangerous.
   But something can be done. We can remain strong. We can remain
number one. But seven and a half years of borrow and debt _ a
policy of national neglect _ have led to an increasing dependency
on foreign capital. It is time of change course. The trade bill on
the president's desk is one step in the right direction.
   The president has the trade bill on his desk. If he signs it, he
makes America stronger. If he vetoes it, he weakens America. At
stake is nothing less than our economic future and security. Mr.
President, the future is in your hands. Sign the trade bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
