<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Princesses     05-21 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Princesses,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Frees Emperor's Relatives After 14 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Saturday freed seven
female members of the former royal family imprisoned since a 1974
Marxist revolution ended the 44-year rule of Emperor Haile Selassie.
   The women were greeted by relatives in a tearful reunion in the
courtyard of the police headquarters, said an East bloc journalist
who witnessed the release.
   The government-owned Ethiopia News Agency announced the release
in a short statement.
   ``The State Council of the People's Democratic Republic of
Ethiopia today granted amnesty to seven members of the former royal
family of the defunct feudal regime,'' the agency said.
   Freed Saturday were Selassie's 79-year-old daughter,
Tenagne-Work Haile-Selassie; her four daughters, Aida, Hirut, Seble
and Sofia; her daughter-in-law, Sara Gizaw; and Zuriash-Work
Gebere-Egziabher, identified only as a relative of the princess.
   No ages were available on the other royals.
   The release of the seven princesses leaves three grandsons of
Haile Selassie still behind bars. All are sons of Tenagne-Work
Haile-Selassie. They are believed to range in age from 27 to 40
years.
   In addition to his daughter, Haile Selassie claimed three other
children, all sons. Two of the sons have been dead for more than 20
years.
   The crown prince, Merid Azmatch Asfa-Wossen Haile Selassie, 71,
lives in London. He had been in London for nearly two years
undergoing treatment for diabetes when his father's reign ended.
   They princesses spent nearly 14 years of detention in the
women's section of the Central Prison in Addis Ababa.
   Over the years, a number of Ethiopians living in the West have
passed themselves off as the crown prince or a princess of the
Ethiopian royal family.
   The government kept the jailed royals under tight wraps, and it
was only in 1986 that they were permitted outside their cells to
receive regular medical and dental treatment in hospitals in Addis
Ababa. Before then, physicians were taken to the prison to treat
the royals.
   The 10 relatives were never brought to trial. Amnesty
International, the London-based human rights group, listed them
among its prisoners of conscience in Ethiopia, and the government
had ignored appeals for their release.
   In Britain, conservative members of Parliament had led an
international campaign to win the royals' freedom.
   ``This has come about because of the buildup of international
pressure in which we played our part,'' said David Harris, one of
the leaders in the campaign.
   ``It was an act of great inhumanity that they had been locked up
without trial and without charge,'' he said. ``This is wonderful
news and brings to an end one of the worst cases of imprisonment
without trial in modern history.''
   Harris said the princess were held under ``appalling
conditions.'' He said Princess Tenagne-Work suffers from stomach
ulcers and chronic rheumatism, one of her daughters is partially
paralyzed, another has skin cancer and a third has hepatitis.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, reported
``that if the princesses wanted to come to Britain, no bar will be
placed in their way.'' The agency did not attribute those comments
to any government official.
   Haile Selassie, who received worldwide attention in the 1930s
when Italy occupied his country, ruled Ethiopia for 44 years as
head of one of the world's last feudal states. He was deposed on
Sept. 12, 1974 by a military clique that established a Marxist
government.
   The emperor, who had made Ethiopia the United States' strongest
ally in Africa, was last seen alive climbing into the back seat of
a Volkswagen Beetle parked outside his main palace in the center of
Addis Ababa.
   He died under obscure circumstances 11 months later while in
detention, and the government buried his body in a secret location.
   The military leaders who dethroned Haile Selassie, led by Col.
Mengistu Haile Mariam, swung Ethiopia into the Soviet Union's camp
and made the East Africa country Moscow's closest ally in Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
