<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorkingWomen     05-21 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Working Women,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Outpace Men In New England Labor Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three out of five New England women had jobs or
were seeking work last year as the influx of females into the
region's labor force continues to outpace men by a three-to-one
margin, a U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics report says.
   Yet almost a third of working women in New England hold
``traditional female occupations,'' such as clerical jobs or
teaching, while women's median earnings were only 70 percent of
their male counterparts last year, according to the report being
released Sunday.
   ``However, the growing number of women and their increased
commitment to the labor force have consistently narrowed the
earnings gap between men and women,'' said Anthony J. Ferrara,
regional commission of the bureau's Boston office.
   Women's record-high 60 percent participation in the region's
labor force last year rose from 51.8 percent in 1977, compared with
56 percent nationwide last year and 48.4 percent in 1977.
   For the period between 1982 and 1987, 353,000 women and 102,000
men joined the labor force in the six-state New England region,
according to the report.
   Although increases were noted in all women's age categories, the
greatest gains since 1982 were registered among 25- to
44-year-olds. The highest percentage in the region's labor force
last year was women 20-24 years old at 78.6 percent.
   Only divorced, widowed or separated women and black or Hispanic
women experienced a slight decrease in the labor force since 1982.
   In general, New England women's employment figures were higher
than the nationwide statistics. New England men and women, however,
had slightly lower average work hours in 1987 than the national
average. And women's average work week in New England last year was
34.3 hours compared to 41.9 hours for men.
   Ferrara attributed the shorter work hours to women's prominence
in the retail and service industries, where part-time work is
common.
   ``New England woman have participated more fully in the labor
market and have benefited from an extended period of economic
growth,'' said the report.
   The data in the report indicates mothers across the country are
returning to work sooner after giving birth.
   Last year, 52 percent of U.S. mothers in the work force have
children less than one year old, compared with 43 percent in 1982
and 32 percent 10 years ago.
</TEXT>
