<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-GenderGap 1stLd-Writethru a0590 05-21 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Gender Gap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,920</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf bgng, `A CBS-New York' to restore dropped word
Michael.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gender-gap problem that plagued President
Reagan could become an even greater liability for George Bush,
whose standing among women is deteriorating as the fall campaign
approaches.
   The vice president, who used his close identification with
Reagan to clinch the Republican presidential nomination, appears to
have inherited Reagan's relative weakness among women voters
without picking up the president's strength among Democratic
blue-collar and ethnic voters, polling data suggests.
   The prospect that Bush may have a problem winning support among
women in November has campaign aides worried and has sent political
analysts searching for explanations.
   ``Clearly, I think that if you're 16 or 18 points behind, it's
not an enviable situation to be in,'' said Bush spokesman Peter
Teeley. ``Obviously there's a (gender) gap there. And it's probably
related to certain issues that women, particularly single women,
are interested in.
   ``I think once Bush begins to talk about various issues, there
will be some benefit to him and that (gap) will close,'' Teeley
said.
   Republican consultants interviewed by The Associated Press were
nearly unanimous in saying that Bush needs to do something quickly,
and that the gender-gap problem not only affects him but all GOP
candidates this year.
   The current gender gap ``is not just George Bush's problem. It
is an institutional problem for all Republican candidates,'' said
Roger Stone, a Republican consultant.
   Bush ``has got to recognize that women are a target group for
him. And he's got to lay out his own views of parental leave, child
care, and stress his own theme that his experience in foreign
policy is best to lead us to peace,'' Stone said.
   ``If he does those things, I think he will close the gap by
election day, Just as Reagan closed the gap with Carter.''
   A CBS-New York Times poll last week put Bush 10 points behind
Michael Dukakis, with the Massachsetts governor at 49 percent and
the vice president at 39 percent in a fall matchup. It also showed
that while the two candidates ran about evenly among men, Dukakis
held a 54-35 percent lead among women.
   Recent internal polls for Bush and the Republican Party show a
similarly wide deficit _ in the vicinity of 20 points _ in support
among women voters, according to GOP sources who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   These polls also disclose that women are far less optimistic
about the economy than men, suggesting that the current 65-month
economic recovery _ usually viewed as a major campaign asset for
Bush _ may be of little help in persuading many women voters to
vote Republican.
   And while pollsters caution that polls 5{ months before an
election are not to be taken too seriously, the recent results
suggest that Bush's current gender gap problem is about twice as
deep as it was in the Reagan-Bush 1984 landslide re-election
victory. That ticket won a narrow majority of women's votes.
   An election day poll in 1984 by NBC showed that men backed
Reagan and Bush by 64-to-36 while women backed the ticket by 55-45.
In the 1980 election, an AP-NBC poll showed that men backed
Reagan-Bush by 56-36 percent, women by 47-45 percent.
   Why should Bush score more poorly than Reagan among women?
   ``Reagan has far more charm than Bush ever will have. I think
that helps in politics,'' said Molly Yard, president of the liberal
National Organization for Women.
   But she said the Reagan administration has had a negative image
among many women all along. Bush, like Reagan, ``is anti-ERA,
anti-reproductive rights. Those are kind of bottom line issues for
an awful lot of women.''
   Republican pollster Linda DiVall said Bush ``did not have a
gender gap when he ran for president in 1980. He has one now
because he's part of the Reagan team. It is a problem, in that we
need to recognize it exists. And we need to determine the kind of
issues that can be targeted to certain types of women to minimize
the gap.''
   ``It provides a good case for naming a woman as vice
president,'' she added. Some Bush advisers have suggested that a
moderate woman candidate, such as Kansas Sen. Nancy Kassebaum,
might be a good choice.
   Irene Natividad, leader of the National Women's Political
Caucus, said that Bush's poor polling among women ``doesn't
surprise me. This vice president has flip-flopped on women's issues
as he changed from a fairly moderate Republican to a very
conservative one.''
   ``The other reason there is a serious gender gap is that he
hasn't shown a sensitivity to the concerns of the modern women.
Through statements and gestures, he's been showing an attitude
toward women that's frozen in the '50s,'' she said.
   Aides note that, despite the apparent gender gap, Bush has
stressed issues that are important to many women, such as day care.
   But Bush spokesman Teeley conceded ``one or two trips (to day
care centers) is not going to solve it. It has to be done on a more
consistent basis.''
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, a moderate Republican who is a Bush
supporter, said the gender issue ``is also a problem for the
Democrats, but in the reverse. Why do they have a problem with
males? Shouldn't that issue be treated as seriously as the
Republican problem with females?''
   However, he said Bush ``has got to be far more in tune with
younger people's concerns and far more compassionate than Reagan on
issues like day care'' if he expects to narrow the gender gap.
</TEXT>
