<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Haley,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author Touts `Just Say No' Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Roots'' author Alex Haley says the
``Just Say No'' anti-drug program is second only to classroom
curriculum as the most important element in schools.
   Haley visited Springdale-Memphis Magnet Elementary School on
Friday where he encouraged students to avoid using drugs in order
to protect their future.
   ``I think that of the organizations that exist in schools today,
I don't feel that there is any single thing other than the
classroom curriculum that is as important as what the Just Say No
program represents,'' he said.
   ``It's almost a matter of survival. To say no is to protect
one's future,'' the Pulitzer Prize winner said after arriving in a
gold luxury car.
   Haley, who grew up about 50 miles north of Memphis, visited the
school at the invitation of its Just Say No club.
