<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Biden     05-21 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biden,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biden Leaves Hospital After Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., plagued with
health problems since February, was released from the hospital
Saturday about three weeks after he underwent surgery to repair an
artery near his brain.
   ``I am happier than you can possibly believe to be out of the
hospital,'' Biden said at a news conference outside Walter Reed
Army Medical Center. ``I am in good shape and anxious to go back to
work.''
   He also said that though his health problem didn't come to light
until after he dropped out of the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination, ending his campaign may have saved his
life.
   ``I think getting out of the race was, quite frankly, a
godsend,'' he said. If he had stayed in the race, ``the percentages
are I might not have made it down here,'' he said.
   The 45-year-old senator withdrew from the race after
acknowledging he plagiarized a law school exam and exaggerated his
achievements.
   Biden, appearing thin but relaxed and in good humor, said he
planned to recuperate at his home in Wilmington, Del., before
resuming his duties in the Senate, where he is chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee and a member of the Foreign Relations
Committee. He left the hospital in a car driven by his wife, Jill,
and accompanied by his 6-year-old daughter, Ashley, and his mother,
Jean.
   ``There is no reason why I cannot resume all of my Senate duties
with the same vigor that I have before,'' Biden said, noting that
he routinely worked 15-to-18-hour days in the past.
   ``I feel like I could go back now, but they (doctors) won't let
me ... until I build up my strength,'' Biden said. He said he hoped
to resume his schedule in the Senate ``between now and September,
but it's kind of hard to tell.''
   Biden said he had generally followed developments in the
Judiciary Foreign Relations committees, although he had not kept up
with the day-to-day events.
   To gain strength, Biden said he follows a regimen that includes
lifting weights and riding a stationary bicycle. He plans to return
to the hospital in about a month for a checkup.
   Peter Esker, a spokesman at Walter Reed, said a team of
neurological surgeons, headed by Dr. Eugene George, is ``extremely
pleased'' with Biden's progress. ``His overall health is
excellent,'' he said.
   Doctors have found no additional aneurysm or ``other problems
that would interfere with his complete recovery.''
   Biden, who dropped out of the Democratic presidential race last
September, first underwent surgery on Feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm
in an artery supplying blood to the left side of his brain.
   At that time, doctors discovered _ but were unable to fix _ a
second, smaller aneurysm in an artery on the right side of the
brain. Doctors repaired the second aneurysm during a 4 1@2 hour
operation on May 3.
   An aneurysm is a weakened area in an artery. The pressure of
blood causes the area to balloon, forming a blister-like flaw on
the side of the artery.
   To correct the problem, doctors perform microscopic surgery,
inserting a metal clip into the head that locks at the base of the
flaw. The clip remains in the head.
   Further complicating Biden's recovery was a blood clot that
doctors found in his lung on March 13. The clot was absorbed into
the body without any damage, but to prevent further problems
doctors inserted a tiny filter into a major vein to prevent other
clots from reaching the lungs.
   Biden said he never feared for his life, despite the severity of
the operations, particularly the first one in which he said doctors
told him his changes of surviving were a ``little better than
even.''
   The odds improved dramatically for operation on the second
aneurysm, with only about a 1 percent change of dying, he said.
   Biden said he planned to seek re-election to the Senate in 1990.
   Asked whether he thought Attorney General Edwin Meese III should
resign, Biden said he was one of the few people who argued
strenuously against Meese's appointment from the start. ``I stand
by my remarks,'' he said.
   Meese has been criticized for a number of actions, including his
association with E. Bob Wallach, a lawyer indicted in the Wedtech
case.
</TEXT>
