<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Cuba-Earthquake 4thLd-Writethru   05-21 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cuba-Earthquake, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0622,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Denies Reports of Earthquake</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to move up report of quake in Chile. No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's Civil Defense denied that a major
earthquake hit the eastern provinces of Santiago and Cienfuegos on
Saturday, the Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina said.
   There was, however, an earthquake in Santiago, Chile, that
caused no injury or damage.
   ``The only thing that is taking place in Santiago de Cuba are
the Meteoro 88 exercises, which include evacuation drills in the
event of natural disasters,'' Prensa Latina said.
   The dispatch from Havana, the Cuban capital, quoted an
unidentified spokesman from the Civil Defense general staff. The
report was monitored in Mexico City.
   Amateur radio reports monitored in Santo Domingo, the capital of
the Dominican Republic, had said that a strong earthquake hit
eastern Cuba and caused extensive damage and injury.
   Nadin Cury, director of the Civil Defense in Santo Domingo, said
radio reports indicated the eastern Cuban town of Santiago had been
severely damaged. The report was received from the Radio Club of
Santiago, the official said.
   A telephone operator at the Sierra Maestra newspaper in Santiago
said there had been no earthquake. The Cuban interest section in
Washington and the Foreign Relations office in Havana said they had
no knowledge of a quake.
   Geophysicist John Minsch at National Earthquake Information
Center in Golden, Colo., said there was ``no record of a quake in
Cuba in this morning's records.''
   In Santiago, Chile, a strong earthquake caused alarm but no
injuries or damage, authorities said. Minsch said it measured 5.3
on the Richter scale.
   The Seismological Institute of the University of Chile said the
quake hit at 10:28 EDT. The epicenter was off the country's central
coast, 125 miles northwest of Santiago.
   In addition, four small earthquakes rocked central Guatemala
over a period of seven hours Saturday, causing alarm among the
population but no damage or casualties, authorities reported.
Minsch had no record of that quake.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in
populated areas.
</TEXT>
