<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Violence     05-21 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Violence,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Up To 14 Moslems Killed In Mountain Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 14 people were reported killed
Saturday in gunfights between rival Moslem groups in northern
Pakistan, and a U.S. official said foreign tourists were being
evacuated from the region.
   Joanne Clifton of the U.S. Information Service said Pakistan had
promised to fly 94 tourists from the remote northern town of Gilgit
to Islamabad in a military transport plane Sunday if weather
prevented civilian flights.
   In a phone interview from Gilgit, Clifton said Pakistan
International Airlines canceled at least two flights Saturday
because of heavy cloud cover in the rugged Korakoram mountains.
   U.S. Embassy sources in Islamabad, speaking on conditon of
anonymity, said they had heard that 10 to 14 people were killed in
violence between Sunni and Shiite Moslems. Ms. Clifton said no
foreigners were reported among the victims. Pakistani officials
claimed no knowledge of the situation.
   Combined Western sources said fighting between the two groups
had been going on as long as a week, but first reports reached the
capital late Friday.
   Reports conflicted on the duration and details of the fighting.
   They indicated clashes had occurred in Gilgit's central bazaar
and several roads leading out of town.
   Pakistan's 90 million population is mainly Sunni, with an
estimated 15 percent Shiite.
   The rivals occasionally clash, but there was no word on the
cause of the latest fighting.
   Gilgit is a tourist resort 155 miles north of Islamabad.
</TEXT>
