<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sharansky     05-21 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharansky,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharansky Relates Episodes from His Imprisonment in New Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nathan Sharansky, the human rights activist
who was freed from the Soviet Union in February 1986 after nearly a
decade in captivity, says prison doctors once pried his mouth open
with a metal device to force-feed him during a hunger strike.
   ``The force-feeding was intended to feed my body, the torture to
save my soul,'' Sharansky writes in his new book, ``Fear No Evil.''
Excerpts were published in the May 21 edition of U.S. News & World
Report.
   Sharansky, 40, spent from 1977 until 1986 in Soviet prisons,
charged with spying and other offenses, which he denied. He was
allowed to emigrate to Israel in 1986 after his case attracted
international attention.
   In his book, Sharansky recalls how he embarked on a hunger
strike in 1982 because Soviet authorities refused to allow him to
see his family or correspond with them.
   Before they resorted to metal pincers, authorities tried a
number of methods to feed Sharansky whose weight dropped from 143
pounds to 77 pounds. Finally, they arrived with ``more reliable
methods,'' he said.
   ``The handcuffs were clicked on, and the guards held me by the
feet, head and shoulders,'' he said. ``Somebody pressed pincers on
my cheeks, and pushed down very painfully while rotating the
pincers.
   ``As soon as I opened my mouth, a metal object was inserted
between my teeth. The turning of the screw, to which two plates
were attached, began to separate the plates, which make my mouth
open wider and wider. The complicated task of introducing a tube
into my mouth had been completed.''
   The force-feeding continued for three days until prison
officials relented and allowed Sharansky to correspond with his
mother. His hunger strike lasted 110 days.
   Sharansky's book also relates other episodes from his
imprisonment, as well as his flight to freedom in Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
