<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WellsFargo     05-21 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wells Fargo,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Defendant Released On $1 Million Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Puerto Rican separatist accused of
masterminding the $7 million robbery of a Wells Fargo depot has
been released on $1 million bail after being held for 32 months in
pretrial detention.
   Filiberto Ojeda Rios, alleged to have helped plan the September
1983 robbery in order to finance a violent separatist movement in
Puerto Rico, was allowed to leave prison Friday after a federal
judge certified that title to three pieces of real estate on the
island was being transferred to the government, securing his bail.
   ``I have read it. I understand it. I agree to it voluntarily,''
Ojeda said of the terms of his release. A packed gallery burst into
applause as he was pronounced free.
   ``It's good to breathe fresh air,'' he said moments later
outside the courthouse, holding a full-sized Puerto Rican flag in
front of him while family and friends waved smaller plastic
versions of the flag behind him. ``I think it's a victory of the
people.''
   While awaiting trial with 15 other defendants, Ojeda must wear
an electronic ankle bracelet that authorities will use to monitor
his movements. He will live in a Hartford apartment, and won't be
able to leave the city.
   U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie set Ojeda's trial date for
Sept. 6. Pre-trial hearings began in January 1987. Asked outside
the courthouse if he planned to appear for the trial, Ojeda said,
``I do.''
   But, he said, ``I do not recognize the jurisdiction of the court
and principles will be my line of guidance for future conduct.
Principles, honor and particularly the honor of my people and my
country are the elements that will serve as guidance as to whatever
action I take in the future.''
   Authorities allege that the 55-year-old Ojeda is a Cuban agent
who helped mastermind the robbery of the Wells Fargo depot in West
Hartford to finance activities of Los Macheteros, a violent group
seeking Puerto Rican independence.
   Other Wells Fargo defendants are free on bonds ranging as high
as $1.5 million. Clarie had previously denied bond for Ojeda five
times. Prosecutors contend Ojeda is a risk to flee the country.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York last week
ordered that bond be set and that Ojeda be released, further
detention would violate his constitutional rights.
</TEXT>
