<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Ethnic 2ndLd-Writethru a0637 05-21 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Ethnic, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0637,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Leaders Fired in Armenia and Azerbaijan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The official...' to CORRECT that meetings not
reported in Sumgait. Picks up 9th graf, `Armenian activist...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party authorities on Saturday fired the
leaders of the southern republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan in an
apparent effort to prevent more of the ethnic turmoil that has
killed at least 32 people this year.
   The official Tass news agency said Karen Demirchyan, first
secretary of Armenia's Communist Party, was ousted during a meeting
of his republic's Central Committee in the capital city of Yerevan.
   Azerbaijani party First Secretary Kyamran Bagirov was fired
during a meeting in Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, Tass said.
   Both meetings were attended by Politburo officials in charge of
party organization, ideology and propaganda, a sign of Moscow's
concern about events in the two southern republics and its direct
involvement in the changes.
   The Kremlin's No. 2 man, Yegor K. Ligachev, addressed the Baku
meeting. Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, party propaganda
chief and a key adviser to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
spoke to the meeting in Yerevan. Tass gave no details about what
either man said.
   Tass said Demirchyan and Bagirov were retired for health
reasons. But their replacement likely reflected dissatisfaction in
Moscow with their failure to contain the dispute over control of
the mountainous Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan.
   Armenians are demanding that the Armenian-dominated region be
annexed to their republic.
   After a period of quiet following riots in the Azerbaijani city
of Sumgait in which at least 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis were
killed, mass meetings were reported again last week by Armenian
activists and the official Baku radio.
   Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan said Thursday that there was a
``constant danger of an explosion'' in Nagorno-Karabakh and that
the region was surrounded by soldiers.
   Bagirov, 55, was replaced in the job he had held since 1982 by
58-year-old Abdul Rahman Vezirov, the Soviet ambassador to Pakistan.
   The 56-year-old Demirchyan, who had been Communist Party leader
since November 1974, was replaced by 49-year-old Suren Arutyunyan,
Armenia's first deputy prime minister.
   Dissident journalist Sergei Grigoryants, who is half Armenian
and has followed events there closely, said Armenians despised and
distrusted Demirchyan for corruption.
   ``The party must have someone who can command at least a minimum
of trust. That's the only way to quiet Armenia,'' Grigoryants said
in a telephone interview from his Moscow home.
   Telephone calls to the official media and activist sources in
Armenia and Azerbaijan either did not go through or went unanswered
Saturday.
   Grigoryants said the firing of Bagirov also indicated that
Communist authorities recognized they could not control the unrest
until he was removed.
   Armenians have accused Azerbaijani leaders of encouraging the
rioting in Sumgait. Selection of a diplomat to be party leader
indicated a deep distrust by Moscow of officials in Baku.
   The rioting in Sumgait began Feb. 28, about two weeks after
massive demonstrations in Yerevan and in Nagorno-Karabakh.
Nagorno-Karabakh was joined to Azerbaijan in 1923, in the early
days of Soviet power.
   Central authorities in February rejected Armenia's demands to
change jurisdiction over the region. Instead they announced a
longterm program of social and economic development for the region.
   The first of more than 80 people brought to trial in the Sumgait
riots, Azerbaijani metalworker Talekh Salekh Ogli Ismailov, was
found guilty Monday of murder and sentenced to the maximum 15 years
in prison.
   Armenian sources said 150,000 people gathered in Yerevan Tuesday
to stress that such convictions were not a solution to the area's
ethnic problems.
   About 30 Armenians gathered across the street from the Soviet
Supreme Court in Moscow on Friday to demand the trial of the other
suspects in the rioting be open to Armenian observers and broadcast
on television.
   Gorbachev had singled out Demirchyan for personal criticism for
the republic's poor economic performance.
   Tass said Vezirov, the new Azerbaijani party leader, graduated
from an industrial institute and worked in the republic's Young
Communist League from 1951 to 1970. He was involved in other party
work until 1976, when he entered the diplomatic service.
   He was consul-general in Calcutta, India, ambassador in Nepal
and then in Pakistan.
   Arutyunyan graduated from a veterinary school and joined the
Communist Party at the age of 22, Tass said.
   He graduated from the V.I. Lenin military-political academy in
Moscow and obtained a degree in philosophy, it said.
   Arutyunyan was a secretary of the Young Communist organization
and began working in the Communist Party Central Committee in 1978.
</TEXT>
