<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GatesPlea     05-21 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gates Plea,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conrail Engineer to Plead Guilty on Federal Obstruction Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Conrail engineer who was at the
controls of a train involved in the worst crash in Amtrak history
has agreed to plead guilty to a charge of conspiring to obstruct
investigation of the crash, his lawyer says.
   Fred Warren Bennett, a federal public defender, said Friday that
former engineer Ricky Gates would plead guilty in exchange for the
dropping of three other federal charges against him.
   Sixteen people were killed and 175 injured Jan. 4, 1987, when
Gates ran a string of Conrail locomotives past a signal and into
the path of a speeding Amtrak passenger train near Chase.
   As part of the plea bargain reached about 10 days earlier,
Bennett said, federal prosecutors would recommend that Gates
receive a five-year sentence to be served consecutively to his
five-year sentence on state charges for manslaughter by locomotive.
   He could have been fined $250,000 on the federal charge as well.
   Gates, 34, and brakeman Edward Cromwell were accused of lying to
National Transportation Safety Board investigators and denying that
they had smoked marijuana while operating the train. The indictment
says Gates also lied about having tested cab signals to make sure
they were in working order.
   He had been scheduled for trial beginning June 13 on the federal
charges. He was indicted March 31, two days after he received the
five-year state sentence and a $1,000 fine.
   Gates is scheduled to plead guilty at his rearraignment
Wednesday morning before U.S. District Judge Norman P. Ramsey in
Baltimore.
   Cromwell received state and federal immunity for his testimony.
</TEXT>
