<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NakedTeens     05-21 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Naked Teens,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naked Teens Rescued From Rising Floodwaters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age couple doffed their clothes
to go for a swim were stranded for nearly six hours alongside a
flooded creek when rising water forced them from their car,
authorities said Saturday.
   Rescuers finally reached the teen-agers, who had taken shelter
in some trees atop a mound, and brought them to safety, said Steve
Allen, director of the Berkeley County Office of Emergency
Services. The couple was unhurt.
   The two were naked except for a water-soaked blanket the girl
had wrapped around herself, said Friendship Fire Chief Alvin
``Bud'' Manuel.
   ``He said they were going to swim,'' Manuel said. ``I didn't
even see their clothes.''
   The teen-agers, who were not identified, were trapped near
Opequon Creek early Friday when water from the swollen stream
started seeping into their car, which was parked on a dirt mound,
Allen said. They left the car and climbed to higher ground.
   A rescue helicopter was dispatched but was ordered to return
because of water and weather conditions, Allen said. Members of the
Friendship Fire Co. water rescue unit of Harpers Ferry finally
reached the couple, Allen said.
   Manuel said he guessed the girl to be in her early teens and the
boy to be ``17 or 18.''
</TEXT>
