<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     05-21 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Blast Kills British Soldier</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NIreland-Hope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier and his dog
were killed Saturday by a bomb that went off as they searched for
explosives near the Irish border, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed reponsibility, police said.
   The 28-year-old soldier was leading a search patrol for
explosives in the county of South Armagh, where a 1,400-pound IRA
bomb was discovered Thursday.
   Police said it appeared the soldier or his dog stepped on a bomb
hidden in a field about 10 yards from the road.
   The soldier was identified as Cpl. Derek Hayes.
   Five people in two passing cars sustained minor injuries in the
explosion, but police said it was not immediately clear how they
were hurt.
   Security forces are the main targets of the outlawed IRA in its
guerrilla campaign to oust the British from Northern Ireland and
unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mostly Roman
Catholic Irish Republic.
   There were no immediate details on how the IRA claimed
responsibility for the bomb.
</TEXT>
