<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-21 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire's four beloved beagles got
more than scraps and bones in the woman's will: they inherited
$75,000 to keep them in style.
   Tony, Libby, Cissy and Christina belonged to Rebecca Knight, who
died May 12 at the age of 82.
   ``They were like her children,'' Barney West III, Mrs. Knight's
great-nephew, told the News and Observer of Raleigh last week.
``She would cook for them and take extraordinary care of them. I've
heard of fish dinners they would have together _ maybe not shrimp
and lobster _ but as I said, they were her children.''
   Mrs. Knight treated the dogs to Sunday drives in her
mint-condition Volkswagen Beetle. She shopped at farmers markets,
seeking out the best apples and strawberries for the pups.
   The will set aside $75,000 of Mrs. Knight's $2.1 million estate
for two of her friends, William and Elizabeth Davis of Creedmoor,
to care for the animals.
   The will says the couple should use the money for a permanent
addition to their home for the dogs to occupy. Besides the room,
the will calls for an outdoor exercise area and a screened porch
where the dogs can enjoy the sun.
   The Davises haven't started building the new digs yet, but plans
are under way.
   ``We turned a bedroom into a temporary place for them,'' Mrs.
Davis said, ``and we're going to cut a doggy door in the side of
the wall so they can get out and exercise. We're still talking to
contractors, though, about what needs to be built.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may sound like udder bull, but a dairy
specialist says a computer dating service that matches compatible
bovines can yield a herd that's the cream of the crop.
   Michael Tomaszewski, a dairy expert with the Texas Agriculture
Extension Service in Dallas, developed the program called Herdmate.
   Any farmer who has a personal computer can use it to match cows
with bulls to improve a dairy herd, Tomaszewski told the Dallas
Times Herald last week.
   Tomaszewski says his purpose is not to bring romance to the
bovines, but to help dairy farmers produce the best offspring they
can.
   For instance a farmer owning a cow with a particular weak trait
can find a bull with a strong, offsetting characteristic by using
Herdmate to locate available mates, he said.
   The software program debuted in late 1986 after development by
Tomaszewski and other agricultural specialists. This year ``there's
been more interest than in the past,'' he said.
   Next in the evolution of Tomaszewski's service will be Version
2, he says. It will allow farmers to scrutinize bulls even more
than now.
   ``Just like a stockbroker will analyze a portfolio of stocks,
farmers will be able to do the same thing with bulls,'' he says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ever since a bingo game opened two weeks ago in
downtown Dallas during the lunch hour, it has attracted a full
house of almost 200 people a day.
   Circus Bingo, with eight daily games between 11:30 a.m. and 1:30
p.m. and prizes ranging from $25 to $500, caters to a downtown
lunchtime crowd more willing to spend $5 trying their luck with
bingo than grabbing a burger.
   ``People are looking for a different activity to do during their
lunch break. A lot of people enjoy bingo because it gives them
something fun to do and at the same time it can win them money,''
manager Kurt Prather said.
   A second-floor room for non-smokers is scheduled to open up next
week, he said.
   Christopher Exline sat hunched over the bingo table Thursday,
tie askew, suit jacket slung over the back of his chair, briefcase
at his feet.
   ``When you're in commercial real estate in this market, any
chance you have to make $500 is great,'' he said, adjusting his
horn-rimmed glasses.
</TEXT>
