<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Aslan     05-21 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Aslan,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientist Who Promoted Youth Drug Dies At 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ana Aslan, the Romanian scientist who
developed a treatment that held out the vision of restored youth,
has died, Romania's official Agerpres news agency reported
Saturday. She was 91.
   The report monitored in Vienna said Ms. Aslan died Friday in the
Romanian capital of Bucharest. It did not give the cause of death.
   ``Romanian medical research experiences a great loss,'' the
report said.
   Ms. Aslan was the inventor of a treatment for biological and
psychic regeneration. She was dubbed ``Lady Gerovital'' after the
drug she patented. Ms. Aslan believed that old age must be fought
like a disease and that drugs can lengthen the life span and even
bring new vitality.
   A member of the Academy of Sciences of New York, she devised the
``Gerovital H-3'' treatment, which was reported to have favorable
results in a wide range of symptoms, from tightening skin to
reactivating brain functions and repigmentation of hair.
   Wealthy foreigners were among the callers at her Institute of
Geriatrics near Bucharest.
   Despite some skeptics in the medical world, Western
pharmaceutical companies are competing on a vast market with
``youth pills'' claimed to be based on her research.
   Hundreds of thousands of people have received the treatment in
Romania and abroad. Romanian doctors said among them were former
Chinese leaders Mao Tse-tung, former French president Charles de
Gaulle and comic genius Charlie Chaplin.
   The cures of Ms. Aslan have brought Communist Romania millions
of dollars.
   ``People do not live long enough,'' she once said. ``All of us
ought to be able to live at least 100 years.''
   The report did not mention survivors or funeral arrangements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
