<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cyprus-UNShootout     05-21 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus-UN Shootout,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Cypriot Killed In Shootout With U.N. Soldier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH PANOSSIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Austrian soldier of the U.N. force in
Cyprus killed a Turkish Cypriot in the village of Pyla on Saturday
in the first fatal shootout involving the peacekeepers since their
arrival on the island 24 years ago.
   Cyprus television said the Turkish Cypriot man, Hussein Kafa,
shot and wounded the Austrian soldier. The peacekeeper fired back
three pistol shots, killing Kafa, who was in his 60s.
   The Austrian soldier, who was not identified, was rushed to
Larnaca Hospital, three miles from Pyla.
   Pyla, 15 miles southeast of Nicosia, is the only village where
Turkish Cypriots and Greek Cypriots still live together despite the
14-year-old partition of the island.
   The state-run television said Pyla was tense after the incident
and that Turkish Cypriots armed with handguns, including Kafa's
30-year-old son Saleh, were ``threatening'' the Austrian post.
   The elder Kafa, the state-run television reported, crossed into
the U.N. force's zone of operations in the village, claiming he
wanted to mend a wall surrounding his farm. When two Austrian
soldiers ordered him out of the buffer zone, he drew a pistol and
fired at one of them.
   U.N. spokesman Charles Gaulkin confirmed an Austrian soldier was
wounded in a shootout in Pyla, but said he had no information about
the circumstances and could not identify the wounded soldier.
   The eight-nation, 2,300-strong U.N. force in Cyprus known as
UNFICYP has been in Cyprus since 1964. The Austrian contingent has
300 men.
   The other countries that contribute to UNFICYP are Denmark,
Britain, Canada, Sweden, Australia, Finland and Ireland.
   The U.N. force runs 143 observation posts along a 112-mile
``Green Line'' that has divided the island since Turkish troops
invaded the northern third in 1974 in the wake of an abortive Greek
Cypriot coup aimed at uniting the island with Greece.
   Pyla, with a population of 750 Greek Cypriots and 350 Turkish
Cypriots, has been an attraction for tourists who crowd its fish
tavern at weekends.
   Officials said that in March the elder Kafa kidnapped a Greek
Cypriot waiter and his Maltese girlfriend and rammed his minibus
into a number of Greek-owned cars because the Greek-Cypriot police
took his son, Saleh, into custody.
   The waiter and his girlfriend were rescued by a British patrol
while being driven through the nearby British base of Dhekelia on
the Turkish side of the Green Line.
   Saleh Kafa had been charged with contempt of court for refusing
to demolish a shop he had built in the village, police said. He was
later released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
