<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     05-21 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Unit Of Soviet Soldiers Reaches Home Turf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second Soviet military unit withdrawing from
Afghanistan arrived back in the border town of Termez on Saturday,
the Tass news agency said.
   Local officials, youth delegations, friends and relatives
greeted the convoy of rifle troops as they arrived in the border
town of Termez in the Soviet republic of Uzbekistan, the official
news agency said.
   The troops continued on to an unspecified base after resting
briefly. Tass did not say how many soldiers were in the unit nor
where they had been based in Aghanistan.
   The Soviets are pulling out under an agreement signed in Geneva
on April 14.
   They entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replacing one
pro-Soviet government with another. They remained to fight rebels
backed by the United States, China, Pakistan and other countries.
   A Soviet media official confirmed for the first time Thursday
that between 12,000 and 15,000 Soviet soldiers had been killed in
the fighting in Afghanistan.
   The first 1,300 soldiers to leave, another rifle convoy, crossed
the border Wednesday. They had been stationed in the eastern city
of Jalalabad.
   An estimated 115,000 Soviet soldiers have been serving in
Afghanistan, but under the Geneva agreement they must all leave
within nine months.
</TEXT>
