<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoPhones     05-21 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Phones,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Bell Uses U.S. Mail To Reach Suburban Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Bell is using the mail to reach
thousands of customers in six western suburbs to make sure service
is back after a two-week disruption by a fire at a switching
station.
   Illinois Bell spokesman Dick Hill said that as of Saturday
almost all of the 35,000 customers who lost dial tones after the
May 8 fire have had partial service restored, although there were
still some ``spotty problems'' with about 200 to 300 lines still
not working.
   Those people should have limited service restored by the end of
the weekend.
   To make sure they didn't miss anyone, Illinois Bell officials
took the unusual step of mailing postcards Thursday to all 35,000
customers in the Hinsdale area asking those still without phone
service or with phone-related problems to contact the company.
   ``We thought this was about the fastest and ... the most
effective way we could think of to get the message out,'' Hill
said. ``The Postal Service has been very helpful, giving it special
handling. We couldn't possibly have called all 35,000 of them.''
   The service disruptions have caused millions of dollars in
business losses throughout the western suburbs.
   Hill said there were still problems restoring normal access to
long-distance lines routed through the Hinsdale switching station.
   ``There is long-distance service available, but it's not up to
the normal levels.'' Hill said normal long-distance service should
be restored to the region during the upcoming week.
   ``Now it's settling down to be a job to finish the installation
of the new switching equipment,'' he said.
   About 250 Bell employees were working around the clock through
the weekend to install new state-of-the-art switching equipment at
the Hinsdale center, Hill said.
   ``We're down to the very last ones,'' Hill said, ``but we're not
sure how many of the 35,000 lines we restored are working
properly.''
</TEXT>
