<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-MasonPaternity     05-21 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mason Paternity,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Ordered To Jail For Violating Paternity Case Gag Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who won a paternity suit against comedian
Jackie Mason last month was in jail Saturday for violating a gag
order, but friends contended that the comic broke the order first.
   Circuit Judge John Gale on Wednesday ordered Ginger Reiter to
serve a 30-day sentence for giving interviews to several Miami
newspapers and television stations in violation of his court order.
   Ms. Reiter, 37, an actress and playwright who also owns a
struggling striptease-telegram service, was booked into the Dade
Women's Detention Center on Thursday night.
   Her 2-year-old daughter, Sheba, was placed in the custody of the
child's maternal grandmother, Mirian Oliver, of Hallandale.
   Mason is appearing on Broadway in his hit one-man show, ``The
World According to Me!'' Ms. Reiter testified that she had had an
intermittent relationship with the star for more than a decade.
   Last month, Gale declared Mason to be the father of Sheba,
citing the resemblance between the two and a blood test that showed
a 99.94 percent probability that Mason was the father. Gale removed
a gag order and then reinstated it at the insistence of Mason's
lawyers.
   Ms. Reiter's friends and co-stars in her autobiographical
musical, ``Oh Jackie, Oh!'', which plays in community centers in
southern Florida, criticized the sentence.
   Tony Ross, an actor in the musical, said Mason violated the gag
order first when he gave a May 2 interview to the New York Post.
   Mason's attorney, Raoul Lionel Felder, said Mason gave the
interview to offer a response to the paternity suit.
   ``Jackie Mason doesn't put people in jail. The judge puts people
in jail,'' Felder said.
</TEXT>
