<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BlantonRuns     05-21 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blanton Runs,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor, Convicted of Extortion, Announces Race for
Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wrier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton, who served time
in a federal prison and whose administration was riddled by
political scandal, announced Saturday he is running for Congress.
   ``I have been battered. I have been beaten and I have been
burned. But my grandfather taught me on the farm sharpening plow
points ... that the more you heat it and the more you beat it the
sharper and the tougher it gets,'' Blanton said.
   ``I've been that route and I hope it works the same way on me as
it did on that hot steel.''
   Blanton was convicted of extortion and mail fraud in 1981 and
spent two years in federal prison. But the mail fraud conviction
has since been overturned and he is appealing the extortion and
conspiracy charges.
   In announcing his candidacy for the Democratic nomination from
the 8th Congressional District, Blanton painted himself as a victim
of a Republican Justice Department lusting to bring down a
Democratic governor.
   ``I want to show that because I have been mistreated, falsely
accused, been made a political prisoner in the country I love, that
I don't give up on my love for this country,'' he said.
   Blanton, 58, is running for the congressional seat being vacated
by Rep. Ed Jones, a popular Democrat who has represented the
largely rural west Tennessee district since 1968.
   Tennessee's governor from 1975 to 1979, Blanton was convicted of
taking part in a scheme to sell state liquor licenses, and his
administration was rocked by allegations that prison inmates bought
their way to freedom.
   Two former Blanton aides also went to prison in the liquor
license conspiracy, and two other aides and a third man went to
prison in the so-called ``clemency for cash'' scandal.
   The former governor's mail fraud conviction was recently
overturned because of a Supreme Court decision restricting the
definition of that offense. Blanton is appealing his conviction on
extortion and conspiracy charges, and his citizenship rights were
restored by a federal court last fall.
   ``I believe that the people of this district, this state and
this nation realize that what happened to me was purely
political,'' he said.
   Will Jerry Pillow, a Gibson County farmer who joined about 50
Blanton supporters for the campaign announcement at a Jackson
motel, described the former governor as ``honest and humble.''
   ``This state owes him an apology, and a vote for him for
Congress would be a step in the right direction,'' Pillow said.
   Blanton, who represented Tennessee's 7th Congressional District
from 1967 to 1972, lives in Nashville, where he sells prefabricated
industrial buildings. He said he plans to move soon to Madison
County in west Tennessee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880521-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1833EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-21 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jerusalem, West Bank Set to Open Palestinian Public Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Saturday prepared to reopen public
schools for Palestinians in Jerusalem and the occupied West Bank
that were shut down when attendance fell sharply during widespread
protests in February.
   About 16,000 elementary and high school students in Jerusalem
were due back to 31 Palestinian public schools scheduled to reopen
Sunday, said municipal spokesman Menachem Raboy.
   ``All in all, it's an experiment. If they don't come, we can't
teach them,'' Raboy said in a telephone interview.
   Jerusalem's private schools, where the majority of Palestinian
children learn, remain shut down.
   Public schools in the West Bank are due to reopen Monday.
   In other developments, Israel television reported troops opened
fire on Palestinian protesters in Nablus on Saturday, wounding two.
The army did not confirm the report.
   Arab storekeepers shuttered their shops, and cars and buses
disappeared from the streets as Palestinians observed a general
strike Saturday throughout the occupied territories.
   The army imposed a curfew on districts of Gaza City after
soldiers clashed with protesters Saturday morning. According to
Arab reports, demonstrators stoned Israeli soldiers in three
refugee camps and the town of Rafah in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Raboy said education officials decided to reopen the schools
after receiving requests from Palestinian parents and teachers who
did not want to see their children lose a year of schooling.
   ``We have said all along that as soon as we feel there are
enough appeals and a reasonable degree of certainty the schools
will work, we will open them,'' Raboy said.
   Students will study into the summer and have one hour a day and
one day a week added to their timetable, Raboy said.
   Raboy said the municipality shut down the schools in February
after attendance dropped below 25 percent as students protested the
Israeli occupation. At the time, police deployment in the city was
doubled to 1,500 to quell rioting in Arab neighborhoods.
   Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip in the 1967 Middle
East war and annexed Arab east Jerusalem a few days later.
   The West Bank schools became a focal point of protests during
the first stage of the Palestinian uprising which began on Dec. 8.
   According to U.N. figures, 191 Palestinians have died in the
unrest. Two Israelis have also been killed.
   Seventeen left-wing protest groups banded together Saturday to
demonstrate in front of jails where Palestinians are being held by
the army.
   Iris Singer, a spokeswoman for the groups, said the
demonstrators were protesting against the mass arrests and
administrative detentions since the uprising began. She said they
were also protesting poor prison conditions.
   According to estimates by left-wing legislator Deddi Zucker,
10,000 Palestinians have been arrested since the uprising began,
1,900 of them without charges.
   Singer said the army turned away 56 protesters on their way to
Farah prison, near Nablus in the occupied West Bank. The protesters
planned to meet with Palestinian villagers and demonstrate outside
the prison.
   An Arab reporter said the office of a chartered accountant in
Hebron was firebombed in a bid to prevent Palestinian merchants
from paying taxes to Israeli authorities. Arab merchants pay their
taxes to the military government through accountants.
   The reporter said it was the third time in the past 10 days an
accountant's office has been burned down. An army spokeswoman said
she had no information about the attack.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz called on the Israeli
government to accept an international peace conference and be ready
to yield war-won territory.
   In an Israel Television interview broadcast Saturday, Shultz
said Israel must negotiate ``territory for peace. ... If you say no
... then there is no Arab partner that wants to come and negotiate,
because they say, what is there to negotiate.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has rejected the proposal for an
international peace conference on the grounds that Israel would be
isolated in a hostile forum and forced to make dangerous
concessions. He opposes giving up any of the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
