<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreaknessNewspage     05-21 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preakness Newspage,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Risen Star Upsets Filly Winning Colors in Preakness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Risen Star, a son of Secretariat who was third
in the Kentucky Derby, spoiled Winning Colors' bid to become the
first filly to win the Triple Crown by capturing the $536,200
Preakness Stakes Saturday.
   Risen Star, ridden by Eddie Delahoussaye, took the lead on the
final turn. Winning Colors, the Kentucky Derby winner, was in the
hunt but faded in the stretch to finish third, behind Brian's Time.
   Louie Roussell III, co-owner and trainer of Risen Star, had
hedged all week on whether he would even start the strapping colt,
especially because rain had made the Pimlico track muddy. However,
the track condition was upgraded to good before the race.
   ``This is the best racehorse I've had in 20 years and I don't
want him to run on an off-track if I don't have to,'' Roussel said.
   Risen Star finished 1\ lengths ahead of Brian's Time, carrying
scale weight of 126 pounds over 1 3-16 miles in 1:56 1-5 in the
nine-horse field.
   Risen Star, who earned $403,700 for Roussel and co-owner Ronnie
Lamarque, paid $15.60, $7.80 and $4. The colt boosted his record
for the year to five victories in seven starts, with a second and a
third.
   The Preakness is the second jewel of racing's Triple Crown,
which includes the Kentucky Derby and the June 11 Belmont Stakes.
No filly has ever won two Triple Crown races.
</TEXT>
