<DOCNO> AP880521-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 1847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-21 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Bring Tornadoes, Heavy Rain and Hail to
Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms over the central Gulf Coast spawned several
tornadoes in Louisiana and dropped heavy rain and hail on the
state, while rain also hit parts of the Plains and the Northeast
Saturday.
   In southeastern Louisiana, a tornado destroyed several mobile
homes west of Hammond, another tornado destroyed a trailer north of
Folsom and a third damaged a house and barn at Creole.
   Tornadoes also were sighted near Maurice and Nunez in
south-central Louisiana.
   Thunderstorms also generated winds up to 69 mph at Houma, 50
miles south of New Orleans, and up to 75 mph at Cameron on the
state's southwestern Gulf Coast. Winds blew down trees and power
lines north of Baton Rouge and in Tangipahoa and Vermillion
parishes.
   Indian Bayou and Lafayette were hammered with two-inch hail and
storms dropped golfball-sized hail south of Baton Rouge.
   Rainfall was very heavy across the southern part of the state,
with Lafayette recording 1{ inches in the six hours ending at 2
p.m. EDT and Alexandria getting 1\ inches. Streets in Lake Charles
were blocked by flash floods during part of the morning.
   Despite the severity of the storms, there were no serious
injuries or deaths reported.
   Thunderstorms also hit south-central Texas and southern
Mississippi, producing gusts to 62 mph in Biloxi, Miss. Storms also
stretched into northern Louisiana and southern Arkansas.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms also were scattered over much of
the Plains to the Red River Valley of Minnesota and North Dakota.
Huron, S.D., received almost 1\ inches of rain in the six hours
ending at 2 p.m. EDT and Norfolk, Neb., had two-thirds of an inch.
   Rain kept temperatures in the upper 40s and 50s in the central
Plains.
   New York State and northern Pennsylvania received more showers
and thunderstorms, and a flood watch remained in effect for the
Catskill Mountains, the Susquehanna region and lower Hudson Valley
of New York.
   Widely scattered showers also were reported in the Ohio Valley
and New England.
   Sunny skies prevailed west of the Rockies, and skies were clear
or partly sunny over much of the Southeast.
   Temperatures climbed into the 80s across the Southeast and much
of the Mississippi Valley and into the 90s and above 100 degrees in
the desert Southwest.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 48 degrees at Laramie,
Wyom. to 103 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Sunday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms to
stretch from the central Gulf Coast states to the southern Plains,
and north to the upper Mississippi Valley, with showers most
numerous in the lower and middle Mississippi Vally and eastern
Texas and Oklahoma. Showers also were forecast for the northern
Atlantic Coast states, particularly southern New England. Sunny
skies are expected to prevail over the rest of the nation.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s and 60s in New England; in
the 60s in the central Plains, upper Mississippi Valley and upper
Michigan; in the 80s from the Gulf Coast to the Ohio Valley, and
most of the area west of the Rockies; and in the 90s or above 100
degrees in the valleys and deserts of southern California, southern
Nevada and southern Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted for most other areas.
</TEXT>
