<2ND_LINE>AM-Commencements,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Cosby'' Producer, Comic, Economists Address Grads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcy Peterson Carsey, executive producer of
``The Cosby Show,'' told 1,900 University of New Hampshire
graduates Saturday they can have it all if they ``learn how to
delegate _ and get a microwave.''
   Carsey, who received an English degree from UNH in 1966, also
told graduates they don't have to choose between a family and a
career.
   ``You can share your life with someone, raise children if you
want to, do tons of good work, and take karate lessons on the
side,'' Carsey said. ``You just have to learn to delegate well _
and get a microwave.''
   In Goffstown, ``NBC Nightly News'' anchor Tom Brokaw told about
380 Saint Anselm College graduates that ``there's more to life than
looking good and living well.''
   Brokaw urged the audience to try to make a difference in matters
such as as public education, black teen-age unemployment, the drug
epidemic, disparities between rich and poor countries and the arms
race.
   ``Nothing great in this world would have been accomplished
without passion. I call upon you to have the passion to shape the
events of your generation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Rich Little hailed President Reagan
as a great ventriloquist in a speech to graduates at the University
of Nevada-Reno Friday.
   ``Have you ever noticed when (Vice President George) Bush talks,
you never see Reagan's mouth move?'' he said at the school's annual
Graduation Celebration.
   Making light of his academic achievements, Little said a teacher
once told him, ``With your grades you'll never be president, but
with your absentee record, you could make it to the Senate.''
   The comedian interspersed his imitations with some sober advice.
   ``When you leave this school, I want you to forget every single
thing you've learned because there's no future in drinking,'' he
said.
   More than 1,000 students received diplomas Saturday at the
school's graduation exercises.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel Prize-winning economist James M.
Buchanan urged graduates at Ball State University Saturday to
maintain a healthy level of Midwestern skepticism.
   ``To get along in the world, we need to accept the rules of the
social structures that exist, but we also need to learn to question
them,'' he told 2,862 graduates.
   ``Literally everything should be subject to inquiry.''
   Buchanan, who won the Nobel in 1986 and received an honorary
doctor of humanities Saturday, said he was proud to be an
``academic outsider.''
   ``I have never been an Ivy League academician,'' he said. ``I
have never considered myself an adviser to politicians. In fact, I
have considered politicians something to be protected from. I have
never been attracted by the romantic nonsense that government or
politicians know what is best, and I hope you share these views
with me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SMITHFIELD, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan told business graduates at Bryant College Saturday that
they would face bigger challenges than his generation because of
the internationalization of the American economy.
   ``The world today is significantly more challenging than it was
40 years ago,'' he said.
   Speaking to a crowd of about 6,000 people, including 1,000
graduates of business administration, Greenspan said many of the
country's financial problems would fade as the United States
completes its transition to a service economy.
   Greenspan, 62, received an honorary Doctor of Science in
Business Administration.
</TEXT>
