<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Rambo     05-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rambo,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Aside, Soviets Still Don't Care for Rambo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smiles, handshakes and summit meetings aside, good
feelings toward Americans engendered by the upcoming visit of
President Reagan have their limit. Soviets still don't care much
for Rambo.
   A correspondent for the Soviet government newspaper Izvestia got
a sneak preview of the movie ``Rambo III'' in New York recently.
   He didn't like it any better than his colleagues liked any of
the previous ``Rambo'' movies.
   A. Shalnev wrote in Saturday's edition of Izvestia that ``Rambo
III,'' scheduled to be released May 25, could be considered
entertainment only if the definition included ``a torrent of blood
and the crunch of broken bones.''
   Shalnev said a representative of the film company told him the
movie had no political intent. But he wrote ``the thought of the
film, its goal, is politics. The politics is of very evil, very
militaristic anti-Sovietism.''
   ``The dialogue is minimal. When the heroes want to speak, they
talk not in words but in slogans,'' he said.
   Shalnev said the film takes Sylvester Stallone in the title role
to Afghanistan to teach anti-government rebels how to use Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles.
   Soviet soldiers began withdrawing from Afghanistan on May 15.
Under an agreement reached in Geneva April 14 and guaranteed by the
United States and the Soviet Union, they must be totally out of the
country within nine months.
   The United States and Reagan, who once called the Soviet Union
an ``evil empire'' are receiving more positive treatment as
relations gradually improve and the U.S. president prepares to
travel to Moscow for his fourth meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   But Shalnev questioned why the film was being released the day
Reagan leaves Washington for Helsinki, Finland, on his way to
Moscow.
   Soviet media bitterly criticized previous ``Rambo'' movies and
other similar films that they said made enemies of ``Reds who
should be killed, killed, killed.''
   Writers attributed such films to a ``cult of violence'' in the
United States and an effort to erase the memory of the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
