<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Salvador     05-21 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Salvador,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Military Says Salvadoran Leftists Plan Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces said Saturday that
leftist guerrillas in El Salvador plan to enter Honduras this week
to try to kidnap high-ranking government and military officials.
   According to the intelligence information, a special unit of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front will try to carry out the
terrorist actions in an effort to destabilize neighboring Honduras,
the military said.
   The front, which is made up of five guerrilla armies, has been
fighting the U.S.-supported government in El Salvador for more than
eight years.
   The armed forces statement said the rebel unit, which will
include both men and women, will try to take advantage of anti-U.S.
sentiment in Honduras that broke out in early April when
demonstrators burned the U.S. Consulate in Tegucigalpa.
   The demonstration was unusual in Honduras, a staunch U.S. ally
in Central America.
   It occurred after the April 5 arrest of Juan Ramon Matta, a
Honduran suspected of drug trafficking, who was arrested in a
pre-dawn raid at his Tegucigalpa home and deported to the United
States via the Dominican Republic.
   The Honduran Constitution forbids the extradition of Honduran
citizens.
   Matta was taken to a maximum security federal prison in Marion,
Ill., and held on drug-trafficking charges.
   He was also wanted for questioning by U.S. authorities in
connection with the 1985 torture-slaying in Mexico of Enrique
Camarena Salazar, an agent of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</TEXT>
