<HEAD>With AM-School Shooting, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a novel written four years
ago about a fictional kidnapping at the Hubbard Woods Elementary
School was among the shocked parents trying to come to grips with
violence at the same school.
   James McManus, 37, said his son was a student at the school
Friday when a woman opened fire in a second-grade classroom,
killing one child and critically wounding five others before
barricading herself in a nearby home and shooting another person.
   The woman, identified as Laurie Wasserman Dann, 30, later was
found dead after having shot herself in the head, police said.
   ``My son was in the school,'' McManus said. ``He is OK. I don't
want to say anything right now. I don't want to comment about the
relationship with the book.''
   The novel, ``Out of the Blue,'' the first by McManus, was hailed
as a powerful psychological thriller when it was published in 1984.
   The plot involves a 5-year-old girl who is kidnapped from the
Hubbard Woods schoolyard by people who mistake her for the daughter
of wealthy parents in this affluent Chicago suburb.
   Some parents of Hubbard Woods schoolchildren Friday recalled the
novel, which was published by Crown Books.
   ``I read it about five years ago, and I thought about it
today,'' said Blanche Romey, whose 7-year-old daughter Katie is a
first-grader at the school.
   The jacket of the 246-page book calls it the story of how
``random violence can reach out to touch the lives of the
innocent.''
