<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Mitterrand     05-21 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Mitterrand,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Re-elected President Begins Second Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand began his second
seven-year term Saturday, promising to formulate policy aimed at
uniting fellow Socialists with non-Socialists.
   Speaking during a 20-minute inauguration ceremony, Mitterrand
said his May 8 re-election, in which he defeated conservative
Jacques Chirac, who then resigned as premier, ``was not the good
ones winning over the bad ones, nor the other way around.''
   He called on French people to work together ``so that the
principle of hope might triumph over the compulsions of fear and
confrontation.''
   Mitterrand, 71, has called legislative elections for June 5,
with runoffs June 12, in which Socialists backing new Premier
Michel Rocard are expected to win a large majority in the 577-set
National Assembly.
   Rocard and his Cabinet ministers and other top officials were
among about 150 people attending the ceremony in the glittering
Salle des Fetes (Festival Hall) of the presidential Elysee Palace.
Prominent guests included author Marguerite Duras and actor Gerard
Depardieu.
   The proceedings were televised nationwide. Schoolchildren, who
normally attend classes for a half-day on Saturdays, were given a
holiday for the occasion.
</TEXT>
