<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainCollision     05-21 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Collision,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Human Error Caused Fatal Conrail Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIR LAWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispatcher mistakenly allowed two
Conrail freight trains onto the same track, causing a head-on
collision early Saturday that killed a brakeman, railroad officials
said.
   The brakeman, F.W. Clinton, 50, apparently got off a local
freight train to ``perform normal duties'' like throwing a switch
or coupling hoses when the accident occurred, said Steve Lubetkin,
a Conrail spokesman in Philadelphia.
   The local train was hit by a Conrail freight train traveling
from Elkhart, Ind., to Newark about 12:50 a.m., Lubetkin said.
   He said Clinton, of Hawley, Pa., had been a railroad employee
for 25 years.
   A preliminary report concluded that the dispatcher, Dave Smith,
mistakenly allowed the two trains to travel in opposite directions
on the same track, said Rosemary Sheridan, spokeswoman for NJ
Transit Corp.
   Smith, 30, has worked for NJ Transit since July 1986 and has a
``very good'' record, she said.
   Smith, an NJ Transit tower operator and five Conrail crew
members underwent blood and urine tests for alcohol and drugs, a
routine procedure following a rail accident under National Railroad
Administration guidelines, she said. There was no indication
substance abuse was involved, she said.
   Smith and the tower operator, William Strubb, who has worked for
NJ Transit for nearly 23 years, were suspended until the test
results come in, which is expected in about two weeks, Ms. Sheridan
said.
   Lubetkin said the Conrail employees were not suspended.
</TEXT>
