<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Davis,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sammy Davis Sr. Dead at 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sammy Davis Sr., a vaudeville song-and-dance
man and father of entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. died Saturday, a
publicist said.
   He was 87.
   Davis died at his Beverly Hills home of natural causes, Arnold
Lipsman said.
   Sammy Davis Jr. was to deliver the eulogy at public services
Monday at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in Glendale, said Dick Fisher,
a park spokesman.
   The elder Davis was born in Wilmington, N.C., the grandson of
slaves. He began a 40-year career in New York City by winning a
series of dance contests, then joined the Will Maston Trio after
World War I and went on to appear in vaudeville, on stage, and in
posh nightclubs, Lipsman said.
   Davis played Fletcher Henderson in the 1955 film, ``The Benny
Goodman Story'' and appeared on television with such celebrities as
Steve Allen, Eddie Cantor, Milton Berle and Jack Benny, Lipsman
said.
   Davis's last television performance was in 1973 with his son on
a General Electric special, Lipsman said.
   Besides his son, Davis is survived by two daughters, Ramona
James of New York City and Suzette Davis of Portland, Ore., as well
as six grandchildren and one great-grandchild, Fisher said.
</TEXT>
