<HEAD>Rep. Kennedy Announces Re-election Bid.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II on Saturday
formally announced his candidacy for re-election to the
congressional seat once held by his late uncle, John F. Kennedy,
and former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill.
   The 35-year-old freshman congressman, son of the late Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy, made his announcement to more than 200 cheering
supporters at Arlington Town Hall.
   ``Use the elections of 1988 to send a message of peace and hope
to those who suffer around the world,'' he urged his constituents.
``We can make a difference, we can bring this country together.''
   With his mother Ethel, wife Sheila, and two sons joining him on
the platform, Kennedy thanked those who worked with him during his
first year in Congress to perform constituent services, preserve
veterans' benefits threatened by budget cuts and help find funds
for investment in affordable housing.
   Kennedy spent a state record $1.8 million fighting through an
11-candidate primary field to win the seat in 1986. This year he
has the backing of 16 Democratic state representatives from the
district and faces no opposition within his own party, Kennedy aide
James Mahoney said.
   The state Republican Party has not announced a candidate to
challenge Kennedy.
