<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mideast-Walters     05-21 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mideast-Walters,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Talks With Assad About Hostages And Syrian Forces In
Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Lebanon-Violence, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. envoy Vernon Walters said Saturday
the Syrian government is aware it could endanger foreign hostages
if it sends it troops into Beirut's southern slums.
   Walters, the U.S. ambassador at the United Nations, spoke to
reporters at Damascus airport before flying to Baghdad, the third
stop of a Middle East visit. He met earlier with Syrian President
Hafez Assad and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
   The U.S. envoy said the talks included discussion of the nine
Americans and nine other foreign hostages being held in Lebanon,
and the imminent deployment of Syrian troops in south Beirut.
   Walters said that during the talks, ``there was a recognition of
the fact that this (the deployment) could work two ways.
   ``In one way it could work to endanger the hostages and in
another way, it could work such that it would not endanger them and
would make the hostages safe,'' he said.
   Most of the hostages are held in the slums by
Hezbollah-affiliated kidnappers.
   ``I don't want to go into the detail. I'm sure that the
president (Assad) is very much aware of the possible dangers and
the possible advantages of such an action,'' Walters said.
   He added: ``I did not attempt to influence his decision one way
or the other.
   Iran'a proxy force, Hezbollah, or Party of God, has wrested
control of Beirut's southern slums from the Syrian-backed Amal in
recent fighting.
   Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon, is Iran's main Arab
ally. But Damascus has been alarmed by Tehran's attempts to
dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiite Moslems through Hezbollah at
the time efforts are focused on eliminating Lebanon's sectarian
feuds to establish a secular system of government.
   Lebanese and Syrian officials have said that with or without
Iran's consent, some 7,500 Syrian soldiers, now poised on the edges
of the southern slums, would soon deploy in the 16-square-mile
enclave. Fighting has raged in that area since May 6.
   On arrival in the Iraqi capital later Saturday, Walters told the
Iraqi News Agency he would discuss the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war
with officials.
   He later met with Iraqi Foreign Minister Tarik Aziz, the agency
said.
   Before leaving Damascus at the end of a 24-hour visit, he said
his trip, which began in Israel, would also take him to ``most of
the Arab countries.'' Walters, however, did not elaborate on the
purpose of the tour, two weeks in advance of the arrival in the
Middle East of Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
</TEXT>
