<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0701 05-21 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0701,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Leader Pledges Help To Free Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf ``The Shiite...'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
report of two hostages held by Islamic Jihad, PICKS UP graf 11th
pvs ```I am...'''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With AM-Lebanon-Violence, Bjt
^By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Shiite Moslem leader pledged in a
statement Saturday to ``invest all my energies'' and exert pressure
to free foreign hostages held in Lebanon.
   ``I feel with the families of the hostages and I am doing all I
can to reach a happy ending,'' Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
spiritual leader of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, said in the
statement.
   The Rev. Ray Barnett, head of the Seattle-based Friends in the
West, said Fadlallah issued the statement Saturday after the two
made contact.
   ``Despite the limited means I have in this respect, I will
invest all my energies in this direction,'' Fadlallah said in the
statement.
   ``I have sought to close this file with all the means that I
have and I am still working on exerting pressure to reach a
humanitarian solution to this problem,'' he said, without
specifying who he was exerting pressure on.
   An aide to Barnett gave a copy of Fadlallah's statement in
Arabic to The Associated Press.
   Barnett, of Vancouver, Canada, arrived in Lebanon Friday,
seeking to deliver a petition to Fadlallah asking him to help free
the hostages. Speaking in a telephone interview from his hotel in
Christian east Beirut, he declined to comment on how he established
contact with Fadlallah.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is the umbrella organization for
pro-Iranian groups believed holding most of the 18 foreign hostages
_ including nine Americans _ in Lebanon.
   The longest-held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   In another development, a freed French hostage was quoted Sunday
in a London newspaper as saying a British television newsman and a
Northern Irish teacher are held in Lebanon by the pro-Iranian
Islamic Jihad.
   Jean-Paul Kauffmann would not, however, say how he knew that
John McCarthy, 31, and Brian Keenan, 36, were held by the Shiite
Moslem extremist group, The Sunday Times reported. They both
disappeared in April 1986, but no group has claimed responsibility
for their kidnapping.
   Kauffmann was released in Beirut May 4 with two other French
hostages after nearly three years in captivity.
   The newspaper also said Kauffmann revealed that until October
1986, McCarthy was held in a cell next to an American hostage. But
he said he wanted to keep the American's name secret to avoid
putting him or McCarthy in danger.
   Fadlallah started his statement by expressing how deeply moved
he was by the hostage issue.
   ``I am stirred by this issue which is a humanitarian one
although it has been placed within a political framework,'' he said.
   In an earlier interview Saturday, Barnett had said he did not
know how the petition, with 40,000 signatures from various
countries, would be delivered.
   An aide to Barnett said the petition was not actually delivered
to Fadlallah but that the Shiite leader considers it as good as
done.
   He said Fadlallah showed deep concern and thanked all those who
``made this great effort.''
   Barnett, 50, has met Fadlallah twice on previous trips to west
Beirut over the last two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
