<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Protest     05-21 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Protest,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priests, Nuns Head Rally in Manila for Land Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic priests and nuns led
about 1,000 demonstrators in a march to the Senate building
Saturday to press for comprehensive land reform.
   The demonstrators carried signs which read ``Land to the
Tillers'' and ``Our Land, Our Life.'' They snarled traffic as they
blocked off the road in front of the Senate office building for two
hours. The Senate was closed for the weekend.
   ``This is to show that the church is all the way behind a truly
comprehensive agrarian reform that is pro-poor and that will
promote social justice,'' said Manila auxiliary bishop Teodoro
Bacani.
   Negotiators are trying to reconcile differences between two
versions of a reform bill passed by both houses of the
American-style legislature.
   Many people view land reform as a solution to the 19-year-old
communist insurgency, since a majority of the Marxist rebels are
peasants.
   Also Saturday, a news report said a guerrilla commander denied
allegations communist rebels accepted money from foreign
journalists in exchange for staging ambushes against the military.
   The communist New People's Army commander, Ernesto Bergola, made
the statement Friday to Filipino journalists at his mountain
hideout about 30 miles north of Manila, the Manila Chronicle
newspaper said.
   The nationally circulated newspaper said Bergola admitted
guerrillas accept donations from anybody ``without strings
attached'' but denied collecting money from journalists to stage
ambushes.
   Two weeks ago, the military said it had evidence showing foreign
journalists were present during an ambush on Feb. 27 which killed
11 soldiers. A rebel who surrendered said the ambush was staged
after a group of foreign journalists paid guerrillas about $20,000
to film it.
   Manila newspapers, quoting military officials, earlier
identified the film crew as members of the British Broadcasting
Corp. But the military has since denied having identified the crew
and the BBC denied it had a crew in the area at the time.
   The armed forces announced Friday it had invited a Hong
Kong-based American reporter of Newsweek to shed light on the
incident after the magazine reported details of the ambush in its
April 4 issue.
</TEXT>
