<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Homeless     05-21 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Homeless,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope and Mother Teresa Open Vatican Shelter for Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday inaugurated an
80-bed shelter within the Vatican's walls for homeless men and
women.
   Moter Teresa, the Nobel Peace Prize winner whose Missionaries of
Charity serve sick and poor people around the world, assisted the
pope as he sprinkled holy water from a chalice inside the two-story
building that houses the shelter.
   Nuns from Mother Teresa's order will help run the facility,
where Rome's homeless can sleep during the night in dormitory
rooms, simply furnished, with bunk beds. The shelter will serve
three meals a day.
   The building was erected in a courtyard near Paul VI auditorium,
where the pope holds his general weekly audiences during the winter
or in bad weather.
   John Paul appealed to the public and politicians to recognize
``the urgency of the problem of so many millions of our brothers,
deprived of such precious well-being and yet who can and must _ if
so helped _ be at the service of the common good.''
