<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-ChristianMarch     05-21 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Christian March,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands In Evangelical March Through London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singing, praying and waving banners, thousands of
evangelical Christians joined a ``March for Jesus'' through central
London on Saturday.
   Organizers said more than 50,000 people from across Britain took
part in the march and rally in Hyde Park. Police had no immediate
crowd estimate.
   ``This is not a protest march,'' said Gerald Coates, one of the
organizers. ``It's an expression of traditional grassroots
Christianity.''
   He said the event reflected a rebirth of evangelism in Britain,
partly borne from dissatisfaction with the orthodox churches.
   Some of the marchers recited prayers, using portable amplifiers,
while others played guitars and trumpets, shook tambourines, banged
drums and sang.
   One group calling itself the ``Jesus Army'' wore camouflage flak
jackets.
   As the marchers passed the grounds of Buckingham Palace, they
said a prayer for Queen Elizabeth II and her family.
   Organizers said a letter explaining the march would be delivered
to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's official residence at No. 10
Downing St.
   Meanwhile, celebrations marking the 250th anniversary of the
founding of Methodism got under way in London Saturday.
   To mark the occasion, two British Rail high-speed trains were
named after Methodist founders John and Charles Wesley in a
ceremony at St. Pancras Station.
   A week of celebrations is planned to commemorate the conversion
of John Wesley on May 24, 1738, at a Christian meeting in London.
His brother was converted soon afterwards.
   About 450 Americans traveled to Britain to join local
congregations in services and visits to sites associated with the
fiery preacher John Wesley and his hymn-writing brother.
</TEXT>
