<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortedTakeoff     05-21 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aborted Takeoff,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet's Nose Gear Collapses During Aborted Takeoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines DC-10 carrying 254
people aborted its takeoff Saturday, ran off the runway at
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport and slid to a stop on its
nose when its front landing gear collapsed.
   Six people, including the three-person cockpit crew, were
injured in the accident, which occured about 4 p.m., airline
spokesmen said. None of the injuries was serious, they added.
   Flight 70 was beginning a non-stop flight to Frankfurt, West
Germany, with 240 passengers, a cockpit crew of three, and 11
flight attendants, American Airlines spokesman John Hotard said.
The plane had a capacity for 244 passengers.
   Another spokesman, Steve McGregor, said a cockpit warning light
flashed during the takeoff, and Capt. Bob Cornelison radioed the
tower that he was aborting the flight.
   ``But he was rolling at such a speed,'' Hotard said, ``that by
the time the plane slowed, it had run off the runway and into a
grassy area, which had been softened by a rain. Sinking into this
soft grassy area caused the nose gear to collapse,'' Hotard said.
   As a precautionary measure, passengers were evacuated by
emergency chute, Hotard said.
   The captain, co-pilot, flight engineer and three passengers
suffered minor injuries and were taken to area hospitals, American
spokesman Al Becker said. The three passengers suffered back
injuries, Becker said.
   The crew, Hotard noted, ``would have been the ones to drop the
farthest. They were right over the nose gear.''
   A passenger on the flight, Juhani Jamia, of Helsinki, Finland,
said that before takeoff ``it seemed the plane was having some kind
of technical difficulty. The power was going on and off.''
   The flight was scheduled to depart at 2:50 p.m., but it left the
passenger gate at 3:28 p.m. and was in position for takeoff shortly
after 4 p.m., the spokesman said. They did not give a reason for
the delay.
   No smoke or fire was noted during the incident, Hotard said.
   The passengers were returned to the terminal by bus, Hotard said.
   Airline officials arranged a 9 p.m. flight to Frankfurt, with
baggage scheduled for a later flight, McGregor said.
   An American Airlines maintenance crew from Tulsa was scheduled
to defuel the plane and take off baggage before officials tried to
move the plane, McGregor said.
   It was American Airline's third major problem this month.
   A two-week-old American Airlines jet made an emergency landing
in Bermuda on May 10 after a fuel pump split on a flight from New
York's John F. Kennedy Airport to San Juan, Puerto Rico, spewing
fuel into the Atlantic Ocean.
   Early this past week, a domestic flight was diverted to Detroit
because of a crack in the main landing gear well, an airline
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
