<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill     05-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shell Doubles Estimates of April Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell Oil Co. has doubled its size
estimate for last month's crude oil spill that soiled hundreds of
boats and killed 200 birds and animals in a wildlife habitat.
   Under orders from state investigators, Shell re-examined its
figures and said Friday that about 365,000 gallons spilled during
the April 23 leak of San Joaquin crude into environmentally
sensitive Peyton Marsh.
   Since May 2, Shell has insisted that only 175,000 gallons leaked
from the 12.5-million-gallon storage tank at its Martinez refinery
after a drain hose broke.
   In the days following the accident, Shell insisted less than
4,000 gallons of the thick petroleum had escaped.
   Independent consultants working for the state Bay Regional Water
Quality Control agency will review the new estimate. State
regulators ordered the review of Shell's spill estimate because
cleanup crews appeared to be recovering far more oil than Shell had
admitted leaked.
   The revision came after Shell discovered that refinery employees
working on the spill estimate erroneously used a formula commonly
employed when extracting oil from a drilling mixture of oil, water
and sand, Shell spokesman Bill Sharkey said.
   Technicians subtracted from the percentage of the oil-water
mixture recovered by cleanup workers a set percentage used in
drilling for determining sediment and water.
   As for the cleanup, ``There's still an awful lot of oil in
sensitive wildlife areas,'' said Michael Rugg, a state Fish and
Game Department biologist.
   Under guidance from the wildlife agency, Shell is draining the
100-acre marsh. Grasses will be mowed to remove the stickiest oil
and the marsh will be flooded again in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
