<DOCNO> AP880521-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Swiss-Lefebvre     05-21 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swiss-Lefebvre,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishop Confirms Agreement With Vatican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre on
Saturday confirmed reports he and the Vatican have reached an
agreement allowing him to consecrate new bishops.
   Lefebvre confirmed the reports after ordaining 26 deacons at his
traditionalist seminary in Econe. He said he signed the agreement
May 5 with Cardinal Josef Ratzinger, head of the Congregation for
the Doctrine of the Faith, or the Vatican's guardian of theological
orthodoxy.
   Lefebvre did not give details of the agreement. He said it did
not specify the date and number of bishops he could consecrate, but
he said he wanted to go ahead with his plans to consecrate bishops
on June 30 in Econe.
   The archbishop said he was traveling to Rome Sunday to hold
further talks with Ratzinger.
   In 1976, Pope Paul VI suspended Lefebvre, 82, from his priestly
duties including saying Mass because he refused to recognize the
results of the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s.
   In defiance of the Vatican, Lefebvre has ordained priests and
celebrated the Tridentine Mass, a banned 16th century liturgy in
Latin. He claims millions of followers and sympathizers around the
world and much enthusiasm for the Latin Mass.
   Without Vatican permission, his consecration of bishops would
lead to excommunication from the Roman Catholic Church and set the
stage for a possible schism.
</TEXT>
