<DOCNO> AP880521-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0687 05-21 1172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0687,1100</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 27th graf pvs, bgng: ``Dukakis is ...''
to UPDATE with Dukakis at Missouri fundraiser and INSERTS 2 grafs
after 32nd graf pvs, bgng: ``George Bush ...'' to UPDATE with Dole
comments on charges against Noriega.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic rivals Michael Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson were continuing their dialogue Saturday, while Vice
President George Bush was making his strongest move so far away
from President Reagan.
   Dukakis, aiming to lock up the Democratic presidential
nomination in the final primaries on June 7, completed a California
campaign swing with a visit to a community health clinic and then
planned to attend a fund-raiser in St. Louis before flying home to
Boston.
   Jackson, appearing at a rally at a shipyard in San Pedro, denied
reports circulated by a campaign staff member earlier in the day
that he had been hospitalized Friday night in San Francisco,
possibly for a stomach ailment.
   ``There was some rumor about my health,'' Jackson told the
crowd. ``My health is fantastic. Ain't nothing wrong with me; feel
so good, I want to jump off the stage. Feel so fine.''
   Dukakis, during a stop at a community clinic, told the mostly
Hispanic crowd that if elected president he would ``put basic
health insurance for all of our citizens at the top of the national
agenda.''
   Dukakis said he would build coalitions with representatives of
business, labor and politics to enact legislation that would
require businesses to provide health insurance for their employees.
He recently signed such an insurance plan into law in his home
state.
   Dukakis received a loud round of applause at the clinic when he
lapsed into Spanish, which he speaks fluently.
   Bush, who attended a 2{-hour meeting at the White House, had no
response when reporters called out questions to him as he left the
session on U.S. policy on Panama.
   Meanwhile, CBS News, citing unnamed Republican sources Saturday,
said Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III would take over running
the Bush campaign next month, but Baker told CBS that he was not
preparing to leave his Cabinet post to go to work for the campaign.
   In an interview on his campaign plane late Friday, the
Massachusetts governor said he had talked earlier in the day by
telephone with Jackson.
   He did not say what they talked about but described his contacts
with Jackson as routine.
   ``What we try to do is arrange things so that when our paths
cross, we spend some time together,'' said Dukakis.
   He rejected the notion that he was negotiating with Jackson.
   ``We respect each other; we like each other,'' he said. ``We
agree on some things, we disagree on others. It's a good
relationship and it will continue to be.''
   Jackson told the shipyard crowd, which heard earlier that the
candidate had been hospitalized, that flight delays not an illness
was the reason he was late.
   ``Let me set the record straight. This morning in San Francisco
we sat on the runway for nearly an hour and threw our plane late,''
he said.
   But Rick Roberts, a spokesman in Jackson's Los Angeles office,
said earlier: ``He was hospitalized. We don't know for sure what it
was.''
   ``It was a possible stomach ailment. We don't want to speculate
until the national campaign people get here,'' Roberts said.
   Jackson was appearing at the rally and then attending three
fund-raisers in the Los Angeles area.
   There are 466 Democratic delegates at stake in the party's final
four primaries on June 7. California is the biggest prize with 314,
while New Jersey has 109. The other two primaries were New Mexico
with 24 delegates and Montana with 19.
   In Colorado, backers of Dukakis on Friday withdrew their
challenge of a decision to add 198 Jackson representatives to the
Democratic state convention. The state's Democrats are meeting this
weekend to finalize delegates to the national convention in
Atlanta, July 18-21.
   Evelyn Davidson, representing 18 Denver Democrats who challenged
the expanded convention delegation on May 2, said that although
party rules were violated, the Jackson delegates would not change
the final outcome.
   ``Mike Dukakis will clearly win the nomination. One or two
delegates from Denver will make no significant difference,'' Ms.
Davidson said.
   In Vermont, Republicans and Democrats also held their respective
state conventions this weekend to determine the delegates to the
national convention.
   Dukakis was sounding increasingly certain of getting enough
delegates on June 7 to top the 2,081 needed for a convention
majority.
   During his latest campaign swing through California, he often
made only passing reference to the primary, while tailoring his
rhetoric to his anticipated confrontation with Bush in the fall.
   Dukakis is heavily favored to defeat Jackson in California and
New Jersey.
   The Massachusetss governor stopped in Missouri on his way back
East, and was introduced at a fund-raiser in Creve Coeur by former
Democratic rival Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   ``Because of Dukakis, thousands and millions of people who voted
for Ronald Reagan in 1984 are going to vote Democratic in 1988,''
the Missouri congressman said.
   Bush, with the Republican nomination already locked up, appeared
to have found the issue on which to separate himself from the
president _ the controversial negotiations with Panamanian
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The administration, according to a State Department source, was
considering a deal in which Noriega would leave Panama for nine
months in exchange for the United States dropping drug charges
against him.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, said Friday that
``administration sources who have suggested that the vice president
favors ending the negotiations (with Noriega) and bringing the
envoy back to Washington are essentially correct.''
   In an interview with Cable News Network, White House staff chief
Howard H. Baker Jr. said Bush had stated his differences with the
Noriega negotiations ``persistently ... and enthusiastically.''
   ``George Bush must stake out his position as a candidate for
president of the United States,'' said Baker.
   Senate GOP leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who made an unsuccessful
bid for the GOP presidential nomination, said Republican candidates
could suffer if the Reagan administration drops charges against
Noriega.
   ``I don't want the administration to make a mistake,'' Dole said
at a news conference at Mississippi's Republican state convention
in Jackson. ``We're in quicksand if we start dismissing
indictments, political quicksand.''
   At a news conference in Sacramento on Friday, Dukakis demanded
that the administration explain its past dealings with Noriega.
   ``I and the American people want an explanation of what this
administration has been doing doing business with Noriega,'' said
Dukakis.
   The Massachusetts governor has made denunciations of U.S.
dealings with Noriega a standard part of his stump speeches.
   Jackson also denounced administration dealings with the
Panamanian.
   ``Noriega is not plea bargaining with Reagan and Bush,'' said
Jackson. ``Reagan and Bush are plea bargaining with Noriega. ... We
need to know what's going on.
   ``Send a special prosecutor to Panama. Send a congressional
delegation to Panama. Hear both sides of an ugly story.''
</TEXT>
