<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomosexualSlaying     05-21 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homosexual Slaying,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Sentence Ordered For Two In Homosexual Slaying Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOYLESTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Saturday ordered the death penalty
for two men convicted of murdering a man because they thought he
was homosexual.
   Richard Laird, 24, and Frank Chester, 20, were convicted Friday
of first-degree murder in the Dec. 15 slaying of Anthony Milano, a
26-year-old commercial artist from Levittown.
   The jury returned the death sentence at 5:35 p.m. after nearly
11 hours of deliberations over two days.
   Chester showed no emotion when the verdict was read. Laird,
however, cursed Bucks County Common Pleas Judge Edward G. Biester
when the judge said jurors had not rushed to a decision.
   Family and friends of the defendants began crying and screaming
when the verdict was read.
   Attorneys for both men said they planned to appeal. Death
sentences are automatically reviewed by the Pennsylvania Supreme
Court.
   ``I thought it was wholly appropriate for these two men,'' Bucks
County District Attorney Alan M. Rubenstein said of the sentence.
   Milano's body was found by the side of a road in Bristol
Township with his face slashed and his throat cut so viciously that
the spinal cord was severed, an autopsy showed.
   Milano left his home at 11 p.m. on Dec. 14 to get a beer and
sandwich at a bar called the Edgely Inn, where he crossed paths
with Laird, of Bristol Borough, and Chester, of Bristol Township.
   A bartender testified the two men forced Milano to buy them
drinks and harassed and humiliated him.
   Both Chester, who worked at a diner, and Laird, a carpenter,
said they drank with Milano and got in his car for a ride home that
ended in a scuffle along a Britsol Township street. Each man
testified that the other had killed Milano.
   Rubenstein had insisted the motive for the killing was a fierce
hatred of homosexuals.
   Besides first-degree murder, both men also had been convicted on
charges of kidnapping, aggravated assault, conspiracy, unlawful
restraint, false imprisonment and possession of an instrument of
crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
