<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique-Fighting 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique-Fighting, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0539,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says 18 Rebels Killed In Recent Fighting, Rebels Claim
Killing 67</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with rebels claims of killing
soldiers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops killed 18 guerrillas
in recent fighting north of the capital of Maputo, the national
news agency AIM reported Saturday.
   Also Saturday, rebels announced in Lisbon, Portugal, that they
had killed 52 Mozambican and 15 Zimbabwean soldiers in attacks on
two army barracks earlier this month.
   AIM also said a military statement reported that the government
soldiers freed 13 civilians who were being held by the rebels of
the Mozambique National Resistance, AIM said, citing a military
statement.
   AIM said the clashes took place Wednesday about 30 miles north
of the town of Maluana on Mozambique's main north-south road. The
report made no mention of government casualties.
   Maluana has been the site of repeated ambushes by the rebels,
who attack both civilian and military vehicles traveling in convoys.
   The rebels, also known by their Portuguese acronym RENAMO, have
been fighting for 11 years to overthrow Mozambique's Marxist
government. An estimated 100,000 people have died in the war in the
past three years, according to a recent U.S. State Department
report.
   No government acknowledges supporting the group, which has
seriously damaged Mozambique's economy with hit-and-run attacks on
civilian and military targets.
   Mozambique claims that South Africa assists the rebels, but
South Africa denies the allegation, saying it has abided by a 1984
mutual non-aggression pact with Mozambique.
   In Lisbon, the rebels said in a statement that their forces
killed 23 Mozambicans and the 15 Zimbabweans in an attack on a
joint barracks in the town of Macossa about 55 miles from the
border with Zimbabwe.
   The rebels said the Mozambican battalion had been trained in
Zimbabwe by British military instructors.
   Troops from Zimbabwe, Tanzania and Malawi fight in Mozambique
alongside the army, mainly to protect transport routes and an oil
pipeline.
   In the other attack, the rebels said they killed 29 Mozambican
soldiers stationed at a barracks in the town of Morrumbene in the
southeastern province of Inhambane.
   The rebels gave no specific dates for the attacks, which were
not independently confirmed.
</TEXT>
