<HEAD>Reagan Puts In Plug For Preserving Deteriorating Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan watched film clips of Fred
Astaire and other Hollywood stars of past years, including himself,
Saturday night and then put in a plug for ``preserving our
country's film heritage.''
   The president spoke at a dinner sponsored by the American Film
Institute to raise funds for the preservation of deteriorating
films from the early days of the movie industry.
   The evening was billed as ``A Fred Astaire Remembrance'' in
honor of the late song-and-dance man and featured clips from movies
in which Astaire appeared.
   Also featured were a few shots from ``This is the Army,'' an
Irving Berlin musical in which Reagan appeared while he was a
lieutenant in the Army Air Corps film unit during World War II.
   ``What a surprise,'' the president quipped. ``I usually know
when I'm going to be on the late, late show.''
   ``In Hollywood, if you don't sing or dance, you become an
after-dinner speaker, and look where I wound up,'' he added.
   The president paid tribute to ``the important work the American
Film Institute is doing in preserving our country's film heritage.''
