<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LonetreeSentence 1stLd-Writethru a0789 05-21 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lonetree Sentence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Petersen Reduces Lonetree Prison Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 30-year prison sentence imposed on
former Marine Sgt. Clayton J. Lonetree in a Moscow embassy
sex-for-secrets case was cut by five years Friday by the commander
of the Quantico Marine Base.
   Lt. Gen. Frank E. Petersen also lifted the $5,000 fine imposed
on Lonetree after his Aug. 24 espionage conviction in a
court-martial at the northern Virginia installation.
   Petersen acted after a review of Lonetree's case ``because of
his total cooperation and conduct during his voluntary post-trial
debriefings by counter-intelligence specialists.''
   Gunnery Sgt. Dean Chamberlain said Lonetree would be eligible
for parole after serving one-third of his sentence, which means he
would have to spend 8 1-3 years instead of 10 years behind bars
before being considered for release.
   Lonetree also was sentenced by the eight-officer court-marital
to a dishonorable discharge, reduction to private and forfeiture of
all pay and allowances. Those penalties were unaffected.
   Chamberlain said Lonetree has been held at Quantico since his
trial.
   Lonetree was convicted on 13 counts, including allegations that
he turned over CIA identities and floor plans of the U.S. embassies
in Moscow and Vienna to the Soviets.
   Prosecutors alleged that Lonetree became a spy after falling in
love with a Soviet translator, Violetta Sanni.
   His defense lawyers contended Lonetree gave nothing of value to
the Soviets, but was trying to string the KGB along by providing
them with non-vital secrets in an effort to be a double agent.
   Lonetree's case unleashed concern over security at American
embassies world wide and led to a secret presidential study that
criticized the State Department and the Marines for neglecting
security.
   Lontree, who served as a guard at the Moscow embassy in 1985 and
1986, also was charged along with Marine Cpl. Arnold Bracy with
allowing KGB agents to roam the embassy at will. Those charges were
dropped by the government for lack of evidence.
   Another member of the detachment, Sgt. Robert Stufflebeam, was
convicted at Quantico on minor counts of dereliction of duty.
   The State Department and the Marines later minimized the
security report that more than 500 instances of possible wrongdoing
by guards at embassies worldwide had occurred.
   In a statement, the Marines said many of the so-called
infractions were minor, such as curfew violations, insubordination,
and misuse of telephone that could have no tie to espionage
activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
