<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush was told as early
as 1983 of allegations that Panamanian officials were involved in
the drug trade, but did not follow up on them, says Bush's top
foreign policy aide.
   The aide, Donald Gregg, testified in a deposition Friday that
then-Panamanian President Ricardo de la Espriella mentioned the
allegations to the vice president at the close of a December 1983
meeting in Panama, but the Panamanian official also told Bush the
stories were untrue.
   Bush, then chairman of a task force to combat the flow of drugs
into south Florida, ``said he had not been aware (of the charges)
or he would have raised them'' with de la Espriella, Gregg
testified in a deposition for a private civil lawsuit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders are expressing growing doubts
the chamber will ratify the U.S.-Soviet nuclear weapons treaty
before President Reagan meets Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
Moscow eight days from now.
   Unless the Senate speeds up its pace, ``the chance of having
that little package with the blue ribbon tied around it in the
president's pocket by the time he goes to Moscow are going to
diminish daily and hourly,'' Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., said late Friday.
   The problem is that conservative Republicans opposed to the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces (INF) treaty have used Senate
rules to delay action, according to Senate GOP leader Bob Dole of
Kansas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest government figures on federal
spending and tax receipts indicate chances of avoiding
election-year budget headaches are growing increasingly dim,
private analysts say.
   Sharply lower income tax receipts in April and continued
increases in federal spending left the year-to-date budget deficit
24.6 percent higher than in the same month of 1987, the Treasury
Department said Friday.
   Private analysts said the April report indicates the government
will have a tough time avoiding a large jump in the deficit, let
alone achieving the reduction envisioned by the two-year budget
deal sealed by lawmakers and the president in December.
   The government collected $13.9 billion more than it spent in
April, helping to hold the deficit for the first seven months of
the 1988 fiscal year to $105 billion. But that was more than $20
billion higher than the $84.3 billion gap for the same period a
year ago.
   Nevertheless, the administration still is officially projecting
that the tide of red ink will recede from $150.2 billion in 1987 to
$146.7 billion when the budget year ends Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contra guerrillas are leaving Nicaragua
``at a high rate'' because they are hungry and searching for food
in neighboring Honduras, the head of the U.S. foreign aid program
says.
   The American-supported Contras are moving because they have been
blocked from receiving supplies at their jungle bases in Nicaragua,
said Alan Woods, administrator of the Agency for International
Development.
   Woods told a Senate subcommittee Friday that ``there are people
inside Nicaragua who are desperate ... we've had reports of people
eating tree roots.''
   Woods declined to estimate how many people were involved, but
other administration officials have said that up to 3,000 rebels
have fled into neighboring Honduras in recent weeks to look for
food.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aging Pioneer spacecraft that
gave scientists their first close-up look at Venus continues to
yield secrets of the cloud-shrouded planet 10 years after its
launch, NASA says.
   The Pioneer orbiter has revealed many previously unknown
features of Venus, whose thick veil of sulfuric acid clouds has
kept Earth's telescopes from seeing its 800-degree surface.
   ``It challenges our thinking to try to understand why did Venus
evolve in such a different fashion than Earth,'' project scientist
Larry Colin said Friday. ``And are there any lessons to be learned
there in terms of the direction our own climate is evolving?''
   The probe, with some adjustments, should continue to send data
until it burns up in the Venusian atmosphere when its fuel runs out
in the summer of 1992, said Colin and project manager Richard
Fimmel.
</TEXT>
