<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-StElsewhere Adv23 1stLd-Writethru 05-21 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-St Elsewhere, Adv 23, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0122,0885</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, May 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``The writers...,'' to CORRECT that actor who
had played Floyd was NOT on program; that actor is deceased.</NOTE>
<HEAD>`St. Elsewhere' Leaves at Top of Form With Surprise Ending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Wayne Fiscus, soon to depart for
humanitarian work in Nicaragua, reminisces about his three years at
St. Eligius: ``Grueling hours, bad food, egomania, death and moral
confusion. It'll be hard to leave.''
   For its loyal viewers, too, it'll be hard to leave ``St.
Elsewhere,'' the NBC series that after six seasons becomes
television history with Wednesday's final episode, ``The Last
One.'' In terms of unbridled creativity, it was arguably the best
series ever on network television.
   The conclusion is suitably daft and won't be revealed here.
Suffice it to say that the impact of the final seconds will take a
minute to sink in, but the ending is perfect. Think Kafka.
   When ``St. Elsewhere'' premiered, it was compared to the
still-new ``Hill Street Blues,'' also from MTM Productions, that
broke ground with a similar messy style: characters talking over
each other and shaky, hand-held camera shots. ``Hill Street'' bowed
out at the end of last season.
   Writing set ``St. Elsewhere'' apart. Hip, weird, heartfelt and
very funny, no subject was too taboo, no character safe from
bizarre plot twists.
   Dr. Caldwell (Mark Harmon) turned from playboy to victim of
AIDS. Dr. Peter White (Terence Knox) was a rapist. Dr. Morrison
(David Morse) got raped. Fiscus (Howie Mandel) had a near-death
experience and took a tour of the afterlife. Dr. Axelrod (Stephen
Furst) died of a heart attack. Nurse Helen Rosenthal (Christina
Pickles) got breast cancer and addicted to drugs. A patient was
killed by a folding hospital bed. Doctors performed surgery in the
nude. A coroner only got turned on in the morgue. And Dr. Westphall
(Ed Flanders), the saint of St. Eligius, told off his new corporate
boss (Ronny Cox) by baring his behind in prime time.
   The show figuratively mooned NBC after the network made the
producers change the name ``Ecumena,'' the corporation that bought
St. Eligius at the start of the season, because the real-life
hospital chain, Humana Inc., sued for copyright infringement. The
writers put a lawsuit plotline in the show, and characters
complained about corporate bosses folding under pressure.
   The writers poked fun at television, especially MTM. In one
episode, a male patient fervently believed he was Mary Richards
from ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and was ecstatic when guest star
Betty White showed up _ ``Sue Ann!'' There were jokes on MTM shows
``The White Shadow'' and ``Newhart,'' and on TV in general. When a
patient played by an actor from ``The Andy Griffith Show'' needed a
haircut, the barber's name was Floyd. In the final episode, Fiscus
treats a man suffering eyestrain from watching too much tube.
   ``St. Elsewhere'' writers perfected the unlikely art of the hip
pun and managed to tuck a rock lyric into the dialogue of virtually
every show. Samples from Bruce Paltrow and Mark Tinker's final
script _ ``Jumpin' Jack! What was that flash?'' And ``Move that
gurney, Hal!'' a reference to Hal Gurnee, director of ``Late Night
with David Letterman.''
   What can be revealed of the final plot without disservice to
fans is that snooty Dr. Craig (William Daniels) is banished to
Cleveland. Reminded that the city is home of the Rock 'n' Roll Hall
of Fame, he sniffs, ``Yeah, yeah, yeah.'' The move sheds his
sycophant, Dr. Victor Ehrlich (Ed Begley Jr.), who declares after
another fawning surgery session, ``I'd follow you to the ends of
the earth. But not to Cleveland!''
   Early in the episode, an airplane crashes through a wall, but it
is never mentioned by anyone except Westphall's autistic son, who
mutters with mild interest, ``Plane.''
   Despite unfounded rumors that the producers intended to kill off
every character in the final episode, the only one to succumb is
Dr. Auschlander (Norman Lloyd), the liver cancer specialist who got
liver cancer. But he does manage to arrange the return of the
hospital to the Catholic Diocese and the return of Westphall to run
it.
   Paltrow, Tinker and Tom Fontana have a promising new series,
``Tattinger's,'' on NBC's fall schedule. But the real reason ``St.
Elsewhere'' won't be back is financial. Hour shows are not selling
well in syndication, and MTM has been producing the show at a loss.
   There could have been many more years in ``St. Elsewhere,'' but
it might not be so bad for a fine show to leave at the top of its
form.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   RATINGS EXPRESS _ That trip on the Orient Express paid off for
NBC's ``Today'' show last week. For the week ending May 13,
``Today'' had a rating of 5.1 and a 24 share. ABC's ``Good Morning
America'' had a 4.1 and 20. ``CBS This Morning'' had a 2.1 and 10.
The rating is a percentage of the 88.6 million U.S. homes with
televisions, and the share is a percentage of sets in use. GMA
spent last week in Sweden.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, May 23</NOTE>
