<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Summit-TitforTat Adv22 3rdLd-Writethru 05-21 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Tit for Tat, Adv 22, 3rd Ld-Writethru, b0741,0893</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Diplomatic Reciprocity Means Amazingly Similar Summits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 23rd graf to CORRECT that Reagan speech will be May 31,
sted June 31</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan leaves this week for a summit
in Moscow that, under a diplomatic code of reciprocity, will be
amazingly similar to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's visit in
Washington late last year.
   Begin with their cars. Gorbachev shipped his Zil limousine to
Washington instead of relying on his host for transportation, so
Reagan will follow suit, sending his armored Cadillac to Moscow.
   Gorbachev met in Washington with American writers, actors, news
executives and businessmen. Reagan will meet in Moscow with monks,
dissidents, students, writers, artists and filmmakers.
   Gorbachev gave an interview in Moscow to NBC anchorman Tom
Brokaw. Reagan sat down at the White House with Moscow television
correspondents Valentin Zorin and Boris Kalyagin for an interview
that will be broadcast May 27 in the Soviet Union.
   The two leaders gave dinners for each other in Washington;
they'll do the same in Moscow.
   White House planners even counted the number of meetings the two
leaders had in Washington and checked the time they spent together.
That provided the basis for planning the Moscow summit.
   ``I would expect that the actual formal meeting times will
closely reflect the meeting times here _ maybe a little bit more
but not an awful lot,'' said Tom Griscom, the White House
communications chief and a key architect of Reagan's trip.
   ``You can blink your eye and see a difference here or there, but
it is set up so that there is a commonality to what we're doing,''
Griscom said.
   Reagan will arrive in Moscow on May 29, a Sunday, after a
four-night stop in Helsinki, Finland. He will be the first American
president in 14 years to visit the Soviet capital.
   Officials in both countries say there is no chance the summit
will produce a new arms treaty to curb strategic nuclear weapons.
However, they are expected to sign a variety of other agreements,
dealing with issues such as ocean pollution, search and rescue
missions at sea, fishing, and cultural programs.
   Moreover, minor agreements on providing notice of missile tests
and on nuclear testing also are expected to be ready for signature.
   Reagan will see Gorbachev on Sunday in St. George's Hall in the
Kremlin Palace, the first of five official summit meetings.
   Two rounds of talks are planned at the Kremlin on Monday,
another meeting is planned on Tuesday and the fifth and final
official session is set for Wednesday, after which time has been
set aside for a signing ceremony.
   In Washington, Gorbachev held a news conference after the
summit. Reagan is slated to meet with reporters June 1, the day
before he leaves Moscow for an overnight stop in London on his way
back to Washington.
   There will be some small twists in the schedule in Moscow.
   For example, Gorbachev has invited the Reagans to the Bolshoi
Theater for a special ballet presentation Wednesday evening,
followed by an intimate dinner at a country cottage outside Moscow.
Nothing like that occurred in Washington.
   Moreover, Reagan will arrive on a Sunday and depart on a
Thursday, visiting with Gorbachev formally or informally on each of
the five days.
   On his trip to Washington last December, Gorbachev arrived on a
Monday but did not see Reagan until Tuesday. They held three days
of talks, with the Soviet leader departing on a Thursday.
   The planning for Reagan's trip actually started when the Soviets
were here last fall arranging Gorbachev's visit in December.
   ``What we tried to do was to recognize last year that whatever
we did in Washington would probably have an impact on what we were
going to do in Moscow, and that reciprocity is very important,''
Griscom said.
   ``And so, in looking at this schedule coming up, we used the
Washington summit schedule as the model to build from, particularly
for the official part of the schedule: the number of meetings,
dinners and things like that,''
   Unlike Gorbachev, who received his visitors at the Soviet
Embassy, Reagan will go out to his audiences instead of bringing
them to him.
   The major speech of his trip will be delivered on May 31 before
students at Moscow University. A question and answer session also
is planned.
   Reagan also plans to visit a monastery on the outskirts of
Moscow to watch monks restore icons, and to have lunch with
writers, artists and filmmakers at the House of Writers.
   Reagan is known as ``the great communicator,'' and Griscom said,
``Part of his communication is not just the spoken word but where
it's delivered, how it's delivered. ... I think the fact that this
president will go to Moscow University to speak to the students
will have an impact on them.
   ``I tend to think that they will appreciate that fact, that he
came to them, that he was willing to take his time out to come to
where they were, rather than to lift them up and move them where he
might be,'' Griscom said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
