<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv21-22   05-21 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 21-22,0682</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
<HEAD>Weathering The Soybean Rally Is A Risky Proposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
price trends.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The charging soybean futures market has attracted many new
investors who are betting on a continuation of this spring's dry
weather to drive prices even higher.
   But weather markets are risky, and experts warn that a sudden
shower could wash profits away.
   ``Where we try to be careful with our investors is to let them
know just that, that a weather scare can just as easily turn around
with tomorrow's forecast,'' said Penny Wydominic, a marketing vice
president at Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith Inc. in New York.
   The combination of diminishing soybean stockpiles and unusually
dry conditions during the spring planting period has pushed soybean
futures prices to four-year highs on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid mounting fears of tight supplies.
   Even though planting is only about half finished, and despite
the fact that growers in the South can safely delay planting of
fast-growing soybeans until early July, trading of soybean futures
has reached frenzied proportions at times during the past two weeks.
   The wheat, corn and oat markets have also been strong but the
gains in soybeans have been dramatic.
   Prices have soared more than 25 percent since mid-March; the
contract for May delivery of soybeans expired Thursday at $7.77 a
bushel compared to $6.11{ on April 16. Soybean trading volume has
nearly tripled.
   The open-interest figures tell another part of the story.
Soybean open interest _ the tally of outstanding orders and a rough
indicator of the number of new players in the market _ has jumped
about 30 percent since mid-March.
   ``We're getting phone calls from people who've never been
involved with this stuff before looking to get in,'' said Walter
Spilka, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New
York.
   ``I would say that what you're seeing first is people who
speculate in other commodities moving easily into the grains,''
Spilka said. ``Then you're probably also seeing people who have
been, for instance, in the stock market or the bond market, who
again are speculative by nature, making more inquiries about the
prospects for commodities and grains.''
   Ms. Wydominic agreed: ``What you're seeing is people looking for
alternative places to earn a good rate of return.
   ``People who have been involved in the stock market are looking
for another good story,'' she said. ``The grains and soybeans have
certainly presented a good story and it's a relatively easy thing
for (investors) to understand: The weather's not good, soybean
supplies are short and it provides a good weather market
opportunity.''
   The soaring prices and increasing talk of drought have long-time
traders recalling previous soybean rallies, including the one 15
years ago in which soybean futures hit an all-time high of $12.90 a
bushel on June 5, 1973.
   But experienced observers also recalled that in a weather
market, the change can come as suddenly as a summer storm.
   ``It has at times dropped faster than it went up,'' said Robert
Wisner, Iowa State University extension economist in Ames, Iowa.
``In times past, we have seen bull markets like this end with as
much as three days of limit-down moves.''
   For soybean futures, in which prices are permitted to fluctuate
no more than 30 cents a day, that would translate into a loss of 90
cents a bushel, or $4,500 per 5,000-bushel contract.
   ``The person who's trading these markets needs to be well versed
in charting techniques and indicators like the relative price
index, which shows the soybean market is overbought and due for a
correction,'' Wisner said. ``It could come down sharply in the
event of rain.''
   Wisner said investors attracted by the strong soybean market but
looking to limit their exposure should consider options, which
allow players to set their maximum risk exposure in advance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
