<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Has the Fed `Wimped Out' on Interest Rates?
^By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The continued buildup of inflation anxiety this
past week has left many bond traders wondering if the Federal
Reserve has ``wimped out'' on its interest rate policy.
   Fears have been mounting in recent weeks in financial markets
that robust economic growth could ignite high inflation. The
tension has driven down bond prices and pushed up interest rates to
their highest levels since last December.
   Many traders have been expecting the Fed to nudge interest rates
still higher, in an effort to cool inflationary pressure. But the
central bank _ which did respond earlier this month _ is apparently
reluctant to tighten credit any further for now.
   The Fed governors are ``resting on their monetary oars,'' said
William Sullivan, director of money-market research for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Some market observers, much less flatteringly, referred to the
Fed's inaction as ``wimping out.''
   ``The Fed is suffering from an extreme bout of
election-year-itis,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist and
senior vice president of the fixed-income division of Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc. He reflected the feeling in some
quarters that the Fed is buckling under pressure from the Reagan
administration not to raise interest rates, since that could hurt
the chances of Republican presidential contender George Bush.
   The perception that the central bank is staying the course and
not pushing rates higher helped bond prices recover Thursday from a
three-day selloff. Most observers believe that the Fed's
policy-making arm, its Federal Open Market Committee, decided at a
meeting last Tuesday not to tighten rates.
   Traders said bond prices also were cushioned during the week by
a ``flight to safety'' by investors fleeing the eroding stock
market into the relative security of bonds or more liquid
investments like money-market accounts. Among bonds, the trend
mainly helped short-term issues such as three-month Treasury bills,
since they offer greater liquidity to jittery investors.
   ``People are definitely leaning toward more marketable''
investments, said Jack Baker, the head of block stock trading at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The markets' inflation anxiety was aggravated last Tuesday, when
the Commerce Department reported that the nation's trade deficit
was sliced by more than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion _ the
lowest monthly shortfall since March 1985.
   The seemingly positive trade report was taken as bad news by the
stock and bond markets. Traders saw the big boom in exports in
March as another sign the economy could be overheating dangerously.
   Friday's report that consumer prices rose a modest 0.4 percent
in April, a level that had been widely anticipated, failed to
dispel the markets' inflation worries. Investors remained fearful
that the economy is growing so quickly that inflation may
eventually accelerate.
   The yield on the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped
to 9.22 percent Tuesday, the day of the trade report, from 9.11
percent late Monday. The long bond traded Friday at around 9.33
percent, its highest level since it hit 9.40 percent last Dec. 14.
   The rate on three-month Treasury bills, which apparently
benefited strongly from the ``flight to safety'' out of Wall
Street, fell to 6.14 percent late Thursday from 6.30 percent on
Tuesday. But it moved up on Friday to 6.42 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
