<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv21-22   05-21 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 21-22,0726</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
<HEAD>Program Traders Get Important Boost From Fed Chief, Market's
Behavior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Program trading, a prime target of Wall Street's
post-crash scapegoat searchers, received two key defenses this past
week, one from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and the
other from the market's own behavior.
   Greenspan's endorsement of the computerized trading strategy
convinced one major brokerage to reconsider the voluntary ban it
had placed on the most controversial form of program trading, index
arbitrage.
   Bear Stearns & Co. suspended index arbitrage earlier this month,
partly in response to a growing public outcry that the practice had
injected volatility into the market, devastating investor
confidence and scaring away business.
   Salomon Brothers Inc., Morgan Stanley & Co., PaineWebber Inc.
and Kidder Peabody & Co. also suspended index arbitrage for their
own accounts, although they have said they would continue to use it
for clients if asked.
   In index arbitrage, brokerages use computers to instantly sell
big baskets of stocks in New York while simultaneously buying the
equivalent stock-index futures in Chicago, or vice versa, to profit
from price discrepancies.
   This strategy, devised about five years ago, has been credited
with helping sustain the 1982-87 bull market that preceded the
October collapse. But some studies have suggested that index
arbitrage also played a role in the wild price swings that
accompanied the crash and the market's spasms since then.
   Testifying before Congress, Greenspan argued that index
arbitrage isn't the destructive influence critics claim, but
instead helps stabilize the market by keeping the prices of index
futures and stocks from varying too widely.
   ``It is a mistake to single out one segment of the broad
marketplace as the culprit for large and rapid price movements,''
said Greenspan, who is a member of a special presidential panel
that has studied the causes of the crash. The panel has recommended
no major changes in any professional trading techniques.
   Some prominent critics of index arbitrage program trading were
stunned by Greenspan's statement.
   ``As much as I admire and respect Mr. Greenspan, I almost fell
off my chair when I read that,'' said Robert Kirby, head of Capital
Guardian Trust Co. in Los Angeles, which had threatened to boycott
brokerages that use index arbitrage for their own accounts.
   ``I just think computer-driven program trading is a disruptive
influence,'' Kirby said. ``He could be right and I could be wrong,
but I sure don't agree with him.''
   Perhaps a more significant defense of index arbitrage than
Greenspan's remarks was the market's action itself this past week.
Although the biggest users of the technique were absent, it did
little to calm investor anxiety or bring back the disenchanted.
   On the contrary, many traders said another excuse was found to
dump stocks: fear of inflation and higher interest rates, despite
the best monthly trade news in three years. The Dow Jones
industrial average hit its lowest point in more than three months
last Wednesday, closing at 1,951.09.
   The key index of 30 industrial stocks finished the week barely
above that level at 1,952.59, bringing its loss for the week to
37.95.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index fell 2 to 143.30;
the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
6.45 to 366.03; and the American Stock Exchange market value index
fell 6.10 to 291.84.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 156.80 million shares a day vs.
153.07 million the week before.
   Despite the thin volume and falling prices, some trading
strategists said they believed the absence of index arbitrage as a
force in the market had caused a noticeable and welcome change.
   For one thing, they said fewer speculators were taking positions
in advance of computerized buy or sell programs, and investors were
basing their decisions more on the long-term merits of stocks
rather than quick-profit opportunities.
   ``The market isn't as jerky,'' said James Cramer, an outspoken
critic of index arbitrage and president of a small investment firm
that bears his name. ``Buyers come in because stocks are
attractive. We're not seeing the short-term hot money and fast
traders.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
