<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv21-22-1stAdd   05-21 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 21-22-1st Add,0250</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... in advance.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures rose sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $3.46{ a bushel, up
from $3.15 a week earlier; July corn jumped to $2.21\ a bushel from
$2.06; July oats advanced to $1.73} a bushel from $1.62\; and July
soybeans soared to $7.78} a bushel from $7.27}.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle for delivery in June fell to 73.37 cents a pound
from 73.80 cents; May feeder cattle advanced to 80.90 cents a pound
from 80.77 cents; June hogs rose to 53.87 cents a pound from 53.55
cents; and May frozen pork bellies retreated to 53.25 cents a pound
from 54.40 cents.
   Precious metals moved higher on the Commodity Exchange in New
York. Gold for delivery in June settled at $458.70 a troy ounce,
compared with $453.70; May silver rose to $6.690 a troy ounce from
$6.632.
   Energy futures advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for delivery in July settled
at $17.70 a barrel compared with $17.66; June heating oil rose to
47.71 cents a gallon from 47.47 cents; and June unleaded gasoline
advanced to 52.36 cents a gallon from 52.34 cents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 21-22</NOTE>
