<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Board Rejects Bank of NY's Sweetened Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. has amended it ``poison pill''
takeover defense to prevent hostile suitor Bank of New York Co.
from carrying out its threat to buy up Irving stock and operate the
bank as a subsidiary.
   Irving announced Friday that in a special meeting its board of
directors rejected Bank of New York's sweetened takeover bid. The
board refused to rescind its poison pill, a condition under which
Bank of New York had proposed to slightly raise the stock portion
of its $1.1 billion hostile offer.
   Instead, Irving said, the directors amended the defensive
provision so that it would be activated should someone acquire at
least 20 percent of Irving shares on the open market. The poison
pill previously would have gone into effect in the event of a
takeover not supported by management.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said: ``The action taken
by Irving's board ... is clearly invalid.''
   The company said it asked the New York State Supreme Court on
Friday to act quickly to invalidate Irving's poison pill. A hearing
was set for May 24.
   Bank of New York had threatened to proceed with its orignal
tender offer by Tuesday and run Irving separately, provided at
least two-thirds of Irving's 18.5 million outstanding shares were
tendered.
   Irving's management, meanwhile, supports a friendly merger with
Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, a major state-run Italian
institution.
   ``A lot depends now on what the court rules,'' said Michael
Alpert, a banking analyst with Bear Stearns. ``If it (the poison
pill) is ruled valid it will make it more difficult for the Bank of
New York to acquire Irving unless there's a negotiated settlement.''
   Poison pill defenses are designed to discourage takeover bids by
greatly increasing the cost of an acquisition. In Irving's case,
existing shareholders would be permitted to buy stock in an
acquiring company at about half price.
   Brady said that as of Monday, Bank of New York held about 50
percent of Irving's stock, including shares it owned or had been
tendered to it.
   Also Friday, Irving filed suit in U.S. District Court against
the Bank of New York alleging its unwanted suitor was in violation
of federal securities laws by failing to notify shareholders of the
financial ramfications of its amended offer. It said Bank of New
York also failed to disclose the effects of its proposal to operate
Irving as a subsidiary.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in Irving and
had received conditional regulatory approval for an Irving merger,
had offered to raise the stock portion of its bid to 1.675 Bank of
New York shares from 1.575 shares, adding $3.20 per share to the
deal and pushing its value to around $1.2 billion. The $15 cash
portion would remain the same.
   The proposal came after Irving announced a preliminary proxy
count showed its shareholders re-elected its board of directors,
rejecting a rival slate put forward by Bank of New York. The
hostile suitor has since questioned the results and says it may
file a formal challenge.
   Banca Commerciale, Italy's second largest bank, is offering $75
a share for 9.5 million Irving shares, or about 51 percent of the
stock outstanding, for a total of about $707 million. The bid is
part of a complex restructuring plan that would include asset
sales, cost-cutting measures and a $10-a-share special cash
dividend.
   Irving said in a statement Friday that it was in ``active
discussions with BCI concerning improvement in its offer.''
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving
closed down 37.5 cents Friday to $60.12{ while Bank of New York
rose 25 cents to $30.12{.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
