<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abundant crude oil supplies have helped drag
futures prices lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Contracts for June delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, closed at $17.17 per barrel, down 28 cents
from Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among June contracts for refined products traded on the
exchange, wholesale prices for heating oil rose 0.08 cent to 47.71
cents a gallon, while wholesale unleaded gasoline gained 0.10 cent
to 52.36 cents a gallon.
   ``What happened today is telling the story that short-term
supplies of crude are more than ample. There's plenty, everywhere
you look,'' said Donald Morton, vice president for energy futures
in the Boston office of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Another factor putting selling pressure on the June contract was
the fact that it expired Friday.
   On Monday, the July contract will become the new ``near month''
contract on the exchange.
</TEXT>
